{"title_page": "\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville", "text_new": "{{short description|French printer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name = \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville\n| honorific_suffix =\n| image = Edouard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville.jpg\n| caption = \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1817|04|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], [[Kingdom of France]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1879|04|26|1817|04|25|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic]]\n| death_cause =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments =\n| residence = Paris, France\n| nationality = French\n| other_names =\n| education =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = {{Plainlist|\n* Printer\n* Bookseller\n}}\n| years_active =\n| employer =\n| organization =\n| agent =\n| known_for = Inventing the earliest known sound recording device\n| notable_works =\n| style =\n| influences =\n| influenced =\n| home_town =\n| television =\n| religion =\n| spouse =\n| partner =\n| children =\n| parents =\n| relatives =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville''' (25 April 1817 \u2013 26 April 1879) was a French printer, bookseller, and inventor.\n\nHe invented the earliest known sound recording device, the [[phonautograph]], which was patented in France on 25 March 1857.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\">{{cite news|first=Steven E. | last=Schoenherr| url=http://history.sandiego.edu/gen/recording/scott.html |title=Leon Scott and the Phonautograph |work=Recording Technology History |publisher=University of San Diego |accessdate=27 March 2008 |quote=Edouard-Leon Scott de Martinville was born in France in 1817.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Oldest recorded voices sing again. |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/7318180.stm |quote=An \"ethereal\" 10 second clip of a woman singing a French folk song has been played for the first time in 150 years. The recording of \"Au Clair de la Lune\", recorded in 1860, is thought to be the oldest known recorded human voice.  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=29 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sound Recording Predates Edison Phonograph |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=89148959 |quote=He invented a device called the phonautograph, and, on 9 April 1860, recorded someone singing the words, 'Au clair de la lune, Pierrot repondit {{sic}}.' But he never had any intention of playing it back. He just wanted to study the pattern the sound waves made on a sheet of paper blackened by the smoke of an oil lamp. |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=5 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Early years ==\nAs a printer by trade, he was able to read accounts of the latest scientific discoveries and became an inventor. Scott de Martinville was interested in recording the sound of human speech in a way similar to that achieved by the then-new technology of photography for light and image. He hoped for a form of [[stenography]] that could record the whole of a conversation without any omissions. His earliest interest was in an improved form of stenography, and he was the author of several papers on [[shorthand]] and a history of the subject (1849).<ref name=\"Hankins\" />\n\n== Phonautograph ==\n[[File:Phonautograph-cent2.png|thumb|right|200px|Dictionary illustration of a phonautograph. The barrel is made of [[Plaster of Paris]].]]\nFrom 1853 he became fascinated in a mechanical means of transcribing vocal sounds. While proofreading some engravings for a physics textbook, he came across drawings of auditory anatomy. He sought to mimic the working in a mechanical device, substituting an elastic membrane for the [[Eardrum|tympanum]], a series of levers for the [[ossicle]], which moved a stylus he proposed would press on a paper, wood, or glass surface covered in [[lampblack]]. On 26 January 1857, he delivered his design in a sealed envelope to the French Academy.<ref name=\"Hankins\">{{cite book |last=Hankins |first=Thomas L. |author2=Robert J. Silverman  |title=Instruments and the Imagination  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9e_7E22caAC&pg=PA263 |year=1995 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0-691-00549-4  |pages=133 to 135 |chapterurl= }}</ref> On 25 March 1857, he received French patent #17,897/31,470 for the phonautograph.<ref name=\"Phonatographic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.firstsounds.org/public/Phonautographic-Manuscripts.pdf | title=The Phonautographic Manuscripts of \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville | format=PDF | translator-first=Patrick | translator-last=Feaster | first=\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott | last=de Martinville}}</ref>{{rp|13, footnote 85}}\n\nTo collect sound, the [[phonautograph]] used a horn attached to a diaphragm which vibrated a stiff [[bristle]] which inscribed an image on a [[lampblack]]-coated, hand-cranked cylinder.  Scott built several devices with the help of acoustic instrument maker [[Rudolph Koenig]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/edis/learn/historyculture/origins-of-sound-recording-edouard-leon-scott-de-martinville.htm|title=Origins of Sound Recording: The Inventors|date=2017|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref> Unlike [[Thomas Edison]]'s later invention of 1877, the [[phonograph]], the phonautograph created only visual images of the sound and did not have the ability to play back its recordings. Scott de Martinville's intention was for the device's waves to be read by humans as one would read text, which proved unfeasible.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://time.com/5084599/first-recorded-sound/ | title=What Was the First Sound Ever Recorded by a Machine? | accessdate=31 August 2019 | publisher=TIME}}</ref>\n\nScott de Martinville managed to sell several phonautographs to scientific laboratories for use in the investigation of sound. It proved useful in the study of vowel sounds and was used by [[Franciscus Donders]], [[Heinrich Schneebeli]] and [[Rene Marage]]. It also initiated further research into tools able to image sound, such as Koenig's [[Koenig's manometric flame apparatus|manometric flame]].<ref name=\"Hankins\" /> He was not, however, able to profit from his invention, and spent the remainder of his life as a bookseller dealing in prints and photographs, at 9 Rue Vivienne in Paris.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/>\n\nScott de Martinville also became interested in the relationship between linguistics, people's names and their character, and published a paper on the subject (1857).<ref name=\"Hankins\" />\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Rediscovery of the ''Au clair de la lune''<!--NOTE: excepting proper names, in French only the first word in a title is capitalized.--> recording ==\n{{Listen|filename=Au Clair de la Lune (1860).ogg|title=Au clair de la lune|description= Earliest recognizable recording of human voice, from 9 April 1860<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstsounds.org/sounds/scott.php|title=FirstSounds.ORG}}</ref>|filename2=1860-Scott-Au-Clair-de-la-Lune-05-09.ogg|title2=Au clair de la lune|description2= The recording slowed down to match what is now believed to be the correct speed; the result reveals a man's voice, presumably Scott's.<ref>http://www.firstsounds.org/sounds/1860-Scott-Au-Clair-de-la-Lune-05-09.ogg</ref>}}\nIn 2008, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported the playback of a phonautogram recorded on 9 April 1860.<ref name=\"iht\">{{cite news |first= Jody|last= Rosen|title=Researchers Play Tune Recorded Before Edison. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/27/arts/27soun.html?hp |quote=The audio excavation could give a new primacy to the phonautograph, once considered a curio, and its inventor, \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville, a Parisian typesetter and tinkerer who went to his grave convinced that credit for his breakthroughs had been improperly bestowed on Edison. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= 27 March 2008|accessdate=27 March 2008 }}</ref> The recording was converted from \"squiggles on paper\" to a playable digital audio file with the [[IRENE (technology)|IRENE]] technology, developed by scientists at the [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] in [[Berkeley, California]].<ref name=\"iht\" /> The phonautogram was one of several deposited by L\u00e9on Scott in two archives in Paris and only recently brought to light.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe recording, part of the French folk song ''[[Au clair de la lune]]'',<ref name=PierrotLunaire>The melody is also that of the ancient \"Response Before the Gospel\" used during the [[Lent]]en season by the [[Catholic Church]]; it is first sung by a single congregant, then repeated, melody and lyric, by everyone attending the day\u2019s Mass. In English translation, its words are \"[By] Your Cross and Ressurrection,/ You Have Set Us Free\".</ref> was initially played at a speed that produced what seemed to be a 10-second recording of the voice of a woman or child singing at an ordinary musical tempo. The researchers leading the project later found that a misunderstanding about an included reference frequency had resulted in a doubling of the correct playback speed, and that it was actually a 20-second recording of a man, probably Scott himself, singing the song very slowly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/articles/science/2009/06/01/earliest-known-sound-recordings-revealed.html|title=Earliest Known Sound Recordings Revealed|work=US News & World Report}}</ref> It is now the earliest known recording of singing in existence, predating, by 28 years, several 1888 [[Thomas Edison|Edison]] wax cylinder phonograph recordings of a massed chorus performing Handel's oratorio ''[[Israel in Egypt]]''.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130121191004/http://www.webrarian.co.uk/crystalpalace/crystal14.html The 1888 Crystal Palace recordings]</ref>\n\nA phonautogram by Scott containing the opening lines of [[Torquato Tasso]]'s pastoral drama ''[[Aminta]]'', in Italian, has also been found. Recorded around 1860, probably after the recording of ''Au clair de la lune'', this phonautogram is now the earliest known recording of intelligible human speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/articles/science/2009/06/01/earliest-known-sound-recordings-revealed.html|title=Earliest Known Sound Recordings Revealed Researchers unveil imprints made 20 years before Edison invented phonograph|last=Cowen|first=Ron |date=1 June 2009|work=Science News|publisher=U.S.News & World Report|accessdate=26 June 2009}}</ref> Recordings of Scott's voice made in 1857 have also survived, but they are only unintelligible snippets.<ref name=\"Leon\">{{cite web |last1=Orbin |first1=Joe |title=Leon Scott's COMPLETE DISCOGRAPHY 1853 - 1860 |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=uRbIJc05QTA&t=65s |website=YouTube |publisher=FirstSounds.org |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref> However, since then one of these recordings (1857 cornet scale recording) has been restored, and earlier records from 1853 experiments have been found and conserved.<ref name=\"Leon\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Orbin |first1=Joe |title=Restored ! 1857 Cornet Scale Recording |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mMdL7ZI5TdM |website=YouTube |publisher=FirstSounds.org |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt has been claimed that in 1863 Scott's phonautograph was used to make a recording of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s voice at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web| title= In Love With Technology, as Long as It's Dusty | url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9804EFDE1630F936A15750C0A96F958260 | first= Katie | last=Hafner| date=25 March 1999 |work=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=23 February 2013 | quote= In 1863, nearly 15 years before Thomas Alva Edison created the first phonograph, an inventor named Leon Scott is said to have visited the White House. If historical anecdotes are accurate, he made a tracing of President Lincoln's voice with his newly invented 'phonautograph,' a machine that scratched sound patterns onto a soot-blackened sheet of paper wrapped around a drum.}}</ref> A phonautogram of Lincoln's voice was supposedly among the artifacts kept by [[Thomas Edison]]. According to FirstSounds.org, these stories are variations of a myth that seems to have first appeared in print in a 1969 book about antique collecting, in which it is explicitly categorized as a legend and dismissed as based on \"garbled accounts\".<ref name=Lost>{{cite web| url= http://www.firstsounds.org/features/lincoln.php |title= The 'Lost' Tracing of Lincoln's Voice|publisher = FirstSounds.org| accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> There is no solid evidence that such a recording ever existed.<ref name=Lost /> The most nearly similar artifact known to have been kept by Edison was a recording of the voice of President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], captured as a groove indented into a sheet of tinfoil when Edison demonstrated his newly-invented phonograph to Hayes in 1878. Scott did not visit the US in the 1860s and therefore could not have recorded Lincoln himself, as one version of the legend claims he did.<ref name=Lost />\n\nScott's phonautograms were selected by the [[Library of Congress]] as a 2010 addition to the [[National Recording Registry]], which selects recordings annually that are \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/record/nrpb/registry/nrpb-2010reg.html | title=The National Recording Registry 2010 | accessdate=10 April 2011 | publisher=Library of Congress}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dLUIAAAAQAAJ {{lang|fr|Jugement d'un ouvrier sur les romans et les feuilletons \u00e0 l'occasion de Ferrand et Mariette}}]'' (1847)\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/histoiredelast00scot {{lang|fr|Histoire de la st\u00e9nographie depuis les temps anciens jusqu'\u00e0 nos jours}}]'' (1849)\n* ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=p7hrAAAAMAAJ {{lang|fr|Les Noms de bapt\u00eame et les pr\u00e9noms}}]'' (1857)\n* ''[http://www.phonozoic.net/fs/First-Sounds-Working-Paper-03a.pdf {{lang|fr|Fixation graphique de la voix}}]'' (1857)\n* ''[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6354206q.texteImage {{lang|fr|Notice sur la vie et les travaux de M. Adolphe-No\u00ebl Desvergers}}]''\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/EssaiDeClassificationMethodiqueEtS {{lang|fr|Essai de classification m\u00e9thodique et synoptique des romans de chevalerie in\u00e9dits et publi\u00e9s. Premier appendice au catalogue raisonn\u00e9 des livres de la biblioth\u00e8que de M. Ambroise Firmin-Didot}}]'' (1870)\n* ''[http://www.firstsounds.org/public/First-Sounds-Working-Paper-05.pdf {{lang|fr|Le Probl\u00e8me de la parole s'\u00e9crivant elle-m\u00eame. La France, l'Am\u00e9rique}}]'' (1878)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Helmholtz, Hermann. ''On the Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music''. Translated by Alexander J. Ellis. London: Longmans, Green, 1875, p.&nbsp;20.\n* ''History of the Phonautograph'' Marco, Guy A., editor. ''Encyclopedia of Recorded Sound in the United States''. New York: Garland, 1993, p.&nbsp;615.\n* Winston, Brian. ''Media Technology and Society: a History from the Telegraph to the Internet''. New York : Routledge, 1998.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.firstsounds.org/ FirstSounds.org], including [http://www.firstsounds.org/public/Phonautographic-Manuscripts.pdf ''The Phonautographic Manuscripts of \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Leon}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1879 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century French businesspeople]]\n[[Category:French inventors]]\n[[Category:French people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:French printers]]\n[[Category:19th-century inventors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French printer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = Edouard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville.jpg\n| caption = \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1817|04|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Paris]], [[Kingdom of France]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1879|04|26|1817|04|25|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic]]\n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments = \n| residence = Paris, France\n| nationality = French\n| other_names = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = {{Plainlist|\n* Printer\n* Bookseller\n}}\n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = Inventing the earliest known sound recording device\n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| home_town = \n| television = \n| religion = \n| spouse = \n| partner = \n| children = \n| parents = \n| relatives = \n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville''' (25 April 1817 \u2013 26 April 1879) was a French printer, bookseller, and inventor.\n\nHe invented the earliest known sound recording device, the [[phonautograph]], which was patented in France on 25 March 1857.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\">{{cite news|first=Steven E. | last=Schoenherr| url=http://history.sandiego.edu/gen/recording/scott.html |title=Leon Scott and the Phonautograph |work=Recording Technology History |publisher=University of San Diego |accessdate=27 March 2008 |quote=Edouard-Leon Scott de Martinville was born in France in 1817.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Oldest recorded voices sing again. |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/7318180.stm |quote=An \"ethereal\" 10 second clip of a woman singing a French folk song has been played for the first time in 150 years. The recording of \"Au Clair de la Lune\", recorded in 1860, is thought to be the oldest known recorded human voice.  |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=29 March 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sound Recording Predates Edison Phonograph |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=89148959 |quote=He invented a device called the phonautograph, and, on 9 April 1860, recorded someone singing the words, 'Au clair de la lune, Pierrot repondit {{sic}}.' But he never had any intention of playing it back. He just wanted to study the pattern the sound waves made on a sheet of paper blackened by the smoke of an oil lamp. |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |accessdate=5 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Early years ==\nAs a printer by trade, he was able to read accounts of the latest scientific discoveries and became an inventor. Scott de Martinville was interested in recording the sound of human speech in a way similar to that achieved by the then-new technology of photography for light and image. He hoped for a form of [[stenography]] that could record the whole of a conversation without any omissions. His earliest interest was in an improved form of stenography, and he was the author of several papers on [[shorthand]] and a history of the subject (1849).<ref name=\"Hankins\" />\n\n== Phonautograph ==\n[[File:Phonautograph-cent2.png|thumb|right|200px|Dictionary illustration of a phonautograph. The barrel is made of [[Plaster of Paris]].]]\nFrom 1853 he became fascinated in a mechanical means of transcribing vocal sounds. While proofreading some engravings for a physics textbook, he came across drawings of auditory anatomy. He sought to mimic the working in a mechanical device, substituting an elastic membrane for the [[Eardrum|tympanum]], a series of levers for the [[ossicle]], which moved a stylus he proposed would press on a paper, wood, or glass surface covered in [[lampblack]]. On 26 January 1857, he delivered his design in a sealed envelope to the French Academy.<ref name=\"Hankins\">{{cite book |last=Hankins |first=Thomas L. |author2=Robert J. Silverman  |title=Instruments and the Imagination  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O9e_7E22caAC&pg=PA263 |year=1995 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn=0-691-00549-4  |pages=133 to 135 |chapterurl= }}</ref> On 25 March 1857, he received French patent #17,897/31,470 for the phonautograph.<ref name=\"Phonatographic\">{{cite web | url=http://www.firstsounds.org/public/Phonautographic-Manuscripts.pdf | title=The Phonautographic Manuscripts of \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville | format=PDF | translator-first=Patrick | translator-last=Feaster | first=\u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott | last=de Martinville}}</ref>{{rp|13, footnote 85}}\n\nTo collect sound, the [[phonautograph]] used a horn attached to a diaphragm which vibrated a stiff [[bristle]] which inscribed an image on a [[lampblack]]-coated, hand-cranked cylinder.  Scott built several devices with the help of acoustic instrument maker [[Rudolph Koenig]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/edis/learn/historyculture/origins-of-sound-recording-edouard-leon-scott-de-martinville.htm|title=Origins of Sound Recording: The Inventors|date=2017|website=www.nps.gov}}</ref> Unlike [[Thomas Edison]]'s later invention of 1877, the [[phonograph]], the phonautograph created only visual images of the sound and did not have the ability to play back its recordings. Scott de Martinville's intention was for the device's waves to be read by humans as one would read text, which proved unfeasible.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://time.com/5084599/first-recorded-sound/ | title=What Was the First Sound Ever Recorded by a Machine? | accessdate=31 August 2019 | publisher=TIME}}</ref>\n\nScott de Martinville managed to sell several phonautographs to scientific laboratories for use in the investigation of sound. It proved useful in the study of vowel sounds and was used by [[Franciscus Donders]], [[Heinrich Schneebeli]] and [[Rene Marage]]. It also initiated further research into tools able to image sound, such as Koenig's [[Koenig's manometric flame apparatus|manometric flame]].<ref name=\"Hankins\" /> He was not, however, able to profit from his invention, and spent the remainder of his life as a bookseller dealing in prints and photographs, at 9 Rue Vivienne in Paris.<ref name=\"Schoenherr\"/>\n\nScott de Martinville also became interested in the relationship between linguistics, people's names and their character, and published a paper on the subject (1857).<ref name=\"Hankins\" />\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Rediscovery of the ''Au clair de la lune''<!--NOTE: excepting proper names, in French only the first word in a title is capitalized.--> recording ==\n{{Listen|filename=Au Clair de la Lune (1860).ogg|title=Au clair de la lune|description= Earliest recognizable recording of human voice, from 9 April 1860<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstsounds.org/sounds/scott.php|title=FirstSounds.ORG}}</ref>|filename2=1860-Scott-Au-Clair-de-la-Lune-05-09.ogg|title2=Au clair de la lune|description2= The recording slowed down to match what is now believed to be the correct speed; the result reveals a man's voice, presumably Scott's.<ref>http://www.firstsounds.org/sounds/1860-Scott-Au-Clair-de-la-Lune-05-09.ogg</ref>}}\nIn 2008, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported the playback of a phonautogram recorded on 9 April 1860.<ref name=\"iht\">{{cite news |first= Jody|last= Rosen|title=Researchers Play Tune Recorded Before Edison. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/03/27/arts/27soun.html?hp |quote=The audio excavation could give a new primacy to the phonautograph, once considered a curio, and its inventor, \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville, a Parisian typesetter and tinkerer who went to his grave convinced that credit for his breakthroughs had been improperly bestowed on Edison. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date= 27 March 2008|accessdate=27 March 2008 }}</ref> The recording was converted from \"squiggles on paper\" to a playable digital audio file with the [[IRENE (technology)|IRENE]] technology, developed by scientists at the [[Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory]] in [[Berkeley, California]].<ref name=\"iht\" /> The phonautogram was one of several deposited by L\u00e9on Scott in two archives in Paris and only recently brought to light.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}\n\nThe recording, part of the French folk song ''[[Au clair de la lune]]'',<ref name=PierrotLunaire>The melody is also that of the ancient \"Response Before the Gospel\" used during the [[Lent]]en season by the [[Catholic Church]]; it is first sung by a single congregant, then repeated, melody and lyric, by everyone attending the day\u2019s Mass. In English translation, its words are \"[By] Your Cross and Ressurrection,/ You Have Set Us Free\".</ref> was initially played at a speed that produced what seemed to be a 10-second recording of the voice of a woman or child singing at an ordinary musical tempo. The researchers leading the project later found that a misunderstanding about an included reference frequency had resulted in a doubling of the correct playback speed, and that it was actually a 20-second recording of a man, probably Scott himself, singing the song very slowly.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/articles/science/2009/06/01/earliest-known-sound-recordings-revealed.html|title=Earliest Known Sound Recordings Revealed|work=US News & World Report}}</ref> It is now the earliest known recording of singing in existence, predating, by 28 years, several 1888 [[Thomas Edison|Edison]] wax cylinder phonograph recordings of a massed chorus performing Handel's oratorio ''[[Israel in Egypt]]''.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130121191004/http://www.webrarian.co.uk/crystalpalace/crystal14.html The 1888 Crystal Palace recordings]</ref>\n\nA phonautogram by Scott containing the opening lines of [[Torquato Tasso]]'s pastoral drama ''[[Aminta]]'', in Italian, has also been found. Recorded around 1860, probably after the recording of ''Au clair de la lune'', this phonautogram is now the earliest known recording of intelligible human speech.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/articles/science/2009/06/01/earliest-known-sound-recordings-revealed.html|title=Earliest Known Sound Recordings Revealed Researchers unveil imprints made 20 years before Edison invented phonograph|last=Cowen|first=Ron |date=1 June 2009|work=Science News|publisher=U.S.News & World Report|accessdate=26 June 2009}}</ref> Recordings of Scott's voice made in 1857 have also survived, but they are only unintelligible snippets.<ref name=\"Leon\">{{cite web |last1=Orbin |first1=Joe |title=Leon Scott's COMPLETE DISCOGRAPHY 1853 - 1860 |url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=uRbIJc05QTA&t=65s |website=YouTube |publisher=FirstSounds.org |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref> However, since then one of these recordings (1857 cornet scale recording) has been restored, and earlier records from 1853 experiments have been found and conserved.<ref name=\"Leon\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Orbin |first1=Joe |title=Restored ! 1857 Cornet Scale Recording |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mMdL7ZI5TdM |website=YouTube |publisher=FirstSounds.org |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIt has been claimed that in 1863 Scott's phonautograph was used to make a recording of [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s voice at the [[White House]].<ref>{{cite web| title= In Love With Technology, as Long as It's Dusty | url= https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9804EFDE1630F936A15750C0A96F958260 | first= Katie | last=Hafner| date=25 March 1999 |work=[[The New York Times]]| accessdate=23 February 2013 | quote= In 1863, nearly 15 years before Thomas Alva Edison created the first phonograph, an inventor named Leon Scott is said to have visited the White House. If historical anecdotes are accurate, he made a tracing of President Lincoln's voice with his newly invented 'phonautograph,' a machine that scratched sound patterns onto a soot-blackened sheet of paper wrapped around a drum.}}</ref> A phonautogram of Lincoln's voice was supposedly among the artifacts kept by [[Thomas Edison]]. According to FirstSounds.org, these stories are variations of a myth that seems to have first appeared in print in a 1969 book about antique collecting, in which it is explicitly categorized as a legend and dismissed as based on \"garbled accounts\".<ref name=Lost>{{cite web| url= http://www.firstsounds.org/features/lincoln.php |title= The 'Lost' Tracing of Lincoln's Voice|publisher = FirstSounds.org| accessdate=23 February 2013}}</ref> There is no solid evidence that such a recording ever existed.<ref name=Lost /> The most nearly similar artifact known to have been kept by Edison was a recording of the voice of President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]], captured as a groove indented into a sheet of tinfoil when Edison demonstrated his newly-invented phonograph to Hayes in 1878. Scott did not visit the US in the 1860s and therefore could not have recorded Lincoln himself, as one version of the legend claims he did.<ref name=Lost />\n\nScott's phonautograms were selected by the [[Library of Congress]] as a 2010 addition to the [[National Recording Registry]], which selects recordings annually that are \"culturally, historically, or aesthetically significant\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/record/nrpb/registry/nrpb-2010reg.html | title=The National Recording Registry 2010 | accessdate=10 April 2011 | publisher=Library of Congress}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n*''[https://books.google.com/books?id=dLUIAAAAQAAJ {{lang|fr|Jugement d'un ouvrier sur les romans et les feuilletons \u00e0 l'occasion de Ferrand et Mariette}}]'' (1847)\n*''[https://archive.org/details/histoiredelast00scot {{lang|fr|Histoire de la st\u00e9nographie depuis les temps anciens jusqu'\u00e0 nos jours}}]'' (1849)\n*''[https://books.google.com/books?id=p7hrAAAAMAAJ {{lang|fr|Les Noms de bapt\u00eame et les pr\u00e9noms}}]'' (1857)\n*''[http://www.phonozoic.net/fs/First-Sounds-Working-Paper-03a.pdf {{lang|fr|Fixation graphique de la voix}}]'' (1857)\n*''[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6354206q.texteImage {{lang|fr|Notice sur la vie et les travaux de M. Adolphe-No\u00ebl Desvergers}}]''\n*''[https://archive.org/details/EssaiDeClassificationMethodiqueEtS {{lang|fr|Essai de classification m\u00e9thodique et synoptique des romans de chevalerie in\u00e9dits et publi\u00e9s. Premier appendice au catalogue raisonn\u00e9 des livres de la biblioth\u00e8que de M. Ambroise Firmin-Didot}}]'' (1870)\n*''[http://www.firstsounds.org/public/First-Sounds-Working-Paper-05.pdf {{lang|fr|Le Probl\u00e8me de la parole s'\u00e9crivant elle-m\u00eame. La France, l'Am\u00e9rique}}]'' (1878)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Helmholtz, Hermann. ''On the Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music''. Translated by Alexander J. Ellis. London: Longmans, Green, 1875, p.&nbsp;20.\n*''History of the Phonautograph'' Marco, Guy A., editor. ''Encyclopedia of Recorded Sound in the United States''. New York: Garland, 1993, p.&nbsp;615.\n*Winston, Brian. ''Media Technology and Society: a History from the Telegraph to the Internet''. New York : Routledge, 1998.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.firstsounds.org/ FirstSounds.org], including [http://www.firstsounds.org/public/Phonautographic-Manuscripts.pdf ''The Phonautographic Manuscripts of \u00c9douard-L\u00e9on Scott de Martinville'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scott, Leon}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1879 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century French businesspeople]]\n[[Category:French inventors]]\n[[Category:French people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:French printers]]\n[[Category:19th-century inventors]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89douard-L%C3%A9on_Scott_de_Martinville"}
{"title_page": "Christian Rex van Minnen", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=March 2020}}\n{{Like resume|date=March 2019}}\n}}\n\n{{Short description|American contemporary artist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Christian Rex van Minnen\n| image = Rex van Minnen.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1980}}<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n| birth_place = Providence, RI, U.S.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n| field = [[Printmaking]], painting, ceramics\n| training = \n| movement = \n| works =\n| education        = BA and Master\u2019s of Nonprofit Management at Regis University, Denver, 2002<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/><ref name=\"beinart\"/>\n| alma_mater       = [[Regis University]]\n| known_for        = Dutch Golden Age meets Pop Surrealism\n| notable_works    = \n| spouse           = Ashley Muse<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n| partner          = \n| awards           = {{awd|Artist-in-Residence at Anderson Ranch Arts Center|2017}}<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n| website          = {{URL|christianrexvanminnen.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Christian Rex van Minnen''' is an American [[Contemporary Artist|contemporary artis]]<nowiki/>t. He was born in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence, R]]I, in 1980 and received his BA from [[Regis University|Regis University,]] [[Denver]], in 2002.\n\n==Biography==\n\nChristian Rex van Minnen was born in 1980 in [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]] and grew up in [[Colorado]].<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/> His father is a psychotherapist in [[Basalt, Colorado]] and was born in [[South Africa]] but did not have much direct contact.<ref name=\"Interview\">{{cite journal |last1=Molesky |first1=David |title=Christian Rex van Minnen |journal=Juxtapoz |date=April 2014 |volume=159 |pages=94\u2013103}}</ref>\n\nHis uncles were fishermen and had a fish market in [[Charlestown, Rhode Island|Charlestown]], Rhode Island called Rathbones.<ref name=\"Doze\">{{cite web |last1=Espiritu |first1=v |title=This is Christian Rex van Minnen |url=http://www.dozecollective.com/this-is-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |website=Doze Collective |access-date=March 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180608142559/http://www.dozecollective.com/this-is-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |archive-date=June 8, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nHe always doodled in high school and was introduced to painting before going to university.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> He is not formally trained in art but in 2002 he graduated with a BA from [[Regis University]].<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\nHe chose painting as a prime profession in 2005\u20132006.<ref name=\"Bob\"/>  Early in his career he worked on a smaller scale of 18x24 inches. These were more personal pieces.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\nLater, he moved into a larger scale and he had to change his technique and remove some of the complexity and try not to not to fill every square inch on the canvas.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\nIn 2006 he was a landscaper and completed a Masters in [[Nonprofit Management|non-profit management]] while also working at a gallery. It was at time that he became frustrated and worked to use the internet to get around the traditional art scene.<ref name=\"beinart\"/>\n\nHe has lived in [[Denver]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Seattle]], and [[Carbondale, Colorado]] from 2007 to 2014.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/> In 2011, he did a residency at Anderson Ranch Arts Center, [[Snowmass, Colorado|Snowmass]], Colorado.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> He lived and worked in  [[Coyoacan]] [[Mexico City]] for 3 months in 2011.<ref name=\"Rainbow blight\"/> While there, he worked with Mexican artist Rodrigo Cifuentes.  From 2014 until 2017, he lived in [[Brooklyn]]. He now lives in [[Santa Clara County, California|Santa Clara]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n\nHis first solo show in Europe was at the Gallery Paulson in [[Copenhagen]] in May 2014.<ref name=\"Interview\"/> In November 2018, Aaron Johnson and Van Minnen had their first exhibit together in [[Hong Kong]]. Johnson and van Minnen have been long time friends.<ref name=\"Hong kong\">{{cite journal |last1=Bogojev |first1=Sasha |title=Aaron Johnson and Christian Rex Van Minnen's \"Chum Chum Rubby Dubby\" in Hong Kong |journal=Juxtapoz |date=Nov 2018 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/aaron-johnson-and-christian-rex-van-minnen-s-chum-chum-rubby-dubby-in-hong-kong/ |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083112/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/aaron-johnson-and-christian-rex-van-minnen-s-chum-chum-rubby-dubby-in-hong-kong/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\nVan Minnen works almost exclusively in painting but he has also made some ceramic sculptures.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\nVan Minnen is married to Ashley Muse and they have a son, Desmond.<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n\n==Influences==\n\nVan Minnen's favorite artist is [[Otto Marseus van Schrieck]], a Dutch master painter, best known for his paintings of forest flora and fauna.<ref name=\"Menagerie\">{{cite book |last1=Seelig |first1=Gero |title=Medusa's Menagerie: Otto Marseus van Schrieck and the Scholars |date=March 15, 2018 |publisher=Hirmer Publishers |isbn=978-3777428987 |edition=1t}}</ref>\n[[File:Otto Marseus van Schrieck 001.jpg|thumb|Otto Marseus van Schrieck painting|500px]]\n\nVan Minnen has studied the following artists: Nicole Duennebier, Ryan Riss, [[Judy Pfaff]], Jenny Morgan, [[Barnaby Furnas]], Skinner, [[Erik Parker]], [[Judy Fox]], [[Kenny Scharf]], Ryan Schneider, Amir Fallah, Martin Wittfooth, Gregory Jacobsen, Sinisa Kukec, [[Liz Craft]], [[Wayne White (artist)|Wayne White]], Ryan Travis Christian, [[Seamus Conley]], Fulvio di Piazza, [[Mark Dean Veca]], Tomoe Gokita, [[Robin Williams]], Barnaby Whitfield, [[Julie Heffernan]], [[Nicola Verlato]], [[David Altmejd]], Robert Hardgrave, Kim Keever, Aaron Johnson, Brendan Danielsson, [[Wangechi Mutu]]<ref name=\"Doze\" /><ref name=\"QuantumArtReview\">{{cite journal |last1=Hicks |first1=Jacob |title=Christian Rex van Minnen in Conversation with Jacob Hicks |journal=QuantumArtReview |date=February 4, 2017 |url=https://quantumartreview.com/2017/02/04/christian-rex-van-minnen-in-conversation-with-jacob-hicks/ |access-date=March 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170206053744/https://quantumartreview.com/2017/02/04/christian-rex-van-minnen-in-conversation-with-jacob-hicks/ |archive-date=February 6, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>, [[Pieter Bruegel the Elder]] and [[Pieter Aertsen]].<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\">{{cite journal |last1=Caro |title=The Sweetest Sour the Beyond Grotesque Paintings of Christian Rex van Minnen |journal=Hi-Fructose |date=March 2017 |volume=42 |pages=80\u201393}}</ref>\n\n[[Hendrik Goltzius]] and the line work from [[Hugo Grotius|Grotius]] can be seen in some of the tattooed skins.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\" />  \n\nInfluential authors have been  [[John Steinbeck]], [[Cormac McCarthy]] and the [[Mark Frost]] book, [[The Secret History of Twin Peaks]] <ref name=\"Mourn\">{{cite journal|last1=Pricco|first1=Evan|date=November 2017|title=Christian Rex van Minnen: In Mourning and Rebirth|url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/magazine/features/christian-rex-van-minnen-in-mourning-and-rebirth/|url-status=live|journal=S|volume=202|pages=80\u201389|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083135/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/magazine/features/christian-rex-van-minnen-in-mourning-and-rebirth/|archive-date=March 21, 2019|access-date=March 21, 2019|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  [[File:Horatius Cocles.jpg|thumb|An influence on van Minnen for the tattoos and use of the \"swelling line\", where the burin is manipulated to make lines thicker or thinner to create a tonal effect from a distance]]\n\n[[Rembrandt]] and the [[old masters]] have also been a major influence. Much of his color mixing and painting go back to this for technique.<ref name=\"AprilJ\"/><ref name=\"Bob\">{{cite web |last1=Schneider |first1=Bob |title=Christian Rex van Minnen |date=February 4, 2015 |url=http://www.bobschneider.com/2014favorites/bob-schneider-christian-rex-van-minnen |access-date=March 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083114/http://www.bobschneider.com/2014favorites/bob-schneider-christian-rex-van-minnen |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>  \n\nHis colorful [[gummy bear]]s go back to the [[Venetian school (art)|Venetian school]] of mixing grays and colors along with complementary debt coloring.<ref name=\"AprilJ\"/> The gummy bears he paints are painted in reverse in that he paints the brightest colors first on a white oil background and then adds color on top. These gummy bears balance the heavy dark background.  He enjoyed working in New York because of the environment and the competitiveness and pressure. New York to him represents ideas but he had a chance to go back to Colorado each summer for mountain biking, fishing and camping with his son.<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> He has since gone to live in California to continue his surfing which comes through in his most recent paintings in painting tattoos of surfers on portraits. \n\nWhile painting he puts on audio books and podcasts in the background.<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> What he plays depends on the state of mind of what he wants to paint.<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> His listening tastes are very eclectic from country, to classical opera to rap. He has a playlist that shuffles [[Anya]] and [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]].<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> His preference in podcasts is for comedy. Van Minnen is a hard worker who doesn't wait for inspiration to paint but just shows up every day.<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> He has a routine and works a regular work week.<ref name=\"AprilJ\" />\n\nFilm directors such as [[David Lynch]] (especially his 1990s series [[Twin Peaks]]).<ref name=\"AprilJ\" /> [[Werner Herzog]] and [[David Cronenberg]] have influenced van Minnen. But the greatest cinematic influence was the film series [[Alien (film)|Alien]] especially [[Alien 2]]. Van Minnen saw this when he was young and the character [[Ellen Ripley]] to him represents his mother trying to save the kids from the parasites of anger, addiction and the environment. Van Minnen likes the early two movies more than the ones that came after it.<ref name=\"AprilJ\">{{cite journal |title=Christian Rex van Minnen Beautifully Grotesque |journal=Juxtapoz |date=October 2016 |volume=189 |pages=42\u201344}}</ref>  One of the influences is a book he read when he was young was a nature field guide with drawings of parasites.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\" />\n===Painting style===\n\nHe is interested in drawing the viewer into an attraction-repulsion feeding on the same part of the colors while the gummy bears draw the viewer in and the organs and tattoos push the viewer away.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\nThe production process involves a monochromatic underpainting while leaving the white of the canvas exposed for certain figures.<ref name=\"studio\">{{cite journal |last1=Voynovskaya |first1=Nastia |title=Studio Visit: Christian Rex van Minnen Breaks Down His Layered Oil Painting Process |date=June 8, 2015 |url=http://hifructose.com/2015/06/08/studio-visit-christian-rex-van-minnen-breaks-down-his-layered-oil-painting-process/ |access-date=March 8, 2019 |journal= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703115823/http://hifructose.com/2015/06/08/studio-visit-christian-rex-van-minnen-breaks-down-his-layered-oil-painting-process/ |archive-date=July 3, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nWhile his Dutch Masters golden age paintings might try to glorify that period it is clear to him that the richness of materials in those paintings and the painting themselves represent [[Exploitation colonialism|colonial exploitation]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/>  He starts with underpaintings and then over paints with a semi transparent color, as was developed by [[Titian]]. He uses a dynamic color mixing which allows them to paint in layers and allows the light to mix with the color instead of mixing on the pallet. Self-taught, he studied intensively a book called ''Methods and Materials of the Great Schools and Masters'' by Sir [[Charles Lock Eastlake]].<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n\nThe underpaintings are monotypes he works on at home and then continues the over painting at his studio. This allows a quick production of monotypes where he can get a couple done per week and allows him to balance the months of painting and layers that have to go on top. In this way he can get ideas out quickly and not worry about capturing every single idea and painting at first.<ref name=\"Interview\"/>\n\nVan Minnen does not describe his work as macabre which would have to do with death and injury but rather about life and the absurd.<ref name=\"beinart\"/>  His work has also been called Super-Realism because his figures and gummy bears leap off the canvas.<ref name=\"male\">{{cite news |last1=Pagel |first1=David |title=Christian Rex van Minnen's modern tales of male domination, painted like an old master |agency=Los Angeles Times |date=Nov 25, 2017}}</ref> Another series of decapitated heads on top of jelly bears project power and language. All of the figures' heads have been executed but it is not clear how  or why.<ref name=\"male\"/>\n\nVan Minnen has also been compared to a modern [[Arcimboldo]]<ref name=\"Welsh Rats\"/> or a cross between a [[Natural history museum]] and [[H.R. Giger]]<ref name=\"H.R. Giger\"/>\n\nIn 2014 Van Minnen added more color to his work.<ref name=\"beinart\">{{cite web |last1=Winters |first1=Julie Antolick |title=Interview: Christian Rex van Minnen |url=https://beinart.org/interview-christian-rex-van-minnen |website=Beinart Gallery |access-date=March 8, 2019 |date=2014-11-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083123/https://beinart.org/interview-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, while wandering [[Madrid]] Van Minnen picked up a [[watercolor]] kit and has been making a number of pieces when traveling and outside of the studio.<ref name=\"watercolors\">{{cite journal |title=CHRISTIAN REX VAN MINNEN'S WATERCOLORS |date=March 2, 2017 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/studio-time/christian-rex-van-minnen-s-watercolors/ |journal= |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083111/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/studio-time/christian-rex-van-minnen-s-watercolors/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 he started working on a series with real-world issues and social political images. He does not want to go back to previous styles and continues to innovate.<ref name=\"Beyond Grotesque\"/>\n\n===Elements in the portraits===\n\nThe characters or people in van Minnen's portraits are not specific people but objects on which his elements are placed on top in an automatic manner.  None of the elements are metaphors or symbols.<ref name=\"Doze\"/> His paintings are not puzzles to be decoded and broken down and analyzed.<ref name=\"Doze\"/>\n\nHis elements repeat through his work starting from the earlier still life.\n\n*Circles with spirals and bead-like structures are used like repetitive words that lose their meaning with the repetition. \n*Tattoos on figures sometimes are not easy to read and they do not have a private meaning to Van Minnen.\n\n{{quote| \"With my phone in one hand and brushes in the other I go \u201clive\u201d on Instagram and begin \u201ctattooing\u201d the live feed comments into an oil-wet flesh glaze as quickly as I can. I tattoo the comments as they come in, it\u2019s indiscriminate and creates a very permanent registration of things that are most ephemeral, these comments that otherwise have no permanent archive.\"<ref name=\"Elefant\">{{cite journal |last1=Duguid |first1=Rosalind |title=Christian Rex van Minnen on Horror, Humour and Light |journal=Elephant |date=October 31, 2017 |url=https://elephant.art/christian-rex-van-minnen-horror-humour-and-light/ |access-date=March 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083113/https://elephant.art/christian-rex-van-minnen-horror-humour-and-light/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n}}\n*Lack of eyes or mouths on the figures might make it easier for the viewer to look longer at the piece.<ref name=\"Doze\"/>\n*Tie-dyed colors in a portrait.<ref name=\"beinart\"/>\n\n==Galleries of his art==\n\n*Gallery Poulsen, [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]<ref name=\"Paulsen\">{{cite web |title=Gallery Poulsen collection |url=https://www.gallerypoulsen.com/en/artist/works-by-christian-rex-van-minnen |access-date=March 5, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083116/https://www.gallerypoulsen.com/en/artist/works-by-christian-rex-van-minnen |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"QuantumArtReview\"/>\n*Ross + Kramer, New York City<ref name=\"Ross\">{{cite web|url=http://rkgallery.com/|title=Ross + Kramer|website=Ross + Kramer Gallery|access-date=March 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180804192312/http://rkgallery.com/|archive-date=August 4, 2018|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Richard Heller Gallery, Los Angeles<ref name=\"heller\">{{cite web|url=http://www.richardhellergallery.com/dynamic/artist_bio.asp?ArtistID=165|title=Richard Heller Gallery|access-date=March 5, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171005055656/http://www.richardhellergallery.com/dynamic/artist_bio.asp?ArtistID=165|archive-date=October 5, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Permanent collections ==\n\n*[[Denver Art Museum]]<ref name=\"Robischon\">{{cite web |title=Christian Rex van Minnen Golden Memes |url=https://www.robischongallery.com/artist/CHRISTIAN%20REX_VAN%20MINNEN/news/49/ |website=Robischon Gallery |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711202925/http://www.robischongallery.com/artist/CHRISTIAN%20REX_VAN%20MINNEN/news/49 |archive-date=July 11, 2016 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[Djurhuus]] Collection<ref name=\"heller\"/>\n*Colecci\u014dn Solo<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coleccionsolo.com/artists/christian-rex-van-minnen/|title=Colecci\u014dn Solo collection of Christian Rex van Minnen|access-date=March 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083120/https://coleccionsolo.com/artists/christian-rex-van-minnen/|archive-date=March 21, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*Richard B. Sachs Collection<ref name=\"heller\"/>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\n====Solo exhibitions====\n\n2017\n*Mourning Wood in [[Liminal]] Dawn, Richard Heller Gallery, [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, CA]]<ref name=\"solo\">{{cite journal |title=Mourning Wood in Liminal Dawn: Christian Rex van Minnen @ Richard Heller Gallery |journal=Juxtapoz |date=November 24, 2017 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/mourning-wood-in-liminal-dawn-christian-rex-van-minnen-richard-heller-gallery/ |access-date=March 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083111/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/mourning-wood-in-liminal-dawn-christian-rex-van-minnen-richard-heller-gallery/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2016 \n*[[Enantiodromia]], Gallery Poulsen, Copenhagen, Denmark\n\nThis was the first time that van Minnen exhibited ceramic sculptures. [[Enantiodromia]] is an ancient Greek theory that says that any large force in one direction will actually produce the opposite force.<ref name=\"icarus\">{{cite journal |last1=Bogojev |first1=Sasha |title=CHRISTIAN REX VAN MINNEN PREVIEW SHOW, \"ENANTIODROMIA\" WITH GALLERY POULSEN |journal=Juztgapoz |date=September 26, 2016 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/christian-rex-van-minnen-preview-show-enantiodromia-with-gallery-poulsen/ |access-date=March 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083113/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/christian-rex-van-minnen-preview-show-enantiodromia-with-gallery-poulsen/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2018\n\n*Once in a time in America, Copenhagen, Denmark <ref name=\"Once\">{{cite journal |title=Gallery Poulsen Explores the American Painter in \"Once Upon a Time in America\" Group Show in Copenhagen |date=Aug 18, 2018 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/gallery-poulsen-explores-the-american-painter-in-once-upon-a-time-in-america-group-show-in-copenhagen/ |journal= |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083114/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/gallery-poulsen-explores-the-american-painter-in-once-upon-a-time-in-america-group-show-in-copenhagen/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2015 \n*Golden Memes, Robischon Gallery, Denver, CO<ref name=\"Robischon\"/><ref name=\"Artnet Golden\">{{cite web |title=Artnet Golden Memes |url=http://www.artnet.com/galleries/robischon-gallery/christian-rex-van-minnen-golden-memes/ |accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n2014\n*Glazed and Confused, Gallery Poulsen, Copenhagen, Denmark<ref name=\"studio\"/>\n\n2013\n*Welsh Rats, Robischon Gallery, Denver, CO\n\n\u201cWelsh Rats,\u201d is a play on words for a German word \u2018[[Weltschmerz]]\u2019 coming from [[John Steinbeck]] in \u201c[[East of Eden (novel)|East of Eden]]\u201d. In German this means \u201cworld pain.\u201d  Van Minnen is expressing that Americans contort the meanings of older heavy European expressions.<ref name=\"Welsh Rats\">{{cite web |last1=Crest |first1=Russ |title=Made With Color Presents: The Grotesque Paintings Of Christian Rex van Minnen |url=http://www.beautifuldecay.com/2013/03/27/made-with-color-presents-the-grotesque-paintings-of-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |website=Beautiful/Decay |date=2013-03-27 |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009164959/http://beautifuldecay.com/2013/03/27/made-with-color-presents-the-grotesque-paintings-of-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |archive-date=October 9, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Several dark still lives were first presented at this exhibit such as [https://web.archive.org/web/20160823165205/http://beautifuldecay.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/VAN_MINNEN_Christian_BAD_VIBES_2013_Oil-Linen_44_x_70in.jpg Bad Vibes]\n\n2012\n*Fever Dream, Copro Gallery, Los Angeles, CA<ref name=\"CRVM Fever Dreams\">{{cite web |title=Christian Rex van Minnen Fever Dream |url=http://www.copronason.com/cvm/ |access-date=March 9, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170201090558/http://www.copronason.com/cvm/ |archive-date=February 1, 2017 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2011\n*Rainbow Blight, Bert Green Fine Art, Los Angeles, CA<ref name=\"Rainbow blight\">{{cite web |title=Rainbow blight |url=http://samanthalevinfineart.com/2010/05/13/rainbow-blight-new-work-by-christian-van-minnen/ |access-date=March 9, 2019 |date=2010-05-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308005113/http://samanthalevinfineart.com/2010/05/13/rainbow-blight-new-work-by-christian-van-minnen/ |archive-date=March 8, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2010\n*Neo-Grotesque, Roq la Rue Gallery, Seattle, WA<ref name=\"H.R. Giger\">{{cite journal |last1=Owens |first1=Annie |title=Neo Grotesque: New works by Christian Van Minnen |journal=Hi-Fructose |date=March 12, 2009 |url=http://hifructose.com/2009/03/12/neo-grotesque-new-works-by-christian-van-minnen/ |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123062853/http://hifructose.com/2009/03/12/neo-grotesque-new-works-by-christian-van-minnen/ |archive-date=January 23, 2015 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n====Selected group exhibitions====\n\n2019\n* MIXED PICKLES, [[Rundfunk der DDR|FunkhausBerlin]], [[Berlin]], Germany\n* In Heaven, Everything is Fine, Ross + Kramer Gallery, NY with Aaron Johnson. Titled after a song from David Lynch's 1977 film [[Eraserhead]]<ref name=\"heaven\">{{cite web |title=In Heaven Everything is Fine |url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/3/aaron-johnson-christian-rex-van-minnen-in-heaven-everything-is-fine-ross-kramer-gallery |website=Ross and Kramer |access-date=March 10, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190308034614/https://hypebeast.com/2019/3/aaron-johnson-christian-rex-van-minnen-in-heaven-everything-is-fine-ross-kramer-gallery |archive-date=March 8, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2018\n*Chum Chum Rubby Dubby, AishoNanzuka Gallery, Hong Kong<ref name=\"aishonanzuka\">{{cite web |title=chumchumrubbydubby |url=http://www.aishonanzuka.com/chumchumrubbydubby.html |website=aishonanzuka |access-date=March 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083119/http://aishonanzuka.com/chumchumrubbydubby.html |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*[[EXPO Chicago|Expo Chicago]], Richard Heller Gallery, Chicago, IL\n*Immersion, Richard Heller Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n*Dallas Art Fair, Richard Heller Gallery, Dallas, TX\n\n2017\n*UNTITLED, ART, Richard Heller Gallery, Miami Beach, FL\n*EXPO Chicago, Richard Heller Gallery, Chicago, IL\n*Dallas Art Fair, Richard Heller Gallery, Dallas, TX\n*Beheaded, Richard Heller Gallery, Santa Monica, CA\n*con-figuration, Postmasters, New York, NY<ref name=\"conflag\">{{cite web |title=Lunchtime dystopia: CON-Figuration at Postmasters |url=http://www.twocoatsofpaint.com/2017/04/lunchtime-dystopia-postmasters.html |website=TWO COATS OF PAINT |access-date=March 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180921174622/http://www.twocoatsofpaint.com/2017/04/lunchtime-dystopia-postmasters.html |archive-date=September 21, 2018 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n2016\n*UNTITLED, ART, Richard Heller Gallery, Miami Beach, FL\n*EXPO Chicago, Richard Heller Gallery, Chicago, IL\n*Juxtapoz x Superflat, co-curated by [[Takashi Murakami]] and [[Evan Pricco]] (Juxtapoz Magazine), Vancouver Art Gallery, Vancouver, Canada and  Pivot Art + Culture Center, Seattle, WA<ref name=\"Superflat\">{{cite journal |title=SUPERFLAT STUDIO VISIT: CHRISTIAN REX VAN MINNEN |date=July 15, 2016 |url=https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/superflat-studio-visit-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |access-date=March 8, 2019 |journal= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190321083146/https://www.juxtapoz.com/news/painting/superflat-studio-visit-christian-rex-van-minnen/ |archive-date=March 21, 2019 |url-status=live |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n*Dallas Art Fair, Richard Heller Gallery, Dallas, TX\n\n2015\n*Objects Installation, Denver Art Museum, Denver, CO\n*HEY! 3, Halle St Pierre, Paris, FR<ref name=\"HEY!\">{{cite web |title=HEY! |url=https://www.heyheyhey.fr/en/art-exhibitions/hey-modern-art-pop-culture-act-iii/ |website=HEY! modern art & pop culture Act III |accessdate=March 9, 2019}}</ref>\n*The Copenhagen Interpretation, Lodge Gallery, NY, NY\n*Jokes of Nature, Redline Arts, Denver, CO\n*All Types of Characters, Joshua Liner Gallery, NY, NY\n*Pulse NYC, Gallery Poulsen, NY, NY\u2003\n\n2014\n*Heat! Gallery Poulsen, Copenhagen, DK\n*Annual Art Auction, Anderson Ranch Arts Center, Snowmass, CO\n*Winter Group Show, Jonathan Levine Gallery, NY, NY\n*Ducks, Greenpoint Terminal Gallery, Brooklyn, NY\n\n2013\n*Messin\u2019 With The Masters, Mesa Arts Center, Mesa, AZ\n*The Gallery Poulsen 10 Years Anniversary Show, Copenhagen, Denmark\n*Beinart Collective 2013 Group Show, Copro Gallery, LA, CA\n*Varnish 10th Anniversary Show, Varnish Fine Art, San Francisco, CA\n*The Wild Bunch, Gallery Poulsen, Copenhagen, Denmark\n\n2012\n*Texas Contemporary Art Fair, Robischon Gallery, Denver, CO\n*Unnatural History, Royal West of England Academy, Bristol, England\n*Against the Grain, Mark Moore Gallery, Los Angeles,