y American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:American painters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Regis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Painters from Colorado]]\n[[Category:People from Providence, Rhode Island]]\n[[Category:Sculptors from Colorado]]\n[[Category:American ceramists]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Rex_van_Minnen"}
{"title_page": "John McDonnell", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = John McDonnell\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image            = John McDonnell, 2016 Labour Party Conference 2.jpg\n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n|leader           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start       = 13 September 2015\n|term_end         = 4 April 2020\n|predecessor      = [[Chris Leslie]]\n|successor        = [[Anneliese Dodds]]\n|office1          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]\n|term_start1      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end1        = \n|predecessor1     = [[Terry Dicks]]\n|successor1       = \n|majority1        = 9,261 (21.1%)\n|office2          = [[Greater London Council|Deputy Leader of the Greater London Council]]\n|leader2          = [[Ken Livingstone]] \n|predecessor2     = [[Illtyd Harrington]]\n|successor2       = [[Michael Ward (British politician)|Michael Ward]]\n|term_start2      = 7 May 1984\n|term_end2        = 7 May 1985\n|office3          = Member of [[Greater London Council]]<br />for Hayes and Harlington\n|term_start3      = 7 May 1981\n|term_end3        = 31 March 1986\n|leader3          = [[Horace Cutler]]<br/>[[Ken Livingstone]]\n|predecessor3     = A. H. S. Hull\n|successor3       = ''Council abolished''\n|majority3        = 4,346 (17.1%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election-demon.co.uk/glc/glchd.html|title=Greater London Council election results: Hillingdon|author=|date=|website=election-demon.co.uk|accessdate=11 September 2018}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|birth_name       = John Martin McDonnell \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1951|9|8|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Liverpool]], England\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|spouse           = {{marriage|Marilyn Jean Cooper|1971|1987|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|Cynthia Marie Pinto|1995}}\n|children         = 3\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|otherparty       = [[Socialist Campaign Group]]\n|education        = [[Great Yarmouth Grammar School]]<br />[[St Joseph's College, Ipswich]]<br />Burnley Technical College<ref name=BBC2015>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34245371 |title=A profile of John McDonnell \u2013 new shadow chancellor |publisher=BBC |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n|alma_mater       = [[Brunel University London|Brunel University]] (BSc)<br />[[Birkbeck, University of London]] (MSc)\n|website          = {{url|https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/|Official website}}\n}}\n'''John Martin McDonnell''' (born 8 September 1951) is a British politician serving as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], he served as [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] from 2015 to 2020. He ideologically identifies as a Marxist.\n\nHe served as chair of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] in Parliament and [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]]; McDonnell also chaired the Public Services Not Private Profit Group. He is also parliamentary convenor of the Trade Union Co-ordinating Group of eight left-wing trade unions representing over half a million workers. McDonnell attempted to stand for the position of [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party leader]] following [[Tony Blair]]'s resignation in [[2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2007]], but failed to get enough nominations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6660565.stm |title=Brown will enter No 10 unopposed |work=[[BBC]] News |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> He was a candidate for the party leadership again in [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2010]] following [[Gordon Brown]]'s resignation after Labour's [[2010 United Kingdom general election|electoral defeat]],<ref name=\"mirror1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/05/18/labour-mp-john-mcdonnell-to-stand-in-the-leadership-campaign-115875-22268136 |title=Labour MP John McDonnell to stand in the leadership campaign |work=Daily Mirror|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> but withdrew in favour of [[Diane Abbott]], feeling that he would be unable to secure enough nominations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://l-r-c.org.uk/news/story/john-mcdonnell-im-withdrawing-from-labour-leadership-race |title=I'm withdrawing from Labour leadership race |author=McDonnell, John |publisher=[[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]] |date=9 June 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his election as Labour leader in [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2015]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]] appointed McDonnell as his Shadow Chancellor. Alongside Corbyn, McDonnell has been seen as a key figure on the left-wing of the party.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite book |author=Duncan Hall |title=A2 Government and Politics: Ideologies and Ideologies in Action |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KPhwAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45 |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=978-1-4477-3399-7 |pages=45\u201346|year=2011 }}{{self-published source|date=April 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} As Shadow Chancellor, McDonnell pledged to increase spending on infrastructure and research, describing his vision for the economy as \"socialism with an [[iPad]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour wants 'socialism with an iPad' says McDonnell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34877475|year=2015|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcDonnell was born in [[Liverpool]] to a family with an [[Irish Catholic]] background.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joo4w_BwEJs</ref> He moved with his family to [[East Anglia]] when he was very young; his father became a bus driver and was a branch secretary of the [[Transport and General Workers' Union]].<ref name=BBC2015/><ref name=\"Bennett\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/sep/26/labourleadership.labour |title=Honest John |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 September 2006 |accessdate=14 September 2015 |author=Bennett, Ronan}}</ref> McDonnell attended [[Great Yarmouth High School|Great Yarmouth Grammar School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatyarmouthmercury.co.uk/news/shadow-chancellor-shares-memories-of-growing-up-in-great-yarmouth-1-4820510|title=Shadow chancellor shares memories of growing up in Great Yarmouth|last=Dickson|first=Annabelle|website=Great Yarmouth Mercury|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> McDonnell began training to be a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|Catholic priest]], receiving a Local Authority grant to attend [[St Joseph's College, Ipswich]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Senior Prospectus|url=https://www.stjos.co.uk/senior/prospectus/senior-prospectus-pdf/ |website=St Joseph's College |accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> a [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] boarding fee-paying [[independent school]] for boys (now co-educational), before eventually deciding against the vocation at the age of 15 or 16 as he \"basically discovered girlfriends, so celibacy wasn't going to be an option. I was also into politics.\"<ref name=\"MaguirePro\">{{cite news |last1=Maguire |first1=Kevin |title=John McDonnell, the self-made socialist |url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/john-mcdonnell-socialist-kevin-maguire-profile |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=Prospect Magazine |date=18 September 2018}}</ref> McDonnell is now irreligious, but refers to himself as a \"[[cultural Catholic]]\" and is a regular churchgoer.<ref name=\"MaguirePro\" />\n\nUpon leaving education, McDonnell held a series of unskilled jobs. After marrying his first wife, he studied for [[Advanced Level (UK)|A-level]]s at night school at [[Burnley]] [[Technical College]], and at the age of 23, he moved to [[Hayes, Hillingdon|Hayes]] in Greater London, attended [[Brunel University]], and earned a bachelor's degree in government and politics.<ref name=\"Brunel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.brunel.ac.uk/courses/undergraduate/politics-and-history-bsc |title=Politics and History BSc |publisher=[[Brunel University London]] |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/3/30804.stm|title=Candidate: John McDonnell |work=BBC News}}</ref> During this period, he helped his wife run a small children's home in Hayes, and was active on behalf of his local community and for [[National Union of Public Employees]]. After completing his master's degree in politics and sociology at [[Birkbeck, University of London]],<ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/polsoc/ |title=Department of Politics |publisher=Bbk.ac.uk |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> he became a researcher and official with the [[National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain)|National Union of Mineworkers]] from 1977 to 1978, and later the [[Trades Union Congress]] from 1978 until 1982. From 1985 to 1987, McDonnell was head of the policy unit at [[Camden Borough Council]], then chief executive of the Association of London Authorities from 1987 to 1995, and the [[Association of London Government]] from 1995 until 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=John McDonnell|url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/about-us/fellows/downloads/john-mcdonnell.pdf |website=bbk.ac.uk |publisher=Birkbeck, University of London |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Greater London Council (1981\u20131986)==\nIn 1981, McDonnell was elected to the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) as the member for Hayes and Harlington. He became the GLC's chair of finance and deputy leader to [[Ken Livingstone]], who described him as having an \"absolute grasp for detail and every year he produced a balanced budget, no borrowing\". He was sacked by Ken Livingstone in 1985 over the [[Rate-capping rebellion|strategy to oppose rate-capping]]\u2014[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s government had capped council rates (now called council tax), an action which the GLC had claimed, based on figures calculated by McDonnell, would lead to \u00a3135 million in cuts. However, Livingstone claimed in his autobiography to have found that the authority could actually still increase spending and cap the rates; Livingstone said that McDonnell had \u2018exaggerated\u2019 spending figures to support his case that the GLC had to ignore the rates cap, and that he confronted McDonnell, saying \"If these figures are right we\u2019re going to look like the biggest fucking liars since [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]].\" McDonnell described Livingstone's account as \"complete fiction\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: John McDonnell |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5345644.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=11 June 2007 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/15/john-mcdonnell-unreconstructed-on-the-left-but-with-allies-on-the-right</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Ronan Bennett]] for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper, he described his role during this time as being \"to translate policies into concrete realities on the ground.\" He further discussed his performance by indicating, \"I was a fairly hard-nosed administrator. We set in train policies for which we were attacked from all sides but are now accepted as mainstream: large-scale investment in public services; raising the issue of Ireland and arguing for a dialogue for peace; equal opportunities; police accountability. We set up a women's committee, an ethnic minorities committee.\"<ref name=\"Bennett\"/>\n\n==After the GLC (1987\u20131997)==\nFollowing the abolition of the GLC, McDonnell was employed as head of the policy unit at [[Camden London Borough Council]]. In 1987, he became Chief Executive of the Association of London Authorities (eventually the [[Association of London Government]]), where he represented all the [[London boroughs]] in their relations with central government and Europe. Having previously unsuccessfully contested [[Hampstead and Highgate (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Highgate]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]], McDonnell fought for his home constituency of Hayes and Harlington at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], but lost by 53 votes, after three recounts, to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] incumbent, [[Terry Dicks]]. During the campaign, Dicks sued for [[libel]] over critical material in McDonnell's campaign leaflets; McDonnell settled and paid Dicks damages of \u00a315,000 plus legal costs of \u00a355,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.steveplatt.net/archive/newstatesman/johnmajor/majorpaperboy.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504110127/http://www.steveplatt.net/archive/newstatesman/johnmajor/majorpaperboy.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 May 2006 |title=Would you sue your paper boy? |first=Steve |last=Platt |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=12 March 1993 |accessdate=1 November 2006 |df= }}</ref> McDonnell would later refer to Dicks as a \u2018stain\u2019 on the character of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and a stain on the Conservative Party, and a \u2018malignant creature\u2019 during his maiden parliamentary speech.<ref name=\"api.parliament.uk\">https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1997/jun/06/governance-of-london-1#1997-06-06T12:10:00Z</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament (1997\u2013present)==\nWhen Terry Dicks then stood down, McDonnell became the MP for Hayes and Harlington at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], with 62 per cent of the vote and a majority of over 14,000. He made his [[maiden speech]] in the House of Commons on 6 June 1997, where he notably launched a scathing attack against his predecessor, against parliamentary tradition.<ref name=\"api.parliament.uk\"/> He has been involved in several local community campaigns, including one opposing the expansion of [[Heathrow Airport]] and its impact on local communities. He opposed [[New Labour]] policies of the [[Iraq War]], [[foundation hospitals]], student [[top-up fees]], [[trust school]]s and [[anti-terror laws]]. When Ken Livingstone was elected [[Mayor of London]], as an independent in 2000, he appointed McDonnell to his cabinet with responsibility for local government in London.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2000/may/23/londonmayor.uk</ref>\n\n===Iraq War===\nMcDonnell voted against the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 Iraq War]], stating in 2007:{{cquote|I have used every opportunity to oppose the government's alliance with [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] and the [[US occupation of Iraq|US-led military occupation of Iraq]] which has resulted in the deaths of over 655,000, caused untold human suffering, put at risk the territorial integrity of Iraq, destabilised the entire region, alienated our own Muslim communities and given a huge boost to international terrorism \u2013 just as we warned it would.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Labour's contenders see the war |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/feb/21/iraq.labour|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=13 September 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>|sign=|source=}} In October 2006, McDonnell was one of 12 Labour MPs to back [[Plaid Cymru]] and the [[Scottish National Party]]'s call for a [[Iraq Inquiry|parliamentary inquiry into the war in Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6104310.stm|title=Labour MPs who rebelled on Iraq|date=31 October 2006|accessdate=31 October 2006|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n===Irish Republican Army===\nIn May 2003, he made controversial comments about the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA), saying:{{cquote|It's about time we started honouring those people involved in the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army campaign 1969\u201397|armed struggle]]. It was the bombs and bullets and sacrifice made by the likes of [[Bobby Sands]] that brought Britain to the negotiating table. The peace we have now is due to the action of the IRA.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/may/30/northernireland.devolution |title=MP's 'brave IRA' comments spark outrage |first=Tom |last=Happold |work=The Guardian |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 July 2014 |location=London, UK}}</ref>}}\n\nThreatened with expulsion from the Labour Party, he went on to offer a rationale for his comments in an article written for ''The Guardian'' in June 2003 (\"Expulsion would be an odd reward for telling hard truths\"), stating:{{cquote|Let me be clear, I abhor the killing of innocent human beings. My argument was that republicans had the right to honour those who had brought about this process of negotiation which had led to peace. Having achieved this central objective now it was time to move on. The future for achieving the nationalists' goals is through the political process and in particular through the Northern Ireland Assembly elections ... Irish republicans have to face the fact that the use of violence has resulted in unforgivable atrocities. No cause is worth the loss of a child's life. No amount of political theory will justify what has been perpetrated on the victims of the bombing campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=John|title=Why I stood up for Bobby Sands|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/jun/03/northernireland.labour|website=The Guardian|date=3 June 2003|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nIn his study at Hayes, McDonnell has a plaque presented to him by [[Gerry Kelly]] dedicated to the \"H-Block Martyrs 1981\", referring to those who died during the [[1981 Irish hunger strike]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/mcdonnell|work=Financial Times}}</ref> A spokesman for McDonnell said the plaque \"merely commemorates the peaceful protest in prison, not the prior actions of those involved\".<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell defends plaque honouring IRA 'martyrs' in his office|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/northern-ireland-assembly/news/93285/john-mcdonnell-defends-plaque-honouring|work=PoliticsHome.com|date=2 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yorke|first1=Harry|title=John McDonnell continues to display a plaque to IRA terrorists in his study, it emerges|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/03/02/john-mcdonnell-continues-display-plaque-ira-terrorists-study/|work=The Telegraph|date=2 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report in ''[[The Times]]'' published in November 2015, McDonnell in 1985 made similar comments at a Labour Committee on Ireland meeting, before the start of the Northern Ireland peace process. The ''Deptford Mercury'' asserted at the time that McDonnell had suggested there was a role for \"the ballot, the bullet and the bomb\" in achieving a United Ireland, and joked about \"[[kneecapping]]\" the \"gutless wimp\" Labour councillors who had declined to join the meeting.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Dominic |title=McDonnell gave his backing to the IRA's bomb campaign |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article4625106.ece |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Times |date=27 November 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, McDonnell apologised on ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' for any offence caused by his remarks on the IRA. However, contrary to what he had said 12 years previously, he now maintained that his remarks in 2003 had been an attempt to persuade republicans to support the peace process and to afford the IRA the opportunity to disarm without humiliation stating: \"There was a real risk of the Republican movement splitting and some of them continuing the armed process.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/18/john-mcdonnell-apologises-for-ira-comment-labour|title=John McDonnell apologises 'from the bottom of my heart' for IRA comment|last=Watt|first=Nicholas|last2=Gayle|first2=Damien|date=17 September 2015|website=The Guardian|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Groups and campaigns in Parliament===\nMcDonnell is a leading member of several all-party groups within Parliament, including groups representing individual trade unions, such as the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]] (PCS), the [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers]] (RMT), the [[Fire Brigades Union]] (FBU), the [[National Union of Journalists]] (NUJ) and justice unions such as [[Napo (trade union)|NAPO]]. He is also a leading member of groups on a wide range of issues such as Britain's Irish community, the [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] community, [[endometriosis]], and [[Kenya]]. McDonnell is a member of the Labour Land Campaign, which advocates introducing a [[land value tax]].<ref>[http://www.labourland.org/ Labour Land Campaign website], labourland.org. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john-mcdonnell.net/about_john_mcdonnell|title=John McDonnell}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell chairs the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]] (LRC), a left-wing group of Labour activists, local parties, trade unions and MPs that campaigns for the adoption of a raft of socialist policies by the Labour Government. The group was founded on Saturday, 3 July 2004, and currently has more than 800 members and 90 affiliates. He also chairs the Public Services Not Private Profit, an anti-privatisation campaign that brings together sixteen trade unions and several campaigning organisations, such as the [[World Development Movement]], Defend Council Housing and the [[National Pensioners Convention]]. An [[early day motion]] in support of the campaign attracted more than ninety MPs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=30421&SESSION=875 |title=Early Day Motion |date=29 March 2006 |accessdate=1 November 2006}}</ref> The campaign held a mass rally and lobby of Parliament on 27 June 2006, which was attended by more than 2,000 trade unionists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/publicservices/story/0,,1807050,00.html |title=Campaigners demand halt to privatisation |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last=Mulholland |date=27 June 2006 |accessdate=1 November 2006 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Economic policy===\nIn 2006, McDonnell said that \"[[Karl Marx|Marx]], [[Vladimir Lenin|Lenin]] and [[Leon Trotsky|Trotsky]]\" were his \"most significant\" intellectual influences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour's manifesto is more Keynesian than Marxist|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/labours-manifesto-more-keynesian-marxist|year=2017}}</ref> Footage emerged of McDonnell in 2013 talking about the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]] and stating, \"I've been waiting for this for a generation! We\u2019ve got to demand systemic change. Look, I\u2019m straight, I\u2019m honest with people: I\u2019m a [[Marxism|Marxist]].\"<ref name=marxist1>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell: I was joking when I celebrated the 2008 economic crash|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-video-labour-marxist-economic-crash-jeremy-corbyn-a7309651.html|quote=It was a joke. I also said, The bankers have done more to undermine capitalism than any of the Socialist Worker Party's activities in the last forty years.' I think it was taken as a joke, and if you listen to the tape, people fell about laughing as a result.|year=2016|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> He was accused of celebrating the financial crisis of 2007\u20132008; McDonnell denied the allegation and claimed he was \"joking\".<ref name=marxist1 /> During an interview with [[Andrew Marr]] when the footage was played and McDonnell was asked, \"Are you a Marxist?\", he replied: \"I believe there's a lot to learn from reading ''[[Capital: Critique of Political Economy|Kapital]]'', yes of course there is, and that's been recommended not just by me but many others, mainstream economists as well.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Marx Brothers: Jeremy Corbyn joins John McDonnell in praising Communist icon's work|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/08/marx-brothers-jeremy-corbyn-joins-john-mcdonnell-praising-communist/|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 May 2017}}</ref> In 2018, McDonnell attended the Marx 200 conference, where he said, \"Marxism is about the freedom of spirit, the development of life chances, the enhancement of democracy.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=How John McDonnell is leading the surprise rebirth of British Marxism|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2018/05/how-john-mcdonnell-leading-surprise-rebirth-british-marxism|year=2018|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref> In 2019, McDonnell during an interview stated that Marx\u2019s ''Kapital'' is \u201cone of the important analyses of the modern capitalist system.\u201d<ref name=capitalism1>{{cite web|title=John McDonnell interview: why capitalism is on borrowed time|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/john-mcdonnell-interview-why-capitalism-is-on-borrowed-time-623x8tz9w|newspaper=The Times|year=2019}}</ref>\n\n====Public services====\nMcDonnell has consistently opposed the privatisation of public services and chaired the Public Services not Private Profit Campaign launched in 2006 and supported by sixteen trade unions linking up with students, pensioners, health campaigners and the [[World Development Movement]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pcs.org.uk/news/news-archive/public-services-not-private-profit|title=Public services not private profit|work=Public and Commercial Services Union|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbu.org.uk/circular/2006hoc0358dm/re-public-services-not-private-profit-campaign|title=re: Public services not private profit campaign|website=Fire Brigades Union|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tssa.org.uk/en/Your-union/Your-company/company-headlines.cfm/public-services-not-private-profit-1|title=Public Services Not Private Profit|last=Fidler|first=Sue|website=TSSA|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell is \"not supportive of PFI schemes\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060208/halltext/60208h03.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 Feb 2006 (pt 3) |last=Westminster |first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> declaring that he has \"opposed every PFI scheme that was proposed\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110324/debtext/110324-0003.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 Mar 2011 (pt 0003)|last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> In 2006, during the parliamentary debate on the [[Budget resolution|Budget Resolutions]], McDonnell warned against [[Public\u2013private partnership|public-private finance initiatives]] (PFIs), calling for an inquiry:<blockquote>There are numerous examples. I refer hon. Members to the work of Alison Pollock<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/allysonpollock |title=Allyson Pollock |website=The Guardian |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> and to the publications by [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]] in recent months, which contain example after example in the public services, health and education where PFI has been used to exploit the public purse, has failed to deliver and has delivered large bonuses and profits to individual company directors. That is why I regret that the Chancellor is going along that line. I would welcome a Government inquiry into PFI, which would probably echo the work done by the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] on individual PFI schemes, which has demonstrated their lack of deliverability and cost effectiveness.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060322/debtext/60322-22.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 22 Mar 2006 (pt 22) |last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Tax transparency====\nThroughout his time in [[Parliament]], McDonnell has championed the cause of tax justice, hosting the Parliamentary launch of the [[Tax Justice Network]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bccconference.co.uk/speakers/john-mcdonnell-mp/ |title=Rt Hon John McDonnell MP \u2013 BCC Conference 2018 |website=www.bccconference.co.uk |language=en-GB |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, McDonnell worked with William Campbell-Taylor and Maurice Glasman, who challenged a parliamentary bill concerned with the City of London Corporation in relation to alleged tax avoidance:<blockquote>Apart from a couple of brave, independent-minded Labour MPs, notably John McDonnell, nobody supported Glasman and Campbell-Taylor to challenge the bill. Such is the fear that the corporation inspires in parliament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newstatesman.com/economy/2011/02/london-corporation-city | title=The tax haven in the heart of Britain |work=newstatesman|accessdate=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Bank regulations====\nDuring the 2011 Budget Resolutions, McDonnell highlighted his long-term consistent work calling for better regulation of the banking and finance sector:<blockquote>We seem to forget that the cause of that crisis was the cause of this crisis\u2014speculation by the banks and other speculators and, yes, a Government who failed to regulate. I have to say, however, that when a number of Members called for bank regulation in this House, there was an element of quietude on all sides. I remember fighting for four years, in almost a solitary capacity, to secure the passage of the City of London (Ward Elections) Bill at a time when we were pressing for regulation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110324/debtext/110324-0003.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 Mar 2011 (pt 0003)|last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Anti-austerity====\nIn February 2013, McDonnell was among those who supported the [[People's Assembly Against Austerity]] in a letter published by ''The Guardian'' newspaper.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/feb/05/people-assembly-against-austerity People's Assembly opening letter], ''The Guardian'', 5 February 2013.</ref>\n\n===Heathrow Airport expansion===\n[[File:John McDonnell Grow Heathrow at Court-4.jpg|thumb|McDonnell with opponents of the Heathrow Airport expansion outside Central London County Court, 2012]]\nMcDonnell has been a vocal opponent of plans to [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport|expand Heathrow Airport]] with a third runway\u2014the proposed site lies within his constituency. During a debate on the expansion of the airport on 15 January 2009, he was [[Suspension in the UK parliament|suspended]] for five days by Deputy Speaker [[Alan Haselhurst]] after disrupting Commons proceedings. McDonnell picked up the [[ceremonial mace]] and placed it down on an empty bench in the Commons while shouting that the lack of a vote on the third runway was \"a disgrace to the democracy of this country.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7830937.stm|title=MP suspended after mace protest|publisher=BBC|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=15 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jan/15/heathrow|title=Labour MP suspended from Commons over Heathrow protest|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|work=The Guardian|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=15 January 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n===Armed police and MI5===\nIn 2015, McDonnell's name appeared on a letter calling for the armed police and [[MI5]] to be disbanded. He claimed that he had not signed the letter, which was produced by the Socialist Campaign for a Labour Victory (SCLV), but he was photographed holding a copy of the letter, although he later said that he did not know that the demand was on the letter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12005431/John-McDonnell-signed-letter-calling-for-MI5-and-armed-police-to-be-disbanded.html|title=John McDonnell signed letter calling for MI5 and armed police to be disbanded|first=Kate|last=McCann|date=19 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/john-mcdonnell-denies-backing-call-to-end-mi5-and-disarm-police|title=John McDonnell denies backing call to end MI5 and disarm police|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|first2=Frances|last2=Perraudin|date=19 November 2015|website=the Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2007 Labour leadership campaign==\n{{main|2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)}}\nOn 14 July 2006, McDonnell announced his intention to stand for leadership of the Labour Party when [[Tony Blair]] announced the date of his resignation. He called for \"a challenge to the present political consensus\", and, \"a real Labour government based upon the policies that our supporters expect from us\". McDonnell said he would like to see a return to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]'s more traditional areas.\n\nInitially, McDonnell and [[Michael Meacher]] were the two candidates representing the left wing of the party. McDonnell's campaign concentrated on grassroots efforts, which earned him an endorsement from the [[Trades Union Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john4leader.org.uk/latestnews/0016.html|title=John McDonnell MP: Another World Is Possible|publisher=John4leader.org.uk |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907233203/http://www.johnmcdonnell.org.uk/latestnews/0016.html |archivedate=7 September 2008}}</ref> In a [[YouGov]] opinion poll of more than 1,100 Labour Party members asking their preferred choice in the leadership contest, McDonnell received 9% support, and was ranked second to [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Gordon Brown]], who led with 80% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=David |last2=Isabel |first2=Oakeshott |title=Blair under pressure as Labour faces election rout |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1720004.ece |accessdate=28 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=29 April 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014081917/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1720004.ece |archivedate=14 October 2008}}</ref> Declared supporters included [[Diane Abbott]], [[Tony Benn]], and [[Ann Cryer]]. In total, eleven Labour MPs declared their support on McDonnell's campaign website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.john4leader.org.uk/endorsements.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328215354/http://www.john4leader.org.uk/endorsements.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 March 2007 |title=John McDonnell MP: Another World Is Possible |publisher=John4leader.org.uk |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nLabour Party rules require candidates to be nominated by 12.5% of Labour MPs (45 out of a total of 355 in 2007). [[Gordon Brown]] received 313 (88.2%) nominations, while McDonnell failed to collect the 45 nominations required to proceed to the Electoral College. As the only nominated candidate, Gordon Brown was declared leader by the NEC.\n\n==2010 Labour leadership campaign==\n{{main|2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)}}\nOn 18 May 2010, news broke that McDonnell wanted to stand in the Labour Party leadership election, to be held following the resignation of Gordon Brown, and would announce it the following day at the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]] conference in Brighton. McDonnell noted that it would be \"difficult\" to get the 33 nominations needed from the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] required to stand in the election.<ref name=\"mirror1\"/>\n\nDuring a hustings for the [[GMB Union]] on 7 June, McDonnell was asked what single act he would do to improve the world if he could travel back to the 1980s. His off-the-cuff reply was that \"I was on the GLC that [[Margaret Thatcher|Mrs. Thatcher]] abolished, I worked for the NUM and we had the NUM strike, I think I would assassinate Thatcher\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10263076 |title=John McDonnell apologises for Thatcher 'joke' offence |work=BBC News |date=8 June 2010|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulholland |first1=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last2=Stratton |first2=Allegra |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jun/07/john-mcdonnell-assassinate-thatcher-joke |title=John McDonnell jokes that he would have liked to have assassinated Thatcher |work=The Guardian |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Conservative MP [[Conor Burns]] told the BBC that \"[it was] very distasteful\" and \"a very silly remark\". McDonnell told the BBC: \"I'm sorry if I have caused offence to anyone. It was a joke and in that audience it was taken as a joke ... it was taken out of context, I can see if people are upset about that and if I have caused offence to anyone of course I apologise\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/7808953/John-McDonnell-says-he-would-like-to-assassinate-Margaret-Thatcher.html|title=John McDonnell says he would like to 'assassinate' Margaret Thatcher|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 June 2010|accessdate=9 June 2010|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=BBCDP_8June2010>{{cite news|title=BBC Daily Politics|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/the_daily_politics/8728299.stm|accessdate=21 October 2015|date=8 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy 9 June 2010, the deadline for nominations, he had secured only 16 nominations and withdrew from the contest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://l-r-c.org.uk/news/story/john-mcdonnell-im-withdrawing-from-labour-leadership-race |title=John McDonnell: I'm withdrawing from Labour leadership race 9th June 2010 |publisher=L-r-c.org.uk |accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer (2015\u20132020)==\n[[File:Jeremy Corbyn and John McDonnell, 2016 Labour Party Conference.jpg|thumb|McDonnell after giving his 2016 Labour Party Conference speech, with Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]]]]\nMcDonnell was one of the thirty-six Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] (who was elected as Labour leader with 59.5% of the vote) as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|Labour leadership election of 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|work=New Statesman}}</ref> McDonnell managed Corbyn's leadership campaign, and he was appointed Shadow Chancellor in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|first2=Patrick|last2=Wintour|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/13/jeremy-corbyn-shadow-cabinet-andy-burnham-labour|title=John McDonnell appointed shadow chancellor in Corbyn's new frontbench|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London, UK|date=13 September 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an article in ''The Guardian'' in the previous month, he set out the economic principles that a Corbyn government would follow:{{quote|Let me make it absolutely clear that Labour under Jeremy Corbyn is committed to eliminating the deficit and creating an economy in which we live within our means. ... We accept that cuts in public spending will help eliminate the deficit, but our cuts won't be to the middle-and low-income earners and certainly not to the poor ... alongside deficit elimination, the Corbyn campaign is advocating a fundamental reform of our economic system. This will include the introduction of an effective regulatory regime for our banks and financial sector; a full-blown [[Glass\u2013Steagall Legislation|Glass-Steagall]] system to separate day-to-day and investment banking; legislation to replace short-term shareholder value with long-term sustainable economic and social responsibilities as the prime objective of companies; radical reform of the failed auditing regime; the extension of a wider range of forms of company and enterprise ownership and control including public, [[co-operative]] and stakeholder ownership; and the introduction of a financial transactions tax to fund the rebalancing of our economy towards production and manufacturing.<ref name=\"Comment\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/11/jeremy-corbyn-close-deficit-poor-labour-economy|title=Jeremy Corbyn would clear the deficit \u2013 but not by hitting the poor|work=The Guardian|date=11 August 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015|author=McDonnell, John}}</ref>}}\n\nMcDonnell's first speech as Shadow Chancellor was at the 2015 Labour Party conference in [[Brighton]]. In the speech, he set out Labour's thinking and priorities in key areas, as well as encouraging Labour MPs who had refused to serve under Corbyn to return.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34378290 |title=Labour's John McDonnell: Another world is possible |work=BBC News |date=28 September 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe surprised many by calling upon Labour MPs to back [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Chancellor [[George Osborne]]'s Fiscal Charter, arguing that supporting the proposed deficit reduction framework showed Labour's commitment to \"living within their means.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell: Labour will match Osborne and live within our means|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/25/john-mcdonnell-labour-will-match-osborne-and-live-within-our-means|accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=25 September 2015}}</ref> However, he reversed that call in October, citing his trip to visit former steelworkers at a recently closed plant in [[Redcar]] as the reason for not wanting to be associated with supporting government cuts.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonnell says fiscal charter U-turn due to meeting Redcar families |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/13/john-mcdonnell-says-fiscal-charter-u-turn-due-to-meeting-redcar-families |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=13 October 2015}}</ref> McDonnell repeated the word \"embarrassing\" five times in his Commons response to the U-turn,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Deacon |first1=Michael |title='Embarrassing! Embarrassing! Embarrassing!' Labour's John McDonnell sums up his own U-turn |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/11932423/Embarrassing-Embarrassing-Embarrassing-Labours-John-McDonnell-sums-up-his-own-U-turn.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=14 October 2015}}</ref> adding that \"a bit of humility amongst politicians never goes amiss\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Nigel |title=John McDonnell admits 'embarrassing' U-turn over key economic policy as new Labour leadership hit by first |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-admits-embarrassing-u-turn-over-key-economic-policy-as-new-labour-leadership-hit-by-a6694526.html |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Independent |date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a November speech ahead of Osborne's Spending Review, McDonnell pledged that a Labour government would spend 3.5% of GDP on infrastructure and fund research through an Innovation Policy Council, describing his vision for the economy as \"socialism with an [[iPad]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=John McDonnell to unveil 'socialism with an iPad' economic plan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/20/john-mcdonnell-to-unveil-socialism-with-an-ipad-economic-plan|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=John McDonnell pledges 'socialism with an iPad' in a Jeremy Corbyn-led Britain|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-pledges-socialism-with-an-ipad-in-a-jeremy-corbyn-led-britain-a6742066.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|newspaper=Independent|date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell has explored ideas surrounding \"alternative models of ownership\", publishing a report on the subject in June 2017 and hosting a discussion conference in London in February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/10/john-mcdonnell-says-moving-services-to-public-hands-would-cost-nothing |title=John McDonnell says nationalising services would cost nothing |last=Association |first=Press |date=2018-02-10 |website=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref> The report sets out the \"practicality and necessity of a shift to a variety of alternative forms of ownership and control of productive enterprises, including co-operatives, municipal and locally-led ownership forms, and ... new democratic forms of national ownership\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/labours-alternative-models-of-ownership-report/|title=Labour's Alternative Models of Ownership Report|date=2017-06-11|work=New Socialist.|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref>\n\nDuring his response to the 2015 [[Autumn Statement]] in which he accused George Osborne of \"sheer economic illiteracy\", McDonnell highlighted that the government was \"selling off at least \u00a35,000,000,000 worth of our own assets\" to foreign investors, emphasising [[China]].<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell quotes Chairman Mao in Spending Review attack|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34925962|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> To make this point he quoted from a copy of Chairman [[Mao Zedong]]'s ''[[Little Red Book]]'' and then threw it across the despatch box towards the Conservative front bench. A clearly amused Chancellor Osborne, responded by quipping that it was McDonnell's own signed copy.<ref name=\"Telegraph-12016384\">{{Cite news|title=John McDonnell quotes from Mao's Communist Little Red Book during Autumn Statement speech|last=Wilkinson|first=Michael|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=25 November 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/autumn-statement/12016384/John-McDonnell-quotes-from-Maos-Communist-Little-Red-Book-during-Autumn-Statement-speech.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126010819/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/autumn-statement/12016384/John-McDonnell-quotes-from-Maos-Communist-Little-Red-Book-during-Autumn-Statement-speech.html|archivedate=26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_2015-11-25\">{{Cite news|title=John McDonnell under fire for quoting Mao Zedong in Commons|last=Mason|first=Rowena|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 November 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/25/john-mcdonnell-mao-zedong-little-red-book-george-osborne|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125221618/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/25/john-mcdonnell-mao-zedong-little-red-book-george-osborne|archivedate=25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September 2016, he was appointed to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] and may therefore use the title ''[[The Right Honourable]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/List-of-Business-12-Oct-16-Part-1.pdf|title=Orders of the Privy Council for October 2016|date=12 October 2016|website=Privy Council|publisher=The Privy Council of the United Kingdom|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Parliamentary Launch of the British Sikh Report 2018 with the Rt Hon John McDonnell MP.jpg|thumb|McDonnell with members of the [[Sikhism in the United Kingdom|British Sikh]] community in April 2018]]\nIn the aftermath of the [[Grenfell Tower fire]], McDonnell said those who died in it were \"murdered\" by political decisions, arguing \"The decision to close fire stations and to cut 10,000 fire fighters and then to freeze their pay for over a decade contributed to those deaths inevitably\".<ref name=\"bbcgrenfell\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40401314 John McDonnell: Grenfell victims 'murdered by political decisions'] ''[[BBC]]''</ref> The use of the word \"murder\" was questioned by some of his colleagues as well as the Conservative Party, with [[Jim Fitzpatrick (politician)|Jim Fitzpatrick]], leader of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Fire Safety suggesting it was \"premature\" to draw conclusions about what caused the deaths.<ref name=\"bbcgrenfell\" />\n\nMcDonnell said that Grenfell \"symbolised for many everything that's gone wrong in this country since austerity was imposed upon us\" and used it to highlight pay cuts across the public sector, arguing that Conservatives praise the emergency services \"every time there's a tragedy\" while cutting jobs and wages.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/01/jeremy-corbyn-to-speak-at-london-anti-austerity-march Corbyn tells anti-austerity demo he's 'determined to force new election'] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/03/damning-government-report-shows-scale-of-public-sector-pay-cuts Damning government report shows depth of public sector pay cuts] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nMcDonnell sparked controversy when he joked that Conservative politician [[Esther McVey]] should be [[Lynching|lynched]] and described her as a \"stain on humanity.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-lynching-personal-abuse-jeremy-corbyn-esther-mcvey-labour-conference-a7328876.html John McDonnell defends comments about Tory minister being 'lynched'], the Independent, 25 September 2016</ref> He insisted that he was quoting a constituent speaking at a public meeting convened to oppose McVey's policies on benefits and did not endorse the sentiment.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/john-mcdonnell-refuses-apologise-repeating-11888475.amp John McDonnell refuses to apologise for repeating 'lynch Esther McVey' comments], ''The Mirror'', 21 January 2018</ref> The [[Leader of the House of Commons]], [[Andrea Leadsom]], called the remark \"truly evil.\"<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mcdonnells-lynching-rant-condemned-as-truly-evil-jpmmkzq5q McDonnell\u2019s lynching rant condemned as \u2018truly evil\u2019] ''The Sunday Times'', 15 January 2018</ref>\n\nMcDonnell has said: \"I will be the first socialist Labour Chancellor\".<ref>{{cite web|title=John McDonnell: 'I will be the first socialist Labour Chancellor'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-first-socialist-labour-chancellor-corbyn-quit-inevitable-a7722271.html|website=Mirror|date=7 May 2017}}</ref> McDonnell in his Who\u2019s Who posted one of his lobbies as \u201cfermenting [sic] the overthrow of capitalism\u201d.<ref name=capitalism1 /> In 2018, McDonnell claimed that he \"wants to \u201coverthrow capitalism\u201d and replace it with a \"socialist society\"\". He also insisted Venezuela's economic problems were because it was no longer a socialist country.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/05/20/labour-shadow-chancellor-john-mcdonnell-says-job-overthrow-capitalism/ Labour shadow Chancellor John McDonnell says his job is to overthrow capitalism and replace it with a 'socialist society'] Daily Telegraph, 20 May 2018</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, McDonnell said he would only back a second referendum on the European Union if the option to remain is not present.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/24/mcdonnell-new-brexit-referendum-should-not-include-remain-option</ref> He also agreed with shadow international trade secretary Barry Gardiner, when he suggested a second referendum could lead to social unrest.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/24/mcdonnell-backs-claims-second-brexit-referendum-risks-social-unrest</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, McDonnell sparked controversy when he referred to the former Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] as a \"villain.\" Writing on Twitter, [[Boris Johnson]] said: \"JM should be utterly ashamed of his remarks and withdraw them forthwith.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Winston Churchill: Theresa May says she has portrait of wartime PM in her study amid row over John McDonnell comments |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/winston-churchill-theresa-may-john-mcdonnell-villain-labour-tonypandy-miners-a8779111.html |work=The Independent |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring a comprehensive interview conducted by former Labour Party member [[Alastair Campbell]] for British ''[[GQ]]'' in October 2019, McDonnell stated his disapproval of the former's expulsion from the party and indicated he would support his return. He also expressed his own view that the next party leader should be female, and that the party should employ [[positive discrimination]] to aid that prospect if Jeremy Corbyn were to lose the next general election. When asked to name any current [[Tory]] politician whom he respected, he declined, subsequently stating that he \"can't forgive any of them\". Campbell followed up by asking the same question about any historic Tories, to which McDonnell replied \"No\".<ref>{{Citation|title=John McDonnell: Labour should have a female leader if Jeremy Corbyn loses next election {{!}} British GQ|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joo4w_BwEJs|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nUpon the election of [[Keir Starmer]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], McDonnell stood down as Shadow Chancellor, he was succeeded by [[Anneliese Dodds]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=johnmcdonnellMP |author=John McDonnell MP |number=1246373038922379264 |date = 4 April 2020 |title=As I step down as Shadow Chancellor I want to thank all those party members and supporters who have sustained us through the last years with their solidarity. It\u2019s been a privilege and honour to serve our movement. Solidarity.}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcDonnell has two daughters from his first marriage, which ended in 1985,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/sep/26/labourleadership.labour|title=Honest John|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Ronan|last=Bennett|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK}}</ref> and a son<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,1820366,00.html|title=Who is John McDonnell?|date=14 July 2006|accessdate=10 January 2007|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last=Mulholland|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK}}</ref> from his second marriage to Cynthia Pinto in 1995.<ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\"/>\n\nIn 2013, McDonnell suffered a heart attack and was forced to take time off work.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/15/john-mcdonnell-unreconstructed-on-the-left-but-with-allies-on-the-right|title=John McDonnell: unreconstructed on the left, but with allies on the right|first=Robert|last=Booth|date=15 September 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite being raised as a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] and attending a [[minor seminary]], McDonnell now identifies as an [[Atheism|atheist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/11399/john-mcdonnell-acknowledges-debt-to-catholicism|title=John McDonnell acknowledges debt to Catholicism|last=enquiries@thetablet.co.uk|first=The Tablet-w|website=The Tablet|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n*[[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]]\n*[[Socialist Campaign Group]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|John McDonnell}}\n*[http://www.john-mcdonnell.net/ John McDonnell MP] ''official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = john-mcdonnell/178 | guardian = 3825/john-mcdonnell | publicwhip = John_Martin_McDonnell | theywork = john_martin_mcdonnell | bbc = 25474.stm }}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224050/http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/John%2BMcDonnell/ Website] at ePolitix\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060722113325/http://www.publicnotprivate.org.uk/ Public Services Not Private Profit]\n\n;Historical\n*{{UK MP links | hansard = mr-john-mcdonnell | hansardcurr = 1799 }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061117154447/http://www.john4leader.org.uk/ John4Leader] ''official 2007 Leader campaign website''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120306204241/http://www.john-mcdonnell.co.uk/ John McDonnell, Labour MP for Hayes & Harlington] ''official 2010 Leader campaign website''\n*{{YouTube|o6w03WO-HB8|John McDonnell MP, Rally Against Military Intervention in Iran and Syria, Stop The War Coalition}}\n*{{YouTube|t0tsnObvVHg|John McDonnell MP \u2013 Against Islamophobia}}\n*{{YouTube|0Asuqx_Gzec|John McDonnell MP \u2013 Speaking at Ceasefire Now demonstration in London}}\n*[http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=16245&st=17%3A37%3A24.8900000 Speech by John McDonnell during Modern Slavery Bill debate in the House of Commons]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Terry Dicks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]|years=1997\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Leslie]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]]|years=2015\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=''TBD''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Shadow Great Officers of State}}\n{{Shadow Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2007}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2010}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, John}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Birkbeck, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:British Marxists]]\n[[Category:British anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:British religious sceptics]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:British women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:English Marxists]]\n[[Category:English anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:English anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English republicans]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:International opponents of apartheid in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Greater London Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Great Yarmouth Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Joseph's College, Ipswich]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = John McDonnell\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n|image            = John McDonnell, 2016 Labour Party Conference 2.jpg\n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]]\n|leader           = [[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start       = 13 September 2015\n|term_end         = 4 April 2020\n|predecessor      = [[Chris Leslie]]\n|successor        = [[Anneliese Dodds]]\n|office1          = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]\n|term_start1      = 1 May 1997\n|term_end1        = \n|predecessor1     = [[Terry Dicks]]\n|successor1       = \n|majority1        = 9,261 (21.1%)\n|office2          = [[Greater London Council|Deputy Leader of the Greater London Council]]\n|leader2          = [[Ken Livingstone]] \n|predecessor2     = [[Illtyd Harrington]]\n|successor2       = [[Michael Ward (British politician)|Michael Ward]]\n|term_start2      = 7 May 1984\n|term_end2        = 7 May 1985\n|office3          = Member of [[Greater London Council]]<br />for Hayes and Harlington\n|term_start3      = 7 May 1981\n|term_end3        = 31 March 1986\n|leader3          = [[Horace Cutler]]<br/>[[Ken Livingstone]]\n|predecessor3     = A. H. S. Hull\n|successor3       = ''Council abolished''\n|majority3        = 4,346 (17.1%)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.election-demon.co.uk/glc/glchd.html|title=Greater London Council election results: Hillingdon|author=|date=|website=election-demon.co.uk|accessdate=11 September 2018}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n|birth_name       = John Martin McDonnell \n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1951|9|8|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Liverpool]], England\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|spouse           = {{marriage|Marilyn Jean Cooper|1971|1987|reason=div}}<br />{{marriage|Cynthia Marie Pinto|1995}}\n|children         = 3\n|party            = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|otherparty       = [[Socialist Campaign Group]]\n|education        = [[Great Yarmouth Grammar School]]<br />[[St Joseph's College, Ipswich]]<br />Burnley Technical College<ref name=BBC2015>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34245371 |title=A profile of John McDonnell \u2013 new shadow chancellor |publisher=BBC |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref>\n|alma_mater       = [[Brunel University London|Brunel University]] (BSc)<br />[[Birkbeck, University of London]] (MSc)\n|website          = {{url|https://www.john-mcdonnell.net/|Official website}}\n}}\n'''John Martin McDonnell''' (born 8 September 1951) is a British politician serving as the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]] since [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]. A member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], he served as [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]] in the [[Shadow Cabinet of Jeremy Corbyn]] from 2015 to 2020.\n\nHe served as chair of the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] in Parliament and [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]]; McDonnell also chaired the Public Services Not Private Profit Group. He is also parliamentary convenor of the Trade Union Co-ordinating Group of eight left-wing trade unions representing over half a million workers. McDonnell attempted to stand for the position of [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party leader]] following [[Tony Blair]]'s resignation in [[2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2007]], but failed to get enough nominations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6660565.stm |title=Brown will enter No 10 unopposed |work=[[BBC]] News |date=16 May 2007 |accessdate=16 May 2007}}</ref> He was a candidate for the party leadership again in [[2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2010]] following [[Gordon Brown]]'s resignation after Labour's [[2010 United Kingdom general election|electoral defeat]],<ref name=\"mirror1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/05/18/labour-mp-john-mcdonnell-to-stand-in-the-leadership-campaign-115875-22268136 |title=Labour MP John McDonnell to stand in the leadership campaign |work=Daily Mirror|date=16 May 2010|accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> but withdrew in favour of [[Diane Abbott]], feeling that he would be unable to secure enough nominations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://l-r-c.org.uk/news/story/john-mcdonnell-im-withdrawing-from-labour-leadership-race |title=I'm withdrawing from Labour leadership race |author=McDonnell, John |publisher=[[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]] |date=9 June 2010 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his election as Labour leader in [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2015]], [[Jeremy Corbyn]] appointed McDonnell as his Shadow Chancellor. Alongside Corbyn, McDonnell has been seen as a key figure on the left-wing of the party.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite book |author=Duncan Hall |title=A2 Government and Politics: Ideologies and Ideologies in Action |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KPhwAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA45 |publisher=Lulu.com |isbn=978-1-4477-3399-7 |pages=45\u201346|year=2011 }}{{self-published source|date=April 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}} As Shadow Chancellor, McDonnell pledged to increase spending on infrastructure and research, describing his vision for the economy as \"socialism with an [[iPad]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour wants 'socialism with an iPad' says McDonnell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34877475|year=2015|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcDonnell was born in [[Liverpool]] to a family with an [[Irish Catholic]] background.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joo4w_BwEJs</ref> He moved with his family to [[East Anglia]] when he was very young; his father became a bus driver and was a branch secretary of the [[Transport and General Workers' Union]].<ref name=BBC2015/><ref name=\"Bennett\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/sep/26/labourleadership.labour |title=Honest John |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 September 2006 |accessdate=14 September 2015 |author=Bennett, Ronan}}</ref> McDonnell attended [[Great Yarmouth High School|Great Yarmouth Grammar School]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatyarmouthmercury.co.uk/news/shadow-chancellor-shares-memories-of-growing-up-in-great-yarmouth-1-4820510|title=Shadow chancellor shares memories of growing up in Great Yarmouth|last=Dickson|first=Annabelle|website=Great Yarmouth Mercury|language=en|access-date=2019-09-09}}</ref> McDonnell began training to be a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|Catholic priest]], receiving a Local Authority grant to attend [[St Joseph's College, Ipswich]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Senior Prospectus|url=https://www.stjos.co.uk/senior/prospectus/senior-prospectus-pdf/ |website=St Joseph's College |accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> a [[Roman Catholicism|Roman Catholic]] boarding fee-paying [[independent school]] for boys (now co-educational), before eventually deciding against the vocation at the age of 15 or 16 as he \"basically discovered girlfriends, so celibacy wasn't going to be an option. I was also into politics.\"<ref name=\"MaguirePro\">{{cite news |last1=Maguire |first1=Kevin |title=John McDonnell, the self-made socialist |url=https://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/magazine/john-mcdonnell-socialist-kevin-maguire-profile |accessdate=11 March 2019 |work=Prospect Magazine |date=18 September 2018}}</ref> McDonnell is now irreligious, but refers to himself as a \"[[cultural Catholic]]\" and is a regular churchgoer.<ref name=\"MaguirePro\" />\n\nUpon leaving education, McDonnell held a series of unskilled jobs. After marrying his first wife, he studied for [[Advanced Level (UK)|A-level]]s at night school at [[Burnley]] [[Technical College]], and at the age of 23, he moved to [[Hayes, Hillingdon|Hayes]] in Greater London, attended [[Brunel University]], and earned a bachelor's degree in government and politics.<ref name=\"Brunel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.brunel.ac.uk/courses/undergraduate/politics-and-history-bsc |title=Politics and History BSc |publisher=[[Brunel University London]] |date=14 September 2015 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/static/vote2001/candidates/candidates/3/30804.stm|title=Candidate: John McDonnell |work=BBC News}}</ref> During this period, he helped his wife run a small children's home in Hayes, and was active on behalf of his local community and for [[National Union of Public Employees]]. After completing his master's degree in politics and sociology at [[Birkbeck, University of London]],<ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/polsoc/ |title=Department of Politics |publisher=Bbk.ac.uk |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref> he became a researcher and official with the [[National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain)|National Union of Mineworkers]] from 1977 to 1978, and later the [[Trades Union Congress]] from 1978 until 1982. From 1985 to 1987, McDonnell was head of the policy unit at [[Camden Borough Council]], then chief executive of the Association of London Authorities from 1987 to 1995, and the [[Association of London Government]] from 1995 until 1997.<ref>{{cite web |title=John McDonnell|url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/about-us/fellows/downloads/john-mcdonnell.pdf |website=bbk.ac.uk |publisher=Birkbeck, University of London |accessdate=10 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Greater London Council (1981\u20131986)==\nIn 1981, McDonnell was elected to the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) as the member for Hayes and Harlington. He became the GLC's chair of finance and deputy leader to [[Ken Livingstone]], who described him as having an \"absolute grasp for detail and every year he produced a balanced budget, no borrowing\". He was sacked by Ken Livingstone in 1985 over the [[Rate-capping rebellion|strategy to oppose rate-capping]]\u2014[[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s government had capped council rates (now called council tax), an action which the GLC had claimed, based on figures calculated by McDonnell, would lead to \u00a3135 million in cuts. However, Livingstone claimed in his autobiography to have found that the authority could actually still increase spending and cap the rates; Livingstone said that McDonnell had \u2018exaggerated\u2019 spending figures to support his case that the GLC had to ignore the rates cap, and that he confronted McDonnell, saying \"If these figures are right we\u2019re going to look like the biggest fucking liars since [[Joseph Goebbels|Goebbels]].\" McDonnell described Livingstone's account as \"complete fiction\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: John McDonnell |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/5345644.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=11 June 2007 |accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/15/john-mcdonnell-unreconstructed-on-the-left-but-with-allies-on-the-right</ref>\n\nIn an interview with [[Ronan Bennett]] for ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper, he described his role during this time as being \"to translate policies into concrete realities on the ground.\" He further discussed his performance by indicating, \"I was a fairly hard-nosed administrator. We set in train policies for which we were attacked from all sides but are now accepted as mainstream: large-scale investment in public services; raising the issue of Ireland and arguing for a dialogue for peace; equal opportunities; police accountability. We set up a women's committee, an ethnic minorities committee.\"<ref name=\"Bennett\"/>\n\n==After the GLC (1987\u20131997)==\nFollowing the abolition of the GLC, McDonnell was employed as head of the policy unit at [[Camden London Borough Council]]. In 1987, he became Chief Executive of the Association of London Authorities (eventually the [[Association of London Government]]), where he represented all the [[London boroughs]] in their relations with central government and Europe. Having previously unsuccessfully contested [[Hampstead and Highgate (UK Parliament constituency)|Hampstead and Highgate]] in [[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]], McDonnell fought for his home constituency of Hayes and Harlington at the [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992 general election]], but lost by 53 votes, after three recounts, to the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] incumbent, [[Terry Dicks]]. During the campaign, Dicks sued for [[libel]] over critical material in McDonnell's campaign leaflets; McDonnell settled and paid Dicks damages of \u00a315,000 plus legal costs of \u00a355,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.steveplatt.net/archive/newstatesman/johnmajor/majorpaperboy.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060504110127/http://www.steveplatt.net/archive/newstatesman/johnmajor/majorpaperboy.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 May 2006 |title=Would you sue your paper boy? |first=Steve |last=Platt |work=[[New Statesman]] |date=12 March 1993 |accessdate=1 November 2006 |df= }}</ref> McDonnell would later refer to Dicks as a \u2018stain\u2019 on the character of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and a stain on the Conservative Party, and a \u2018malignant creature\u2019 during his maiden parliamentary speech.<ref name=\"api.parliament.uk\">https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/commons/1997/jun/06/governance-of-london-1#1997-06-06T12:10:00Z</ref>\n\n==Member of Parliament (1997\u2013present)==\nWhen Terry Dicks then stood down, McDonnell became the MP for Hayes and Harlington at the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], with 62 per cent of the vote and a majority of over 14,000. He made his [[maiden speech]] in the House of Commons on 6 June 1997, where he notably launched a scathing attack against his predecessor, against parliamentary tradition.<ref name=\"api.parliament.uk\"/> He has been involved in several local community campaigns, including one opposing the expansion of [[Heathrow Airport]] and its impact on local communities. He opposed [[New Labour]] policies of the [[Iraq War]], [[foundation hospitals]], student [[top-up fees]], [[trust school]]s and [[anti-terror laws]]. When Ken Livingstone was elected [[Mayor of London]], as an independent in 2000, he appointed McDonnell to his cabinet with responsibility for local government in London.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2000/may/23/londonmayor.uk</ref>\n\n===Iraq War===\nMcDonnell voted against the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|2003 Iraq War]], stating in 2007:{{cquote|I have used every opportunity to oppose the government's alliance with [[George W. Bush|George Bush]] and the [[US occupation of Iraq|US-led military occupation of Iraq]] which has resulted in the deaths of over 655,000, caused untold human suffering, put at risk the territorial integrity of Iraq, destabilised the entire region, alienated our own Muslim communities and given a huge boost to international terrorism \u2013 just as we warned it would.<ref>{{cite news |title=How Labour's contenders see the war |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2007/feb/21/iraq.labour|date=21 February 2007|accessdate=13 September 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>|sign=|source=}} In October 2006, McDonnell was one of 12 Labour MPs to back [[Plaid Cymru]] and the [[Scottish National Party]]'s call for a [[Iraq Inquiry|parliamentary inquiry into the war in Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6104310.stm|title=Labour MPs who rebelled on Iraq|date=31 October 2006|accessdate=31 October 2006|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n===Irish Republican Army===\nIn May 2003, he made controversial comments about the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (IRA), saying:{{cquote|It's about time we started honouring those people involved in the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army campaign 1969\u201397|armed struggle]]. It was the bombs and bullets and sacrifice made by the likes of [[Bobby Sands]] that brought Britain to the negotiating table. The peace we have now is due to the action of the IRA.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/may/30/northernireland.devolution |title=MP's 'brave IRA' comments spark outrage |first=Tom |last=Happold |work=The Guardian |date=30 May 2003 |accessdate=28 July 2014 |location=London, UK}}</ref>}}\n\nThreatened with expulsion from the Labour Party, he went on to offer a rationale for his comments in an article written for ''The Guardian'' in June 2003 (\"Expulsion would be an odd reward for telling hard truths\"), stating:{{cquote|Let me be clear, I abhor the killing of innocent human beings. My argument was that republicans had the right to honour those who had brought about this process of negotiation which had led to peace. Having achieved this central objective now it was time to move on. The future for achieving the nationalists' goals is through the political process and in particular through the Northern Ireland Assembly elections ... Irish republicans have to face the fact that the use of violence has resulted in unforgivable atrocities. No cause is worth the loss of a child's life. No amount of political theory will justify what has been perpetrated on the victims of the bombing campaigns.<ref>{{cite web|last=McDonnell|first=John|title=Why I stood up for Bobby Sands|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2003/jun/03/northernireland.labour|website=The Guardian|date=3 June 2003|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nIn his study at Hayes, McDonnell has a plaque presented to him by [[Gerry Kelly]] dedicated to the \"H-Block Martyrs 1981\", referring to those who died during the [[1981 Irish hunger strike]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/mcdonnell|work=Financial Times}}</ref> A spokesman for McDonnell said the plaque \"merely commemorates the peaceful protest in prison, not the prior actions of those involved\".<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell defends plaque honouring IRA 'martyrs' in his office|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/northern-ireland-assembly/news/93285/john-mcdonnell-defends-plaque-honouring|work=PoliticsHome.com|date=2 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Yorke|first1=Harry|title=John McDonnell continues to display a plaque to IRA terrorists in his study, it emerges|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/03/02/john-mcdonnell-continues-display-plaque-ira-terrorists-study/|work=The Telegraph|date=2 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a report in ''[[The Times]]'' published in November 2015, McDonnell in 1985 made similar comments at a Labour Committee on Ireland meeting, before the start of the Northern Ireland peace process. The ''Deptford Mercury'' asserted at the time that McDonnell had suggested there was a role for \"the ballot, the bullet and the bomb\" in achieving a United Ireland, and joked about \"[[kneecapping]]\" the \"gutless wimp\" Labour councillors who had declined to join the meeting.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Dominic |title=McDonnell gave his backing to the IRA's bomb campaign |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/politics/article4625106.ece |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Times |date=27 November 2015}} {{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, McDonnell apologised on ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' for any offence caused by his remarks on the IRA. However, contrary to what he had said 12 years previously, he now maintained that his remarks in 2003 had been an attempt to persuade republicans to support the peace process and to afford the IRA the opportunity to disarm without humiliation stating: \"There was a real risk of the Republican movement splitting and some of them continuing the armed process.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/18/john-mcdonnell-apologises-for-ira-comment-labour|title=John McDonnell apologises 'from the bottom of my heart' for IRA comment|last=Watt|first=Nicholas|last2=Gayle|first2=Damien|date=17 September 2015|website=The Guardian|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Groups and campaigns in Parliament===\nMcDonnell is a leading member of several all-party groups within Parliament, including groups representing individual trade unions, such as the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]] (PCS), the [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers]] (RMT), the [[Fire Brigades Union]] (FBU), the [[National Union of Journalists]] (NUJ) and justice unions such as [[Napo (trade union)|NAPO]]. He is also a leading member of groups on a wide range of issues such as Britain's Irish community, the [[Punjabi people|Punjabi]] community, [[endometriosis]], and [[Kenya]]. McDonnell is a member of the Labour Land Campaign, which advocates introducing a [[land value tax]].<ref>[http://www.labourland.org/ Labour Land Campaign website], labourland.org. Retrieved 21 October 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john-mcdonnell.net/about_john_mcdonnell|title=John McDonnell}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell chairs the [[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]] (LRC), a left-wing group of Labour activists, local parties, trade unions and MPs that campaigns for the adoption of a raft of socialist policies by the Labour Government. The group was founded on Saturday, 3 July 2004, and currently has more than 800 members and 90 affiliates. He also chairs the Public Services Not Private Profit, an anti-privatisation campaign that brings together sixteen trade unions and several campaigning organisations, such as the [[World Development Movement]], Defend Council Housing and the [[National Pensioners Convention]]. An [[early day motion]] in support of the campaign attracted more than ninety MPs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edmi.parliament.uk/EDMi/EDMDetails.aspx?EDMID=30421&SESSION=875 |title=Early Day Motion |date=29 March 2006 |accessdate=1 November 2006}}</ref> The campaign held a mass rally and lobby of Parliament on 27 June 2006, which was attended by more than 2,000 trade unionists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/publicservices/story/0,,1807050,00.html |title=Campaigners demand halt to privatisation |first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne |last=Mulholland |date=27 June 2006 |accessdate=1 November 2006 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref>\n\n===Economic policy===\nIn 2006, McDonnell said that \"[[Karl Marx|Marx]], [[Vladimir Lenin|Lenin]] and [[Leon Trotsky|Trotsky]]\" were his \"most significant\" intellectual influences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Labour's manifesto is more Keynesian than Marxist|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/june2017/2017/05/labours-manifesto-more-keynesian-marxist|year=2017}}</ref> Footage emerged of McDonnell in 2013 talking about the [[financial crisis of 2007\u20132008]] and stating, \"I've been waiting for this for a generation! We\u2019ve got to demand systemic change. Look, I\u2019m straight, I\u2019m honest with people: I\u2019m a [[Marxism|Marxist]].\"<ref name=marxist1>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell: I was joking when I celebrated the 2008 economic crash|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-video-labour-marxist-economic-crash-jeremy-corbyn-a7309651.html|quote=It was a joke. I also said, The bankers have done more to undermine capitalism than any of the Socialist Worker Party's activities in the last forty years.' I think it was taken as a joke, and if you listen to the tape, people fell about laughing as a result.|year=2016|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> He was accused of celebrating the financial crisis of 2007\u20132008; McDonnell denied the allegation and claimed he was \"joking\".<ref name=marxist1 /> During an interview with [[Andrew Marr]] when the footage was played and McDonnell was asked, \"Are you a Marxist?\", he replied: \"I believe there's a lot to learn from reading ''[[Capital: Critique of Political Economy|Kapital]]'', yes of course there is, and that's been recommended not just by me but many others, mainstream economists as well.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Marx Brothers: Jeremy Corbyn joins John McDonnell in praising Communist icon's work|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/08/marx-brothers-jeremy-corbyn-joins-john-mcdonnell-praising-communist/|website=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 May 2017}}</ref> In 2018, McDonnell attended the Marx 200 conference, where he said, \"Marxism is about the freedom of spirit, the development of life chances, the enhancement of democracy.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=How John McDonnell is leading the surprise rebirth of British Marxism|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2018/05/how-john-mcdonnell-leading-surprise-rebirth-british-marxism|year=2018|accessdate=3 June 2019}}</ref> In 2019, McDonnell during an interview stated that Marx\u2019s ''Kapital'' is \u201cone of the important analyses of the modern capitalist system.\u201d<ref name=capitalism1>{{cite web|title=John McDonnell interview: why capitalism is on borrowed time|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/john-mcdonnell-interview-why-capitalism-is-on-borrowed-time-623x8tz9w|newspaper=The Times|year=2019}}</ref>\n\n====Public services====\nMcDonnell has consistently opposed the privatisation of public services and chaired the Public Services not Private Profit Campaign launched in 2006 and supported by sixteen trade unions linking up with students, pensioners, health campaigners and the [[World Development Movement]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pcs.org.uk/news/news-archive/public-services-not-private-profit|title=Public services not private profit|work=Public and Commercial Services Union|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbu.org.uk/circular/2006hoc0358dm/re-public-services-not-private-profit-campaign|title=re: Public services not private profit campaign|website=Fire Brigades Union|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tssa.org.uk/en/Your-union/Your-company/company-headlines.cfm/public-services-not-private-profit-1|title=Public Services Not Private Profit|last=Fidler|first=Sue|website=TSSA|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell is \"not supportive of PFI schemes\",<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060208/halltext/60208h03.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 8 Feb 2006 (pt 3) |last=Westminster |first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> declaring that he has \"opposed every PFI scheme that was proposed\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110324/debtext/110324-0003.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 Mar 2011 (pt 0003)|last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> In 2006, during the parliamentary debate on the [[Budget resolution|Budget Resolutions]], McDonnell warned against [[Public\u2013private partnership|public-private finance initiatives]] (PFIs), calling for an inquiry:<blockquote>There are numerous examples. I refer hon. Members to the work of Alison Pollock<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/allysonpollock |title=Allyson Pollock |website=The Guardian |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref> and to the publications by [[Unison (trade union)|Unison]] in recent months, which contain example after example in the public services, health and education where PFI has been used to exploit the public purse, has failed to deliver and has delivered large bonuses and profits to individual company directors. That is why I regret that the Chancellor is going along that line. I would welcome a Government inquiry into PFI, which would probably echo the work done by the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] on individual PFI schemes, which has demonstrated their lack of deliverability and cost effectiveness.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200506/cmhansrd/vo060322/debtext/60322-22.htm |title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 22 Mar 2006 (pt 22) |last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Tax transparency====\nThroughout his time in [[Parliament]], McDonnell has championed the cause of tax justice, hosting the Parliamentary launch of the [[Tax Justice Network]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bccconference.co.uk/speakers/john-mcdonnell-mp/ |title=Rt Hon John McDonnell MP \u2013 BCC Conference 2018 |website=www.bccconference.co.uk |language=en-GB |access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, McDonnell worked with William Campbell-Taylor and Maurice Glasman, who challenged a parliamentary bill concerned with the City of London Corporation in relation to alleged tax avoidance:<blockquote>Apart from a couple of brave, independent-minded Labour MPs, notably John McDonnell, nobody supported Glasman and Campbell-Taylor to challenge the bill. Such is the fear that the corporation inspires in parliament.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newstatesman.com/economy/2011/02/london-corporation-city | title=The tax haven in the heart of Britain |work=newstatesman|accessdate=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Bank regulations====\nDuring the 2011 Budget Resolutions, McDonnell highlighted his long-term consistent work calling for better regulation of the banking and finance sector:<blockquote>We seem to forget that the cause of that crisis was the cause of this crisis\u2014speculation by the banks and other speculators and, yes, a Government who failed to regulate. I have to say, however, that when a number of Members called for bank regulation in this House, there was an element of quietude on all sides. I remember fighting for four years, in almost a solitary capacity, to secure the passage of the City of London (Ward Elections) Bill at a time when we were pressing for regulation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201011/cmhansrd/cm110324/debtext/110324-0003.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Debates for 24 Mar 2011 (pt 0003)|last=Westminster|first=Department of the Official Report (Hansard), House of Commons |website=publications.parliament.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-03-28}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n====Anti-austerity====\nIn February 2013, McDonnell was among those who supported the [[People's Assembly Against Austerity]] in a letter published by ''The Guardian'' newspaper.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/feb/05/people-assembly-against-austerity People's Assembly opening letter], ''The Guardian'', 5 February 2013.</ref>\n\n===Heathrow Airport expansion===\n[[File:John McDonnell Grow Heathrow at Court-4.jpg|thumb|McDonnell with opponents of the Heathrow Airport expansion outside Central London County Court, 2012]]\nMcDonnell has been a vocal opponent of plans to [[Expansion of Heathrow Airport|expand Heathrow Airport]] with a third runway\u2014the proposed site lies within his constituency. During a debate on the expansion of the airport on 15 January 2009, he was [[Suspension in the UK parliament|suspended]] for five days by Deputy Speaker [[Alan Haselhurst]] after disrupting Commons proceedings. McDonnell picked up the [[ceremonial mace]] and placed it down on an empty bench in the Commons while shouting that the lack of a vote on the third runway was \"a disgrace to the democracy of this country.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7830937.stm|title=MP suspended after mace protest|publisher=BBC|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=15 January 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jan/15/heathrow|title=Labour MP suspended from Commons over Heathrow protest|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|work=The Guardian|publisher=[[Guardian News and Media]]|date=15 January 2009|accessdate=15 January 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref>\n\n===Armed police and MI5===\nIn 2015, McDonnell's name appeared on a letter calling for the armed police and [[MI5]] to be disbanded. He claimed that he had not signed the letter, which was produced by the Socialist Campaign for a Labour Victory (SCLV), but he was photographed holding a copy of the letter, although he later said that he did not know that the demand was on the letter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/12005431/John-McDonnell-signed-letter-calling-for-MI5-and-armed-police-to-be-disbanded.html|title=John McDonnell signed letter calling for MI5 and armed police to be disbanded|first=Kate|last=McCann|date=19 November 2015|publisher=|accessdate=11 September 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/19/john-mcdonnell-denies-backing-call-to-end-mi5-and-disarm-police|title=John McDonnell denies backing call to end MI5 and disarm police|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|first2=Frances|last2=Perraudin|date=19 November 2015|website=the Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==2007 Labour leadership campaign==\n{{main|2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)}}\nOn 14 July 2006, McDonnell announced his intention to stand for leadership of the Labour Party when [[Tony Blair]] announced the date of his resignation. He called for \"a challenge to the present political consensus\", and, \"a real Labour government based upon the policies that our supporters expect from us\". McDonnell said he would like to see a return to the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]'s more traditional areas.\n\nInitially, McDonnell and [[Michael Meacher]] were the two candidates representing the left wing of the party. McDonnell's campaign concentrated on grassroots efforts, which earned him an endorsement from the [[Trades Union Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.john4leader.org.uk/latestnews/0016.html|title=John McDonnell MP: Another World Is Possible|publisher=John4leader.org.uk |accessdate=28 May 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907233203/http://www.johnmcdonnell.org.uk/latestnews/0016.html |archivedate=7 September 2008}}</ref> In a [[YouGov]] opinion poll of more than 1,100 Labour Party members asking their preferred choice in the leadership contest, McDonnell received 9% support, and was ranked second to [[Chancellor of the Exchequer|Chancellor]] [[Gordon Brown]], who led with 80% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=David |last2=Isabel |first2=Oakeshott |title=Blair under pressure as Labour faces election rout |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1720004.ece |accessdate=28 May 2019 |newspaper=[[The Times]] |date=29 April 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014081917/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article1720004.ece |archivedate=14 October 2008}}</ref> Declared supporters included [[Diane Abbott]], [[Tony Benn]], and [[Ann Cryer]]. In total, eleven Labour MPs declared their support on McDonnell's campaign website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.john4leader.org.uk/endorsements.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070328215354/http://www.john4leader.org.uk/endorsements.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=28 March 2007 |title=John McDonnell MP: Another World Is Possible |publisher=John4leader.org.uk |accessdate=20 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nLabour Party rules require candidates to be nominated by 12.5% of Labour MPs (45 out of a total of 355 in 2007). [[Gordon Brown]] received 313 (88.2%) nominations, while McDonnell failed to collect the 45 nominations required to proceed to the Electoral College. As the only nominated candidate, Gordon Brown was declared leader by the NEC.\n\n==2010 Labour leadership campaign==\n{{main|2010 Labour Party leadership election (UK)}}\nOn 18 May 2010, news broke that McDonnell wanted to stand in the Labour Party leadership election, to be held following the resignation of Gordon Brown, and would announce it the following day at the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]] conference in Brighton. McDonnell noted that it would be \"difficult\" to get the 33 nominations needed from the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]] required to stand in the election.<ref name=\"mirror1\"/>\n\nDuring a hustings for the [[GMB Union]] on 7 June, McDonnell was asked what single act he would do to improve the world if he could travel back to the 1980s. His off-the-cuff reply was that \"I was on the GLC that [[Margaret Thatcher|Mrs. Thatcher]] abolished, I worked for the NUM and we had the NUM strike, I think I would assassinate Thatcher\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10263076 |title=John McDonnell apologises for Thatcher 'joke' offence |work=BBC News |date=8 June 2010|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulholland |first1=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last2=Stratton |first2=Allegra |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/jun/07/john-mcdonnell-assassinate-thatcher-joke |title=John McDonnell jokes that he would have liked to have assassinated Thatcher |work=The Guardian |date=7 June 2010 |accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref> Conservative MP [[Conor Burns]] told the BBC that \"[it was] very distasteful\" and \"a very silly remark\". McDonnell told the BBC: \"I'm sorry if I have caused offence to anyone. It was a joke and in that audience it was taken as a joke ... it was taken out of context, I can see if people are upset about that and if I have caused offence to anyone of course I apologise\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/7808953/John-McDonnell-says-he-would-like-to-assassinate-Margaret-Thatcher.html|title=John McDonnell says he would like to 'assassinate' Margaret Thatcher|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 June 2010|accessdate=9 June 2010|location=London, UK}}</ref><ref name=BBCDP_8June2010>{{cite news|title=BBC Daily Politics|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/the_daily_politics/8728299.stm|accessdate=21 October 2015|date=8 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nBy 9 June 2010, the deadline for nominations, he had secured only 16 nominations and withdrew from the contest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://l-r-c.org.uk/news/story/john-mcdonnell-im-withdrawing-from-labour-leadership-race |title=John McDonnell: I'm withdrawing from Labour leadership race 9th June 2010 |publisher=L-r-c.org.uk |accessdate=11 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer (2015\u20132020)==\n[[File:Jeremy Corbyn and John McDonnell, 2016 Labour Party Conference.jpg|thumb|McDonnell after giving his 2016 Labour Party Conference speech, with Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]]]]\nMcDonnell was one of the thirty-six Labour MPs to nominate [[Jeremy Corbyn]] (who was elected as Labour leader with 59.5% of the vote) as a candidate in the [[2015 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|Labour leadership election of 2015]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/2015/06/who-nominated-who-2015-labour-leadership-election|title=Who nominated who for the 2015 Labour leadership election?|work=New Statesman}}</ref> McDonnell managed Corbyn's leadership campaign, and he was appointed Shadow Chancellor in September 2015.<ref>{{cite news|first1=Rowena|last1=Mason|first2=Patrick|last2=Wintour|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/13/jeremy-corbyn-shadow-cabinet-andy-burnham-labour|title=John McDonnell appointed shadow chancellor in Corbyn's new frontbench|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London, UK|date=13 September 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an article in ''The Guardian'' in the previous month, he set out the economic principles that a Corbyn government would follow:{{quote|Let me make it absolutely clear that Labour under Jeremy Corbyn is committed to eliminating the deficit and creating an economy in which we live within our means. ... We accept that cuts in public spending will help eliminate the deficit, but our cuts won't be to the middle-and low-income earners and certainly not to the poor ... alongside deficit elimination, the Corbyn campaign is advocating a fundamental reform of our economic system. This will include the introduction of an effective regulatory regime for our banks and financial sector; a full-blown [[Glass\u2013Steagall Legislation|Glass-Steagall]] system to separate day-to-day and investment banking; legislation to replace short-term shareholder value with long-term sustainable economic and social responsibilities as the prime objective of companies; radical reform of the failed auditing regime; the extension of a wider range of forms of company and enterprise ownership and control including public, [[co-operative]] and stakeholder ownership; and the introduction of a financial transactions tax to fund the rebalancing of our economy towards production and manufacturing.<ref name=\"Comment\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/aug/11/jeremy-corbyn-close-deficit-poor-labour-economy|title=Jeremy Corbyn would clear the deficit \u2013 but not by hitting the poor|work=The Guardian|date=11 August 2015|accessdate=14 September 2015|author=McDonnell, John}}</ref>}}\n\nMcDonnell's first speech as Shadow Chancellor was at the 2015 Labour Party conference in [[Brighton]]. In the speech, he set out Labour's thinking and priorities in key areas, as well as encouraging Labour MPs who had refused to serve under Corbyn to return.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34378290 |title=Labour's John McDonnell: Another world is possible |work=BBC News |date=28 September 2015 |accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe surprised many by calling upon Labour MPs to back [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] Chancellor [[George Osborne]]'s Fiscal Charter, arguing that supporting the proposed deficit reduction framework showed Labour's commitment to \"living within their means.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell: Labour will match Osborne and live within our means|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/sep/25/john-mcdonnell-labour-will-match-osborne-and-live-within-our-means|accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=25 September 2015}}</ref> However, he reversed that call in October, citing his trip to visit former steelworkers at a recently closed plant in [[Redcar]] as the reason for not wanting to be associated with supporting government cuts.<ref>{{cite news |title=McDonnell says fiscal charter U-turn due to meeting Redcar families |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/oct/13/john-mcdonnell-says-fiscal-charter-u-turn-due-to-meeting-redcar-families |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=13 October 2015}}</ref> McDonnell repeated the word \"embarrassing\" five times in his Commons response to the U-turn,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Deacon |first1=Michael |title='Embarrassing! Embarrassing! Embarrassing!' Labour's John McDonnell sums up his own U-turn |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/labour/11932423/Embarrassing-Embarrassing-Embarrassing-Labours-John-McDonnell-sums-up-his-own-U-turn.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=14 October 2015}}</ref> adding that \"a bit of humility amongst politicians never goes amiss\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Morris |first1=Nigel |title=John McDonnell admits 'embarrassing' U-turn over key economic policy as new Labour leadership hit by first |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-admits-embarrassing-u-turn-over-key-economic-policy-as-new-labour-leadership-hit-by-a6694526.html |accessdate=27 November 2015 |work=The Independent |date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn a November speech ahead of Osborne's Spending Review, McDonnell pledged that a Labour government would spend 3.5% of GDP on infrastructure and fund research through an Innovation Policy Council, describing his vision for the economy as \"socialism with an [[iPad]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=John McDonnell to unveil 'socialism with an iPad' economic plan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/20/john-mcdonnell-to-unveil-socialism-with-an-ipad-economic-plan|accessdate=27 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=20 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dathan|first1=Matt|title=John McDonnell pledges 'socialism with an iPad' in a Jeremy Corbyn-led Britain|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-pledges-socialism-with-an-ipad-in-a-jeremy-corbyn-led-britain-a6742066.html|accessdate=27 November 2015|newspaper=Independent|date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nMcDonnell has explored ideas surrounding \"alternative models of ownership\", publishing a report on the subject in June 2017 and hosting a discussion conference in London in February 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/feb/10/john-mcdonnell-says-moving-services-to-public-hands-would-cost-nothing |title=John McDonnell says nationalising services would cost nothing |last=Association |first=Press |date=2018-02-10 |website=The Guardian |language=en |access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref> The report sets out the \"practicality and necessity of a shift to a variety of alternative forms of ownership and control of productive enterprises, including co-operatives, municipal and locally-led ownership forms, and ... new democratic forms of national ownership\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newsocialist.org.uk/labours-alternative-models-of-ownership-report/|title=Labour's Alternative Models of Ownership Report|date=2017-06-11|work=New Socialist.|access-date=2018-02-21}}</ref>\n\nDuring his response to the 2015 [[Autumn Statement]] in which he accused George Osborne of \"sheer economic illiteracy\", McDonnell highlighted that the government was \"selling off at least \u00a35,000,000,000 worth of our own assets\" to foreign investors, emphasising [[China]].<ref>{{cite news|title=John McDonnell quotes Chairman Mao in Spending Review attack|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34925962|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> To make this point he quoted from a copy of Chairman [[Mao Zedong]]'s ''[[Little Red Book]]'' and then threw it across the despatch box towards the Conservative front bench. A clearly amused Chancellor Osborne, responded by quipping that it was McDonnell's own signed copy.<ref name=\"Telegraph-12016384\">{{Cite news|title=John McDonnell quotes from Mao's Communist Little Red Book during Autumn Statement speech|last=Wilkinson|first=Michael|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=25 November 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/autumn-statement/12016384/John-McDonnell-quotes-from-Maos-Communist-Little-Red-Book-during-Autumn-Statement-speech.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126010819/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/autumn-statement/12016384/John-McDonnell-quotes-from-Maos-Communist-Little-Red-Book-during-Autumn-Statement-speech.html|archivedate=26 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_2015-11-25\">{{Cite news|title=John McDonnell under fire for quoting Mao Zedong in Commons|last=Mason|first=Rowena|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=25 November 2015|accessdate=27 November 2015|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/25/john-mcdonnell-mao-zedong-little-red-book-george-osborne|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151125221618/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/25/john-mcdonnell-mao-zedong-little-red-book-george-osborne|archivedate=25 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 September 2016, he was appointed to the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom]] and may therefore use the title ''[[The Right Honourable]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://privycouncil.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/List-of-Business-12-Oct-16-Part-1.pdf|title=Orders of the Privy Council for October 2016|date=12 October 2016|website=Privy Council|publisher=The Privy Council of the United Kingdom|accessdate=24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Parliamentary Launch of the British Sikh Report 2018 with the Rt Hon John McDonnell MP.jpg|thumb|McDonnell with members of the [[Sikhism in the United Kingdom|British Sikh]] community in April 2018]]\nIn the aftermath of the [[Grenfell Tower fire]], McDonnell said those who died in it were \"murdered\" by political decisions, arguing \"The decision to close fire stations and to cut 10,000 fire fighters and then to freeze their pay for over a decade contributed to those deaths inevitably\".<ref name=\"bbcgrenfell\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-40401314 John McDonnell: Grenfell victims 'murdered by political decisions'] ''[[BBC]]''</ref> The use of the word \"murder\" was questioned by some of his colleagues as well as the Conservative Party, with [[Jim Fitzpatrick (politician)|Jim Fitzpatrick]], leader of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Fire Safety suggesting it was \"premature\" to draw conclusions about what caused the deaths.<ref name=\"bbcgrenfell\" />\n\nMcDonnell said that Grenfell \"symbolised for many everything that's gone wrong in this country since austerity was imposed upon us\" and used it to highlight pay cuts across the public sector, arguing that Conservatives praise the emergency services \"every time there's a tragedy\" while cutting jobs and wages.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/01/jeremy-corbyn-to-speak-at-london-anti-austerity-march Corbyn tells anti-austerity demo he's 'determined to force new election'] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/03/damning-government-report-shows-scale-of-public-sector-pay-cuts Damning government report shows depth of public sector pay cuts] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>\n\nMcDonnell sparked controversy when he joked that Conservative politician [[Esther McVey]] should be [[Lynching|lynched]] and described her as a \"stain on humanity.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-lynching-personal-abuse-jeremy-corbyn-esther-mcvey-labour-conference-a7328876.html John McDonnell defends comments about Tory minister being 'lynched'], the Independent, 25 September 2016</ref> He insisted that he was quoting a constituent speaking at a public meeting convened to oppose McVey's policies on benefits and did not endorse the sentiment.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/politics/john-mcdonnell-refuses-apologise-repeating-11888475.amp John McDonnell refuses to apologise for repeating 'lynch Esther McVey' comments], ''The Mirror'', 21 January 2018</ref> The [[Leader of the House of Commons]], [[Andrea Leadsom]], called the remark \"truly evil.\"<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mcdonnells-lynching-rant-condemned-as-truly-evil-jpmmkzq5q McDonnell\u2019s lynching rant condemned as \u2018truly evil\u2019] ''The Sunday Times'', 15 January 2018</ref>\n\nMcDonnell has said: \"I will be the first socialist Labour Chancellor\".<ref>{{cite web|title=John McDonnell: 'I will be the first socialist Labour Chancellor'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/john-mcdonnell-first-socialist-labour-chancellor-corbyn-quit-inevitable-a7722271.html|website=Mirror|date=7 May 2017}}</ref> McDonnell in his Who\u2019s Who posted one of his lobbies as \u201cfermenting [sic] the overthrow of capitalism\u201d.<ref name=capitalism1 /> In 2018, McDonnell claimed that he \"wants to \u201coverthrow capitalism\u201d and replace it with a \"socialist society\"\". He also insisted Venezuela's economic problems were because it was no longer a socialist country.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/05/20/labour-shadow-chancellor-john-mcdonnell-says-job-overthrow-capitalism/ Labour shadow Chancellor John McDonnell says his job is to overthrow capitalism and replace it with a 'socialist society'] Daily Telegraph, 20 May 2018</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, McDonnell said he would only back a second referendum on the European Union if the option to remain is not present.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/sep/24/mcdonnell-new-brexit-referendum-should-not-include-remain-option</ref> He also agreed with shadow international trade secretary Barry Gardiner, when he suggested a second referendum could lead to social unrest.<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/aug/24/mcdonnell-backs-claims-second-brexit-referendum-risks-social-unrest</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, McDonnell sparked controversy when he referred to the former Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]] as a \"villain.\" Writing on Twitter, [[Boris Johnson]] said: \"JM should be utterly ashamed of his remarks and withdraw them forthwith.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Winston Churchill: Theresa May says she has portrait of wartime PM in her study amid row over John McDonnell comments |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/winston-churchill-theresa-may-john-mcdonnell-villain-labour-tonypandy-miners-a8779111.html |work=The Independent |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring a comprehensive interview conducted by former Labour Party member [[Alastair Campbell]] for British ''[[GQ]]'' in October 2019, McDonnell stated his disapproval of the former's expulsion from the party and indicated he would support his return. He also expressed his own view that the next party leader should be female, and that the party should employ [[positive discrimination]] to aid that prospect if Jeremy Corbyn were to lose the next general election. When asked to name any current [[Tory]] politician whom he respected, he declined, subsequently stating that he \"can't forgive any of them\". Campbell followed up by asking the same question about any historic Tories, to which McDonnell replied \"No\".<ref>{{Citation|title=John McDonnell: Labour should have a female leader if Jeremy Corbyn loses next election {{!}} British GQ|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=joo4w_BwEJs|language=en|access-date=2019-10-12}}</ref>\n\nUpon the election of [[Keir Starmer]] as [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Leader of the Labour Party]], McDonnell stood down as Shadow Chancellor, he was succeeded by [[Anneliese Dodds]].<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=johnmcdonnellMP |author=John McDonnell MP |number=1246373038922379264 |date = 4 April 2020 |title=As I step down as Shadow Chancellor I want to thank all those party members and supporters who have sustained us through the last years with their solidarity. It\u2019s been a privilege and honour to serve our movement. Solidarity.}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcDonnell has two daughters from his first marriage, which ended in 1985,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2006/sep/26/labourleadership.labour|title=Honest John|date=26 September 2006|accessdate=26 September 2016|first=Ronan|last=Bennett|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK}}</ref> and a son<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politics.guardian.co.uk/labourleadership/story/0,,1820366,00.html|title=Who is John McDonnell?|date=14 July 2006|accessdate=10 January 2007|first=H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|last=Mulholland|work=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK}}</ref> from his second marriage to Cynthia Pinto in 1995.<ref name=\"BBC News Profile 2001\"/>\n\nIn 2013, McDonnell suffered a heart attack and was forced to take time off work.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2015/sep/15/john-mcdonnell-unreconstructed-on-the-left-but-with-allies-on-the-right|title=John McDonnell: unreconstructed on the left, but with allies on the right|first=Robert|last=Booth|date=15 September 2015|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite being raised as a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] and attending a [[minor seminary]], McDonnell now identifies as an [[Atheism|atheist]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetablet.co.uk/news/11399/john-mcdonnell-acknowledges-debt-to-catholicism|title=John McDonnell acknowledges debt to Catholicism|last=enquiries@thetablet.co.uk|first=The Tablet-w|website=The Tablet|language=en|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United Kingdom|Socialism}}\n*[[Labour Representation Committee (2004)|Labour Representation Committee]]\n*[[Socialist Campaign Group]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons category|John McDonnell}}\n*[http://www.john-mcdonnell.net/ John McDonnell MP] ''official constituency website''\n*{{UK MP links | parliament = john-mcdonnell/178 | guardian = 3825/john-mcdonnell | publicwhip = John_Martin_McDonnell | theywork = john_martin_mcdonnell | bbc = 25474.stm }}\n*{{Twitter}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224050/http://www.epolitix.com/EN/MPWebsites/John%2BMcDonnell/ Website] at ePolitix\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060722113325/http://www.publicnotprivate.org.uk/ Public Services Not Private Profit]\n\n;Historical\n*{{UK MP links | hansard = mr-john-mcdonnell | hansardcurr = 1799 }}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061117154447/http://www.john4leader.org.uk/ John4Leader] ''official 2007 Leader campaign website''\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120306204241/http://www.john-mcdonnell.co.uk/ John McDonnell, Labour MP for Hayes & Harlington] ''official 2010 Leader campaign website''\n*{{YouTube|o6w03WO-HB8|John McDonnell MP, Rally Against Military Intervention in Iran and Syria, Stop The War Coalition}}\n*{{YouTube|t0tsnObvVHg|John McDonnell MP \u2013 Against Islamophobia}}\n*{{YouTube|0Asuqx_Gzec|John McDonnell MP \u2013 Speaking at Ceasefire Now demonstration in London}}\n*[http://www.parliamentlive.tv/Main/Player.aspx?meetingId=16245&st=17%3A37%3A24.8900000 Speech by John McDonnell during Modern Slavery Bill debate in the House of Commons]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Terry Dicks]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Hayes and Harlington (UK Parliament constituency)|Hayes and Harlington]]|years=1997\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chris Leslie]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]]|years=2015\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=''TBD''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Shadow Cabinet}}\n{{Shadow Great Officers of State}}\n{{Shadow Chancellors of the Exchequer}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2007}}\n{{Labour Party leadership election, 2010}}\n{{London Labour Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonnell, John}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Birkbeck, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brunel University London]]\n[[Category:Anti-capitalists]]\n[[Category:Anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:British Marxists]]\n[[Category:British anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:British religious sceptics]]\n[[Category:British socialists]]\n[[Category:British women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Critics of the European Union]]\n[[Category:Democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:English Marxists]]\n[[Category:English anti-fascists]]\n[[Category:English anti\u2013Iraq War activists]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:English republicans]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:International opponents of apartheid in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Greater London Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People educated at Great Yarmouth Grammar School]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Joseph's College, Ipswich]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Liverpool]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Morganlinkhorn", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McDonnell"}
{"title_page": "Mass suicide in Demmin", "text_new": "{{Coord|53.905|13.049|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nOn 1 May 1945, hundreds of people [[mass suicide|killed themselves]] in the town of [[Demmin]], in the [[Province of Pomerania (1815\u20131945)|Province of Pomerania]] (now in [[Mecklenburg-Vorpommern]]), [[Germany]]. The suicides occurred during a mass panic that was provoked by atrocities committed by soldiers of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]], who had sacked the town the day before. Although death toll estimates vary, it is acknowledged to be the largest mass suicide ever recorded in Germany. The suicide was part of a [[Mass suicides in 1945 Nazi Germany|mass suicide wave]] amongst the population of Nazi Germany.\n\n[[Nazi Party|Nazi officials]], the police, the [[Wehrmacht]] and many citizens had left the town before the arrival of the Red Army, while thousands of [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|refugees from the East]] had also taken refuge in Demmin. Three Soviet negotiators were shot prior to the Soviet advance into Demmin and [[Hitler Youth]], amongst others, fired on Soviet soldiers once inside the town. The retreating Wehrmacht had blown up the bridges over the [[Peene]] and [[Tollense]] rivers, which enclosed the town to the north, west and south, thus blocking the Red Army's advance and trapping the remaining civilians. The Soviet units looted and burned down the town, and committed rapes and executions.\n\nNumerous inhabitants and refugees then killed themselves, with many families doing so together. Methods of suicides included drowning in the rivers, hanging, wrist-cutting, and shooting. Most bodies were buried in mass graves, and after the war, discussion of the mass suicide was taboo under the [[East Germany|East German]] [[Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands|Communist government]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Demmin Stadtplan.PNG|thumb|325px|[[Demmin]], enclosed by the [[Peene]] river in the north and west, and the [[Tollense]] river in the south. The bridges were blown up by the retreating [[Wehrmacht]], the [[Red Army]] approached the town from the east. Modified [[OpenStreetMap|OSM]] map.]]\nDemmin was a stronghold of the nationalistic organisations [[German National People's Party|DNVP]] and ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]'' in the [[Weimar Republic]]. Before 1933 there were boycotts of Jewish businesses, which drove away most of the Jews. The synagogue was sold in June 1938 to a furniture company, which is why it survives as a building today. In the [[Kristallnacht|riots of November 1938]] thousands gathered in the square in anti-Semitic demonstration.<ref>Artikel ''Demmin'' in: Irene Diekmann (Hg.), ''Wegweiser durch das j\u00fcdische Mecklenburg-Vorpommern'', Potsdam 1998, S. 99 ff, bes. S. 111 f</ref> In the last national elections to the Reichstag on 5 March 1933 the National Socialist Party won 53.7 percent of votes in Demmin.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Thomas |last=Scheck |title=Echt deutsch und national \u2013 Die vorpommersche Kleinstadt Demmin im Jahr 1933 |trans-title=Truly German and national \u2013 the West Pomeranian town of Demmin in the year 1933 |journal=Zeitgeschichte regional |issue=4/4 |year=2000 |pages=14\u201323 |language=German |url=http://aggb-katalog.de/vufind/Record/top569203163}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last weeks of [[World War II]], [[Mass suicides in 1945 Nazi Germany|tens of thousands of Germans killed themselves]], especially in territories occupied by the [[Red Army]].<ref name=lakotta>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German}}</ref> The German historian [[Udo Grashhoff]] and the German author [[Kurt Bauer]] wrote that the suicides occurred in two stages: in a first wave before the Red Army's arrival, in part due to a \"fear of the Russians\" spread by [[Nazi propaganda]],<ref name=Grashoff184>{{Cite book|title=In einem Anfall von Depression: Selbstt\u00f6tungen in der DDR |first=Udo |last=Grasshoff |language=German |page=184 |publisher=Ch. Links Verlag |year=2006 |isbn=978-3-86153-420-4}} Quote: \"Es handelte sich dabei zum Teil um eine Panikreaktion aus einer von der nationalsozialistischen Propaganda gesch\u00fcrten Angst vor den Russen; die Selbstt\u00f6tungswellen ereigneten sich aber zumeist in zwei Phasen. Den ersten von Angst und Panik bestimmten Selbstt\u00f6tungen folgte in vielen Orten eine zweite Selbstt\u00f6tungswelle, nachdem es zu Hinrichtungen, Pl\u00fcnderungen und massenhaften Vergewaltigungen durch die Besatzer gekommen war. Im mecklenburgischen Demmin zum Beispiel nahmen sich innerhalb von einer Woche von ca. 15000 Einwohnern etwa 700 das Leben.[15] [...] 15: Sch\u00e4tzungen der Zahl der Selbstt\u00f6tungen reichen von 700 bis 1200. Vgl Norbert Buske, Das Kriegsende in Demmin, Schwerin 1995, S. 44f.\" Translation: In part, this was a panic reaction, out of a fear of the Russians, fuelled by Nazi propaganda; For the most part, the suicides occurred in two waves. The first suicides, which were sparked by fear and panic, were, in many places, followed by a second wave of suicides, after executions, looting and mass rapes had occurred. For example, in the course of one week, some 700 of 15,000 inhabitants killed themselves in the Mecklenburgian town of Demmin.[15] [...] 15: Estimates of the number of suicides range from 700 to 1,200. Cf. Norbert Buske (1995), Das Kriegsende in Demmin, Schwerin, pp. 44\u201345.</ref> and \u2013 as in Demmin \u2013 in a second wave after the Red Army's arrival, triggered by executions, looting and mass rapes committed by Soviet soldiers.<ref name=Grashoff184/><ref name=Bauer533>{{Cite book| title=Nationalsozialismus: Urspr\u00fcnge, Anf\u00e4nge, Aufstieg und Fall|first=Kurt|last=Bauer|page=533|language=German|publisher=UTB|year=2005|isbn=978-3-8252-3076-0}} Quote: \"Im Anschlu\u00df an die Kampfhandlungen kam es immer wieder zu Massakern an der Zivilbev\u00f6lkerung und an Wehrmachtssoldaten, die sich ergeben hatten. Ausgedehnte Pl\u00fcnderungen und Raubz\u00fcge waren allt\u00e4gliche Begleiterscheinungen des Vormarsches der Roten Armee. Zum kollektiven Trauma wurden die massrenhaften Vergewaltigungen deutscher Frauen durch die russische Soldateska. [...] Von zwei Millionen Vergewaltigungsopfern in den von der Roten Armee besetzten deutschen Gebieten ist in der Literatur die Rede. Jede zehnte Frau d\u00fcrfte an den Folgen der Massenvergewaltigungen gestorben sein oder anschlie\u00dfend Suizid ver\u00fcbt haben. Massenselbstt\u00f6tungen von Menschen, die der Roten Armee nicht hatten entkommen k\u00f6nnen, waren ein weiteres, erschreckendes Ph\u00e4nomen in der Kriegsendphase. In der vorpommerschen Kleinstadt Demmin ver\u00fcbten in den ersten Maitagen 1945 in einer Massenpsychose an die 1000 Menschen Selbstmord, zumeist durch Ertr\u00e4nken.\" Translation: After the fighting, there were repeated massacres of civilians and Wehrmacht soldiers who had surrendered. Extensive looting and raids were every-day occurrences during the Red Army's advance. Mass rapes of German women by Russian soldiers became a pervasive trauma. Two million rape victims are mentioned by writings at the time. One in every ten women died of the mass rapes, or else committed suicide afterwards. These mass suicides of people who had not been able to escape the Red Army were another terrifying phenomenon in the final stage of the war. In the small West Pomeranian town of Demmin, some 1,000 people committed suicide during the first days of May 1945, in most cases by drowning themselves.</ref>\n\nIn 1945, Demmin had between 15,000<ref name=Grashoff184/> and 16,000 inhabitants.<ref name=vernier>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German}}</ref> Thousands of [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|refugees from the East]] were also in town, roughly doubling its population.<ref name=zimmer1>{{Cite web|url= https://www.ndr.de/kultur/geschichte/kriegsendedemmin102.pdf|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1}}</ref> In late April, when the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] drew closer ([[Battle of Berlin#North|Battle of Berlin]]), women, children and elderly men were forced to dig a {{convert|5|km|mi|adj=on}}-long anti-tank ditch east of the town.<ref name=vernier/> On 28 April, the German flight from the town began: the [[Nazi party]] functionaries left on confiscated fire engines, the hospital was evacuated, all the police departed, and a number of civilians fled.<ref name=vernier/>\n\nDemmin was reached by spearheads of the [[65th Army (Soviet Union)|Soviet 65th Army]]<ref>Batow, P.I.: ''\u041e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041e\u0434\u0435\u0440, \u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f 65-\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0439 \u0432 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 \u2013 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b \u2013 \u043c\u0430\u0439 1945 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.'' (Russian), museum Demmin, signature 10.629.</ref> and the [[1st Guards Tank Corps]] at noon on 30 April 1945.<ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> At the tower of the church, a white banner was hoisted.<ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> According to an eyewitness, three Soviet negotiators, one of them a German officer, approached the anti-tank ditch and promised to spare Demmin's civilian population from \"harassment\" and looting in the case of a surrender without fight.<ref name=zimmer1/> This eyewitness was then 19 years old, serving as a [[Wehrmacht|German soldier]], and lying in the anti-tank ditch.<ref name=zimmer1/> According to him, three shots were fired at the negotiators, who sank to the ground.<ref name=zimmer1/> The remaining [[Wehrmacht]] units,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> belonging to [[Army Group Weichsel]], and some [[Waffen-SS]],<ref name=vernier/> retreated through Demmin,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> and roughly about half an hour after the incident,<ref name=zimmer1/> blew up all bridges leading out of town behind them.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> By that time, Soviet units were already advancing through Demmin.<ref name=zimmer1/>\n\nThe destruction of the bridges prevented the Soviet from advancing westward<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> toward [[Rostock]], which they had planned to reach the same day.<ref name=zimmer1/> It also prevented the flight of the civilian population, who were trapped by the rivers surrounding the town.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> According to eyewitnesses, some \"fanatics,\" primarily [[Hitler Youth]],<ref name=lakotta/> shot at the Soviet soldiers,<ref name=zimmer1/> despite several white flags being hoisted on Demmin's buildings. Memorably, a Nazi loyalist schoolteacher, having slain his wife and children, launched a grenade from a [[panzerfaust]] on Soviet soldiers, before finally hanging himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German |quote=Studienrat Moldenhauer, ein Nazi-Mitl\u00e4ufer, erschoss seine Frau und seine drei Kinder, bevor er eine Panzerfaust auf die Russen abfeuerte und sich erh\u00e4ngte (Translation: Lecturer Moldenhauer, a Nazi follower, shot dead his wife and his three children prior to launching a panzerfaust grenade at the Russians and then hanging himself).}}</ref> According to the [[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] magazine, an eyewitness stated that the first Soviet soldier was shot near the hospital at 11:05 AM by someone running amok, apparently the aforementioned teacher, who had before told a neighbor that he had killed his wife and his children.<ref name=vernierquote>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German |quote='Der erste Russe wurde um f\u00fcnf nach elf vor dem roten Krankenhaus erschossen', erz\u00e4hlt der Demminer Uhrmacher Rolf-Dietrich Schultz. Damals, mit neun Jahren, ist er von einem Keller in der Treptower Stra\u00dfe aus Augenzeuge. Der Amoksch\u00fctze ist offenbar Studienrat Gerhard Moldenhauer. Der NSDAP-Mitl\u00e4ufer hatte einer Nachbarin erkl\u00e4rt: 'Ich habe eben meine Frau und meine Kinder erschossen, nun will ich noch ein paar Russen umlegen.' Ein Scharm\u00fctzel gibt es auch am Luisentor. Das alte Stadttor, zuletzt Treffpunkt der Hitlerjungen, beschie\u00dfen die Russen mit Panzergranaten. Dann herrscht \u2013 zun\u00e4chst \u2013 Ruhe. Die Exzesse beginnen noch am Abend (Translation: The first Russian was shot dead at five past eleven in front of the red hospital,' stated watchmaker Rolf-Dietrich Schultz from Demmin. Back then, aged nine, he was an eyewitness, watching from a cellar in Treptower Stra\u00dfe. The gunman was apparently Lecturer Gerhard Moldenhauer. The NSDAP follower had declared to a neighbour: 'I've just shot my wife and children, now I just want to pick off some Russians'. A skirmish also took place at Louisentor gate. The old towngate, which used to be a meeting point of the Hitler Youth, was being shelled with tank grenades by the Russians. Then, there was a \u2013 temporary \u2013 silence. The true violence started later that evening).}}</ref> A third eyewitness confirmed the identity of the amok gunman in a report by [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk]] and blamed him and other fanatics for causing the Soviet troops to retaliate with plundering the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-23|language=German|page=1}} Citing Demmin chronicler Hans-Gerhardt Quadt who was 14 at the time: \"Es gab Fanatiker, die auf vorbeiziehende Russen schossen, die sich das auch vorgenommen hatten. Ich nehme den Studienrat Gerhard Moldenhauer, der seiner Nachbarin sagte: \u201aIch habe eben meine Familie get\u00f6tet, jetzt lege ich noch einige Russen um und dann scheide ich selbst aus dem Leben.' Und so hat er das auch gemacht, und hat hiermit eine Schuld auf sich geladen, die nun nach sowjetischem Kriegsrecht dazu f\u00fchrte, dass Demmin drei Tage zur Pl\u00fcnderung freigegeben wurde. Demmin ist drei Tage zur Pl\u00fcnderung freigegeben und das bedeutete, wir z\u00fcnden die Stadt an und wir \u00fcben hier das Kriegsrecht aus. (lit.: There were fanatics who shot at Russians passing through and who were willing to do that. For example Lecturer Gerhard Moldenhauer who told his neighbour: 'I have just killed my family, now I'm going to pick off some Russians and then I'm going to pass away too.' And that he did and thereby he made himself guilty of causing three days of plundering in Demmin. According to Soviet martial law: 'Demmin may be plundered at will for three days' and that meant 'we'll burn the city and bring martial law upon them'\".)</ref> Then, it was \"quiet\" until the evening, when the atrocities started.<ref name=vernierquote/> Another incident is said to have happened on 1 May, when the local pharmacist hosted a \"victory party\" of Soviet officers, killing them with poisoned wine.<ref name=zimmer2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1252.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=2}}</ref> The [[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] magazine however dismissed that as a \"legend\"<ref name=vernier/> and also theologian and historian Norbert Buske concluded in a 1995 study that the story had been fabricated.<ref name=Buske>{{Cite book|title=Das Kriegsende in Demmin 1945. Berichte, Erinnerungen, Dokumente|first=Norbert|last=Buske|location=Schwerin|publisher=Helms|year=1995|series=Landeskundliche Hefte|isbn=3-931185-04-4|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet soldiers in turn were allowed to loot the town for a period of three days.<ref name=zimmer1/> They committed [[Rape during the occupation of Germany#Soviet troops|mass rapes]] of local women,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer2/> according to eyewitnesses, \"regardless of age\", and shot German men who spoke up against this practice.<ref name=zimmer2/> Furthermore, large areas of the town were set on fire, with nearly all of the center burning down completely.<ref name=zimmer2/> 80% of the town was destroyed within three days.<ref name=vernier/> Reportedly, Soviet soldiers had brushed the houses' walls with gasoline before setting them on fire, and stood guard three days to prevent extinguishing.<ref name=vernier/> Many of the soldiers committing the mass rapes, executions, and pillaging were reportedly drunk.<ref name=lakotta/> Already on 30 April, when the atrocities started in the evening, Soviet soldiers had looted both Demmin's cereal distilleries and several alcohol stores.<ref name=vernier/>\n\n==Suicides==\n[[File:Peene-in-Demmin-26-VIII-2007-07.jpg|thumb|The Peene river in Demmin in 2007]]\nThese events, along with the fear of atrocities stirred up by the [[Nazi propaganda]] before, caused a [[mass panic]] among the population.<ref name=lakotta/> Many local and refugee families killed themselves together.<ref name=zimmer2/> The suicides were either performed with guns, razor blades or poison, others hanged or drowned themselves in the [[Peene]] and [[Tollense]] rivers.<ref name=zimmer3>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1254.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=3}}</ref> Several mothers killed their children before killing themselves,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer3/> or walked into one of the rivers with a rock in a backpack and their babies in their arms.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some families died by walking into the rivers, tied together.<ref name=lakotta/> A local forester first shot three young children, then their mothers, then his wife and then himself, surviving as a blind man.<ref name=zimmer3/> In another recorded case, a daughter cut the wrists of her parents.<ref name=zimmer3/>\n\nNot every suicide case was completed.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some mothers who had drowned their children were unable to drown themselves thereafter.<ref name=zimmer3/> In other cases, doses of poison proved to be lethal for children, but not for their mothers.<ref name=zimmer3/> There were also cases where children survived attempted drownings.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some members who survived a first attempt at suicide killed themselves by other methods. A mother and her repeatedly raped daughter, for instance, died by hanging themselves in an attic, after repeatedly failing to drown themselves in the Peene river.<ref name=zimmer3/> Another mother who had poisoned and buried three of her four children before, tried to hang herself on an oak three times, only to be prevented to do so each time by Soviet soldiers.<ref name=lakotta/> There are further records of Soviet soldiers preventing suicides by retrieving people from the river and nursing cut wrists.<ref name=lakotta/> In another case, a grandfather forcibly took away a razor blade from a mother who was about to kill her children and herself after being raped by Soviet soldiers and hearing of the death of her husband.<ref name=lakotta/> After Soviet soldiers had raped a girl to death and shot her father, an aunt cut her daughter's and son's wrists as well as her own. The other women of the family committed suicide, only one aunt was able to save the grandmother.<ref name=lakotta/> One family survived, because the 15-year-old son persuaded his mother, who had become a rape victim, to abort her induced drowning, when she was already being dragged by the Tollense river.<ref name=lakotta/>\n\nDemmin's current chronicler, then 14 years old, recalls:<blockquote>My mother was also raped. And then, together with us and with neighbors, she hurried towards the Tollense river, resolutely prepared to jump into it. [...] My siblings [...] realized only much later that I had held her back, that I had pulled her out of what may be called a state of trance, to prevent her from jumping into the water. There were people. There was screaming. The people were prepared to die. Children were told: 'Do you want to live on? The town is burning. These and those are dead already. No, we do not want to live any more.' And so, people went mostly into the rivers. [...] That made even the Russians feel creepy. There are examples where Russians, too, tried to pull people out or hinder them. But these hundreds of people, they were unable to withhold. And the population here was extremely panicked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1}} Quote: \"[...] auch meine Mutter fiel der Vergewaltigung anheim. Und dann rannte sie mit uns und mit Nachbarn in Richtung Tollense und hatte den absoluten Vorsatz hineinzuspringen. [...] Meine Geschwister [...] die haben das auch erst viel sp\u00e4ter mitbekommen, dass ich meine Mutter zur\u00fcckgehalten habe, sie aus diesem - ja man k\u00f6nnte es Trance-Zustand nennen - gerissen habe, um sie daran zu hindern, nicht ins Wasser zu springen. Da waren Menschen. Es gab Schreie. Die Menschen waren bereit zu sterben. Kindern wurde gesagt: 'Wollt ihr noch leben? Die Stadt brennt. Die und die sind auch schon tot. Nein, wir wollen nicht mehr leben.' Und so sind die Menschen zumeist in die Fl\u00fcsse gegangen. [...] Das wurde auch den Russen unheimlich. Es gibt Beispiele, wo auch die Russen versucht haben, Menschen rauszuholen oder sie daran zu hindern. Aber die Hunderte von Menschen haben sie nicht hindern k\u00f6nnen. Und die Bev\u00f6lkerung hier war in einer riesigen Panik.\"</ref></blockquote>\n\nGisela Zimmer writes that many of the dead were buried in mass graves<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer4>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1256.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=4}}</ref> on the Bartholom\u00e4i graveyard.<ref name=\"zimmer4\"/> Some were buried in orderly graves on the initiative of relatives.<ref name=zimmer4/> Others were not buried, as their bodies were not retrieved from the rivers.<ref name=zimmer4/> More than 900 bodies were buried in the mass graves.<ref name=lakotta/> 500 of them were recorded on sheets of a warehouse accountant's book converted into a death register.<ref name=vernier/> Weeks after the mass suicide, bodies still floated in the rivers.<ref name=lakotta/> Clothes and other belongings of the drowned formed a border along the rivers' banks,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/> up to {{convert|2|m|ft}} wide.<ref name=vernier/>\n\n==Death toll==\n''[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]'' magazine (1995) quoted Norbert Buske as saying, \"We will have to assume more than 1,000 deaths.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German}} Citing Buske (1995): Das Kriegsende in Demmin. Quote: \"Wir werden von mehr als 1000 Toten auszugehen haben (lit.: we will have to assume a number of more than 1,000 dead).\"</ref> According to Goeschel (2009), with reference to Buske (1995), \"Some 700 to 1,000 people are said to have committed suicide directly after the arrival of the Red Army;\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Suicide in Nazi Germany|first=Christian|last=Goeschel|publisher=Oxford University Press US|year=2009|isbn=0-19-953256-7|pages=162, 205}}</ref> Grashoff (2006), using the same reference, stated that \"estimates of the number of suicides range from 700 to 1,200.\"<ref name=Grashoff184/> ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' (2005) put the death toll at \"more than 1,000.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German |quote=\u00dcber 1000 Menschen in dem vorpommerschen St\u00e4dtchen t\u00f6teten sich selbst samt ihren Familien (lit.: More than 1,000 people in that Western Pommeranian town killed themselves and their families).}}</ref> The [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] stated that \"nearly a thousand women and children committed suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1| quote=Die Schreckensbilanz am Ende: fast tausend Frauen und Kinder begehen Selbstmord (lit.: The horrible outcome: almost a thousand women and children commit suicide).}}</ref> Bauer (2008) wrote that \"some thousand people committed suicide, mostly by drowning.\"<ref name=Bauer533/> According to psychologist Bscheid (2009) and jurist and sociologist Volkersen (2005), it was the largest recorded mass suicide in Germany.<ref name=Bscheid>{{Cite web|url=http://edoc.ub.uni-muenchen.de/9966/1/Bscheid_Andrea.pdf|title=Das N\u00fcrnberger B\u00fcndnis gegen Depression. Pr\u00e4/Post-Vergleich eines depressions- und suizidpr\u00e4ventiven Programms nach 2 Jahren Intervention|first=Andrea Karoline|last=Bscheid|publisher=University of Munich|year=2009|page=19|language=German |quote=Die bislang gr\u00f6\u00dfte bekannte Massenselbstt\u00f6tung in der deutschen Geschichte ereignete sich im Mai 1945 in Demmin. Ca. 900 Einwohner nahmen sich vor und nach dem Einmarsch der Roten Armee das Leben, indem sie sich selbst in der Peene ertr\u00e4nkten (lit.: The greatest mass suicide that is known in the history of Germany so far took place in May 1945 in Demmin. About 900 citizens took their lives before, and after the Soviet invasion [of the town] by drowning themselves in the Peene river).}}</ref><ref name=Volkersen>{{Cite book|title=50 einfache Dinge, die Sie \u00fcber Ihr Recht wissen sollten|first=Nils|last=Volkersen|publisher=Westend-Verlag|year=2005|isbn=3-938060-05-0|language=German|page=86}}</ref> Both mentioned 900 suicides.<ref name=Bscheid/><ref name=Volkersen/> [[University of Rostock|Rostock]] historian Fred Mrotzek estimated that the death toll was 1,200 to 2,500 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stern.de/politik/geschichte/hysterie-der-massenselbstmord-von-demmin-539858.html|last=B\u00fcssem|first=Axel|title= Der Massenselbstmord von Demmin|publisher=[[Deutsche Presseagentur|DPA]], [[Der Stern|Stern]]|date=2005-05-02|accessdate=2010-08-21|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mz-web.de/ntb/ContentServer?pagename=ntb/page&atype=ksArtikel&aid=1114363664655&openMenu=1012569559900&calledPageId=1012569559900&listid=994342720546|title=Der Massenselbstmord im mecklenburgischen Demmin|date=2005-04-27|publisher=Naumburger Tageblatt/Mitteldeutsche Zeitung|accessdate=2010-08-21|language=German}}</ref>\n\n==East German Taboo==\nUnder the [[Communism|Communist]] [[East Germany|East German]] government, the mass suicide became a taboo.<ref name=lakotta/> The site of the mass graves was deliberately not cared for, became overgrown, and was at times tilled with sugar beets.<ref name=lakotta/> The only visible hint of the mass grave was a solitary monument with the engraved date \"1945\",<ref name=lakotta/> soon also overgrown. In contrast, a {{convert|20|m|ft|adj=on}} obelisk was erected in Demmin's burned down center to commemorate Soviet soldiers who had died in the area.<ref name=lakotta/> The local museum listed \"2,300 deaths due to warfare and famine\" for the years of 1945 and 1946.<ref name=vernier/> As late as 1989, the chronicle of the district's [[Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands|Communist party]] blamed the destruction of the town on [[Werwolf]] and [[Hitler Youth]] activities.<ref name=vernier/> The atrocities were blamed on Germans disguised as Soviets by a document found in the local Soviet military administration in [[Neubrandenburg]].<ref name=lakotta/> As ''Der Spiegel'' puts it:<blockquote>Arbitrary executions, the rapes, the torching of towns \u2013 the atrocities of the Red Army were a taboo in the GDR, the mass suicides as well. Those who had witnessed it all or even survived a failed suicide \u2013 children, elderly, raped women \u2013 were ashamed and kept quiet. Somehow, life had to go on in the system of the liberators. Today, many do not want to remember, for too long they had struggled to find a balance between what they had suffered and what they had learned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German}} Quote: \"Willk\u00fcrliche Erschie\u00dfungen, die Vergewaltigungen, das Abfackeln der St\u00e4dte \u2013 die Gr\u00e4ueltaten der Roten Armee waren in der DDR tabu, ebenso die Massenselbstmorde. Diejenigen, die alles mitangesehen oder gar einen gescheiterten Suizidversuch hinter sich hatten \u2013 Kinder, Alte, vergewaltigte Frauen \u2013 sch\u00e4mten sich und hielten still. Irgendwie musste das Leben im System der Befreier ja weitergehen. Heute m\u00f6gen manche nichts mehr davon h\u00f6ren, lange genug haben sie um die Balance zwischen Erlittenem und Erlerntem gerungen.</ref></blockquote>\n\nOnly a few East German documents mentioned the events. The first post-war district official (''Landrat'') of Demmin, who was confirmed in this position by the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|Soviet authorities]] on 15 May 1945, briefly mentioned the events in an internal \"activity report\" of 21 November, speaking of more than 700 suicide victims.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bessel|first=Richard|title=Policing in East Germany in the wake of the Second World War|journal=Crime, histoire et soci\u00e9t\u00e9s|volume=7|issue=2|year=2003|pages=5\u201321: 6\u20137}} Referencing MLHA, Kreistag/Rat des Kreises Demmin, pp. 46ff, 62\u201364: [The Landrat des Kreises Demmin] to the Pr\u00e4sident des Landes Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Abteilung Innere Verwaltung, [Demmin], 21. Nov 1945, T\u00e4tigkeitsbericht \u00fcber die Verwaltung des Kreises Demmin vom Mai bis November 1945. Quote: \"365 houses, roughly 70% of the town, lay in ruins, over 700 inhabitants had ended their lives by suicide.\"</ref> Dieter Kr\u00fcger, eyewitness of the events, son of a raped mother and survivor of a failed family suicide, started recording the mass suicide when working for the local museum in the 1980s, but his works were confiscated.<ref name=lakotta/> Historian [[Erla Vensky]] managed to \"smuggle\" a line about a \"panic, in the course of which 700 people committed suicide\" into the \"History of the local workers' movement\".<ref name=vernier/>\n\nAfter the [[Die Wende|collapse of the East German government]], some of the eyewitnesses, including Demmin's current chronicler, \"broke the silence\" and made their account of the mass suicide public.<ref name=zimmer5>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1258.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=5}}</ref> A new memorial was dedicated at the site of the mass graves.<ref name=zimmer5/> A dedicated issue of a journal published by the state of [[Mecklenburg-Vorpommern]] was released in 1995.<ref name=Buske/> Since then, accounts of the event have been published by German media. In 2008, the mass suicide was a theme of a novel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mare.de/index.php?article_id=457&setCookie=1|title=Canitz' Verlangen (review)|publisher=mare online|accessdate=2010-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Similar mass suicides==\nMass suicides occurred all along the late-war Soviet-German front line.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=Bauer533/> Examples include:\n* [[Neubrandenburg]]: more than 600 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Burg Stargard]]: 120 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Neustrelitz]]: 681 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Penzlin]]: 230 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Tessin, Germany|Tessin]]: 107 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Vietzen]] and [[Rechlin]]: mass suicide by drowning in Lake [[M\u00fcritz]]<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Teterow]], [[G\u00fcstrow]], [[Rostock]], [[Bad Doberan]]: hundreds of suicides each<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Malchin]] more than 500 suicides, buried in a mass grave<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Sch\u00f6nlanke]] (now Trzcianka): about 500 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Stolp]] (now S\u0142upsk): about 1000 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Lauenburg in Pommern|Lauenburg]] (now L\u0119bork): about 600 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Zielona G\u00f3ra|Gr\u00fcnberg]] (now Zielona G\u00f3ra): about 500 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Berlin]]: more than 4,000 suicides in April and May, including mass suicides<ref name=lakotta/><ref>{{cite journal| title=Sieg oder Untergang |trans-title=Victory or Doom |language=German |first=Heike |last=Talkenberger |journal=[[Damals]] |volume=47 |issue=4 |year=2015}} Book review for {{cite book |title=Kind, versprich mir, dass du dich erschie\u00dft |trans-title=Child, promise me to shoot yourself |language=German |first=Florian |last=Huber |publisher=Berlin Verlag |year=2015 |isbn=978-3-82701-247-0}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n;Subject literature\n*{{Cite book|title=Das Kriegsende in Demmin 1945. Berichte, Erinnerungen, Dokumente [The End of the War in Demmin in 1945. Accounts, Memories, Documents]|first=Norbert|last=Buske|location=Schwerin|publisher=Helms|year=1995|series=Landeskundliche Hefte|isbn=3-931185-04-4|language=German}}\n*{{cite book|last=Huber|first=Florian|translator-first=Imogen|translator-last=Taylor|title=Promise Me You'll Shoot Yourself|year=2019|publisher=Allen lane|location=London|isbn=978-0-241-39924-8}} (Originally published in {{lang-de|Kind, Versprich Mir Dass Du Dich Erschie\u03b2t}})\n*{{Cite book|title=\u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0445 \u0438 \u0431\u043e\u044f\u0445 [In Campaigns And Battles]|first=Pavel Ivanovich|last=Batov |authorlink=Pavel Batov|location=Moscow|publisher=Golos|year=2000|isbn=5-7117-0212-2|language=Russian}}\n\n;Fiction\n*{{Cite book|title=Canitz' Verlangen|first=Zora|last=del Buono|year=2008|isbn=978-3-86648-091-9|language=German}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.demminarchiv.de/Seiten/schutt_asche.html Collection of photographs showing Demmin in 1945, after the fire (demminarchiv.de)]\n*[http://www.demmin-web.de/j1/index.php?option=com_joomgallery&func=viewcategory&catid=19&Itemid=2 Collection of photographs showing Demmin in 1945, after the fire (demmin-web.de)]\n\n{{Mass suicide}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mass Suicide in Demmin}}\n[[Category:Mass suicides]]\n[[Category:History of Pomerania]]\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Soviet World War II crimes]]\n[[Category:May 1945 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{Coord|53.905|13.049|display=title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\nOn 1 May 1945, hundreds of people [[mass suicide|killed themselves]] in the town of [[Demmin]], in the [[Province of Pomerania (1815\u20131945)|Province of Pomerania]] (now in [[Mecklenburg-Vorpommern]]), [[Germany]]. The suicides occurred during a mass panic that was provoked by atrocities committed by soldiers of the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Red Army]], who had sacked the town the day before. Although death toll estimates vary, it is acknowledged to be the largest mass suicide ever recorded in Germany. The suicide was part of a [[Mass suicides in 1945 Nazi Germany|mass suicide wave]] amongst the population of Nazi Germany.\n\n[[Nazi Party|Nazi officials]], the police, the [[Wehrmacht]] and many citizens had left the town before the arrival of the Red Army, while thousands of [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|refugees from the East]] had also taken refuge in Demmin. Three Soviet negotiators were shot prior to the Soviet advance into Demmin and [[Hitler Youth]], amongst others, fired on Soviet soldiers once inside the town. The retreating Wehrmacht had blown up the bridges over the [[Peene]] and [[Tollense]] rivers, which enclosed the town to the north, west and south, thus blocking the Red Army's advance and trapping the remaining civilians. The Soviet units looted and burned down the town, and committed rapes and executions.\n\nNumerous inhabitants and refugees then killed themselves, with many families doing so together. Methods of suicides included drowning in the rivers, hanging, wrist-cutting, and shooting. Most bodies were buried in mass graves, and after the war, discussion of the mass suicide was taboo under the [[East Germany|East German]] [[Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands|Communist government]].\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Demmin Stadtplan.PNG|thumb|325px|[[Demmin]], enclosed by the [[Peene]] river in the north and west, and the [[Tollense]] river in the south. The bridges were blown up by the retreating [[Wehrmacht]], the [[Red Army]] approached the town from the east. Modified [[OpenStreetMap|OSM]] map.]]\nDemmin was a stronghold of the nationalistic organisations [[German National People's Party|DNVP]] and ''[[Der Stahlhelm, Bund der Frontsoldaten|Der Stahlhelm]]'' in the [[Weimar Republic]]. Before 1933 there were boycotts of Jewish businesses, which drove away most of the Jews. The synagogue was sold in June 1938 to a furniture company, which is why it survives as a building today. In the [[Kristallnacht|riots of November 1938]] thousands gathered in the square in anti-Semitic demonstration.<ref>Artikel ''Demmin'' in: Irene Diekmann (Hg.), ''Wegweiser durch das j\u00fcdische Mecklenburg-Vorpommern'', Potsdam 1998, S. 99 ff, bes. S. 111 f</ref> In the last national elections to the Reichstag on 5 March 1933 the National Socialist Party won 53.7 percent of votes in Demmin.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Thomas |last=Scheck |title=Echt deutsch und national \u2013 Die vorpommersche Kleinstadt Demmin im Jahr 1933 |trans-title=Truly German and national \u2013 the West Pomeranian town of Demmin in the year 1933 |journal=Zeitgeschichte regional |issue=4/4 |year=2000 |pages=14\u201323 |language=German |url=http://aggb-katalog.de/vufind/Record/top569203163}}</ref>\n\nDuring the last weeks of [[World War II]], [[Mass suicides in 1945 Nazi Germany|tens of thousands of Germans killed themselves]], especially in territories occupied by the [[Red Army]].<ref name=lakotta>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German}}</ref> The German historian [[Udo Grashhoff]] and the German author [[Kurt Bauer]] wrote that the suicides occurred in two stages: in a first wave before the Red Army's arrival, in part due to a \"fear of the Russians\" spread by [[Nazi propaganda]],<ref name=Grashoff184>{{Cite book|title=In einem Anfall von Depression: Selbstt\u00f6tungen in der DDR |first=Udo |last=Grasshoff |language=German |page=184 |publisher=Ch. Links Verlag |year=2006 |isbn=978-3-86153-420-4}} Quote: \"Es handelte sich dabei zum Teil um eine Panikreaktion aus einer von der nationalsozialistischen Propaganda gesch\u00fcrten Angst vor den Russen; die Selbstt\u00f6tungswellen ereigneten sich aber zumeist in zwei Phasen. Den ersten von Angst und Panik bestimmten Selbstt\u00f6tungen folgte in vielen Orten eine zweite Selbstt\u00f6tungswelle, nachdem es zu Hinrichtungen, Pl\u00fcnderungen und massenhaften Vergewaltigungen durch die Besatzer gekommen war. Im mecklenburgischen Demmin zum Beispiel nahmen sich innerhalb von einer Woche von ca. 15000 Einwohnern etwa 700 das Leben.[15] [...] 15: Sch\u00e4tzungen der Zahl der Selbstt\u00f6tungen reichen von 700 bis 1200. Vgl Norbert Buske, Das Kriegsende in Demmin, Schwerin 1995, S. 44f.\" Translation: In part, this was a panic reaction, out of a fear of the Russians, fuelled by Nazi propaganda; For the most part, the suicides occurred in two waves. The first suicides, which were sparked by fear and panic, were, in many places, followed by a second wave of suicides, after executions, looting and mass rapes had occurred. For example, in the course of one week, some 700 of 15,000 inhabitants killed themselves in the Mecklenburgian town of Demmin.[15] [...] 15: Estimates of the number of suicides range from 700 to 1,200. Cf. Norbert Buske (1995), Das Kriegsende in Demmin, Schwerin, pp. 44\u201345.</ref> and \u2013 as in Demmin \u2013 in a second wave after the Red Army's arrival, triggered by executions, looting and mass rapes committed by Soviet soldiers.<ref name=Grashoff184/><ref name=Bauer533>{{Cite book| title=Nationalsozialismus: Urspr\u00fcnge, Anf\u00e4nge, Aufstieg und Fall|first=Kurt|last=Bauer|page=533|language=German|publisher=UTB|year=2005|isbn=978-3-8252-3076-0}} Quote: \"Im Anschlu\u00df an die Kampfhandlungen kam es immer wieder zu Massakern an der Zivilbev\u00f6lkerung und an Wehrmachtssoldaten, die sich ergeben hatten. Ausgedehnte Pl\u00fcnderungen und Raubz\u00fcge waren allt\u00e4gliche Begleiterscheinungen des Vormarsches der Roten Armee. Zum kollektiven Trauma wurden die massrenhaften Vergewaltigungen deutscher Frauen durch die russische Soldateska. [...] Von zwei Millionen Vergewaltigungsopfern in den von der Roten Armee besetzten deutschen Gebieten ist in der Literatur die Rede. Jede zehnte Frau d\u00fcrfte an den Folgen der Massenvergewaltigungen gestorben sein oder anschlie\u00dfend Suizid ver\u00fcbt haben. Massenselbstt\u00f6tungen von Menschen, die der Roten Armee nicht hatten entkommen k\u00f6nnen, waren ein weiteres, erschreckendes Ph\u00e4nomen in der Kriegsendphase. In der vorpommerschen Kleinstadt Demmin ver\u00fcbten in den ersten Maitagen 1945 in einer Massenpsychose an die 1000 Menschen Selbstmord, zumeist durch Ertr\u00e4nken.\" Translation: After the fighting, there were repeated massacres of civilians and Wehrmacht soldiers who had surrendered. Extensive looting and raids were every-day occurrences during the Red Army's advance. Mass rapes of German women by Russian soldiers became a pervasive trauma. Two million rape victims are mentioned by writings at the time. One in every ten women died of the mass rapes, or else committed suicide afterwards. These mass suicides of people who had not been able to escape the Red Army were another terrifying phenomenon in the final stage of the war. In the small West Pomeranian town of Demmin, some 1,000 people committed suicide during the first days of May 1945, in most cases by drowning themselves.</ref>\n\nIn 1945, Demmin had between 15,000<ref name=Grashoff184/> and 16,000 inhabitants.<ref name=vernier>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German}}</ref> Thousands of [[Flight and expulsion of Germans from Poland during and after World War II|refugees from the East]] were also in town, roughly doubling its population.<ref name=zimmer1>{{Cite web|url= https://www.ndr.de/kultur/geschichte/kriegsendedemmin102.pdf|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1}}</ref> In late April, when the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] drew closer ([[Battle of Berlin#North|Battle of Berlin]]), women, children and elderly men were forced to dig a {{convert|5|km|mi|adj=on}}-long anti-tank ditch east of the town.<ref name=vernier/> On 28 April, the German flight from the town began: the [[Nazi party]] functionaries left on confiscated fire engines, the hospital was evacuated, all the police departed, and a number of civilians fled.<ref name=vernier/>\n\nDemmin was reached by spearheads of the [[65th Army (Soviet Union)|Soviet 65th Army]]<ref>Batow, P.I.: ''\u041e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041e\u0434\u0435\u0440, \u0411\u043e\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f 65-\u0439 \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0439 \u0432 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 \u2013 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b \u2013 \u043c\u0430\u0439 1945 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430.'' (Russian), museum Demmin, signature 10.629.</ref> and the [[1st Guards Tank Corps]] at noon on 30 April 1945.<ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> At the tower of the church, a white banner was hoisted.<ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> According to an eyewitness, three Soviet negotiators, one of them a German officer, approached the anti-tank ditch and promised to spare Demmin's civilian population from \"harassment\" and looting in the case of a surrender without fight.<ref name=zimmer1/> This eyewitness was then 19 years old, serving as a [[Wehrmacht|German soldier]], and lying in the anti-tank ditch.<ref name=zimmer1/> According to him, three shots were fired at the negotiators, who sank to the ground.<ref name=zimmer1/> The remaining [[Wehrmacht]] units,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> belonging to [[Army Group Weichsel]], and some [[Waffen-SS]],<ref name=vernier/> retreated through Demmin,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> and roughly about half an hour after the incident,<ref name=zimmer1/> blew up all bridges leading out of town behind them.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer1/> By that time, Soviet units were already advancing through Demmin.<ref name=zimmer1/>\n\nThe destruction of the bridges prevented the Soviet from advancing westward<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> toward [[Rostock]], which they had planned to reach the same day.<ref name=zimmer1/> It also prevented the flight of the civilian population, who were trapped by the rivers surrounding the town.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer1/> According to eyewitnesses, some \"fanatics,\" primarily [[Hitler Youth]],<ref name=lakotta/> shot at the Soviet soldiers,<ref name=zimmer1/> despite several white flags being hoisted on Demmin's buildings. Memorably, a Nazi loyalist schoolteacher, having slain his wife and children, launched a grenade from a [[panzerfaust]] on Soviet soldiers, before finally hanging himself.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German |quote=Studienrat Moldenhauer, ein Nazi-Mitl\u00e4ufer, erschoss seine Frau und seine drei Kinder, bevor er eine Panzerfaust auf die Russen abfeuerte und sich erh\u00e4ngte (Translation: Lecturer Moldenhauer, a Nazi follower, shot dead his wife and his three children prior to launching a panzerfaust grenade at the Russians and then hanging himself).}}</ref> According to the [[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] magazine, an eyewitness stated that the first Soviet soldier was shot near the hospital at 11:05 AM by someone running amok, apparently the aforementioned teacher, who had before told a neighbor that he had killed his wife and his children.<ref name=vernierquote>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German |quote='Der erste Russe wurde um f\u00fcnf nach elf vor dem roten Krankenhaus erschossen', erz\u00e4hlt der Demminer Uhrmacher Rolf-Dietrich Schultz. Damals, mit neun Jahren, ist er von einem Keller in der Treptower Stra\u00dfe aus Augenzeuge. Der Amoksch\u00fctze ist offenbar Studienrat Gerhard Moldenhauer. Der NSDAP-Mitl\u00e4ufer hatte einer Nachbarin erkl\u00e4rt: 'Ich habe eben meine Frau und meine Kinder erschossen, nun will ich noch ein paar Russen umlegen.' Ein Scharm\u00fctzel gibt es auch am Luisentor. Das alte Stadttor, zuletzt Treffpunkt der Hitlerjungen, beschie\u00dfen die Russen mit Panzergranaten. Dann herrscht \u2013 zun\u00e4chst \u2013 Ruhe. Die Exzesse beginnen noch am Abend (Translation: The first Russian was shot dead at five past eleven in front of the red hospital,' stated watchmaker Rolf-Dietrich Schultz from Demmin. Back then, aged nine, he was an eyewitness, watching from a cellar in Treptower Stra\u00dfe. The gunman was apparently Lecturer Gerhard Moldenhauer. The NSDAP follower had declared to a neighbour: 'I've just shot my wife and children, now I just want to pick off some Russians'. A skirmish also took place at Louisentor gate. The old towngate, which used to be a meeting point of the Hitler Youth, was being shelled with tank grenades by the Russians. Then, there was a \u2013 temporary \u2013 silence. The true violence started later that evening).}}</ref> A third eyewitness confirmed the identity of the amok gunman in a report by [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk]] and blamed him and other fanatics for causing the Soviet troops to retaliate with plundering the town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-23|language=German|page=1}} Citing Demmin chronicler Hans-Gerhardt Quadt who was 14 at the time: \"Es gab Fanatiker, die auf vorbeiziehende Russen schossen, die sich das auch vorgenommen hatten. Ich nehme den Studienrat Gerhard Moldenhauer, der seiner Nachbarin sagte: \u201aIch habe eben meine Familie get\u00f6tet, jetzt lege ich noch einige Russen um und dann scheide ich selbst aus dem Leben.' Und so hat er das auch gemacht, und hat hiermit eine Schuld auf sich geladen, die nun nach sowjetischem Kriegsrecht dazu f\u00fchrte, dass Demmin drei Tage zur Pl\u00fcnderung freigegeben wurde. Demmin ist drei Tage zur Pl\u00fcnderung freigegeben und das bedeutete, wir z\u00fcnden die Stadt an und wir \u00fcben hier das Kriegsrecht aus. (lit.: There were fanatics who shot at Russians passing through and who were willing to do that. For example Lecturer Gerhard Moldenhauer who told his neighbour: 'I have just killed my family, now I'm going to pick off some Russians and then I'm going to pass away too.' And that he did and thereby he made himself guilty of causing three days of plundering in Demmin. According to Soviet martial law: 'Demmin may be plundered at will for three days' and that meant 'we'll burn the city and bring martial law upon them'\".)</ref> Then, it was \"quiet\" until the evening, when the atrocities started.<ref name=vernierquote/> Another incident is said to have happened on 1 May, when the local pharmacist hosted a \"victory party\" of Soviet officers, killing them with poisoned wine.<ref name=zimmer2>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1252.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=2}}</ref> The [[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]] magazine however dismissed that as a \"legend\"<ref name=vernier/> and also theologian and historian Norbert Buske concluded in a 1995 study that the story had been fabricated.<ref name=Buske>{{Cite book|title=Das Kriegsende in Demmin 1945. Berichte, Erinnerungen, Dokumente|first=Norbert|last=Buske|location=Schwerin|publisher=Helms|year=1995|series=Landeskundliche Hefte|isbn=3-931185-04-4|language=German}}</ref>\n\nThe Soviet soldiers in turn were allowed to loot the town for a period of three days.<ref name=zimmer1/> They committed [[Rape during the occupation of Germany#Soviet troops|mass rapes]] of local women,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/><ref name=zimmer2/> according to eyewitnesses, \"regardless of age\", and shot German men who spoke up against this practice.<ref name=zimmer2/> Furthermore, large areas of the town were set on fire, with nearly all of the center burning down completely.<ref name=zimmer2/> 80% of the town was destroyed within three days.<ref name=vernier/> Reportedly, Soviet soldiers had brushed the houses' walls with gasoline before setting them on fire, and stood guard three days to prevent extinguishing.<ref name=vernier/> Many of the soldiers committing the mass rapes, executions, and pillaging were reportedly drunk.<ref name=lakotta/> Already on 30 April, when the atrocities started in the evening, Soviet soldiers had looted both Demmin's cereal distilleries and several alcohol stores.<ref name=vernier/>\n\n==Suicides==\n[[File:Peene-in-Demmin-26-VIII-2007-07.jpg|thumb|The Peene river in Demmin in 2007]]\nThese events, along with the fear of atrocities stirred up by the [[Nazi propaganda]] before, caused a [[mass panic]] among the population.<ref name=lakotta/> Many local and refugee families killed themselves together.<ref name=zimmer2/> The suicides were either performed with guns, razor blades or poison, others hanged or drowned themselves in the [[Peene]] and [[Tollense]] rivers.<ref name=zimmer3>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1254.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=3}}</ref> Several mothers killed their children before killing themselves,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer3/> or walked into one of the rivers with a rock in a backpack and their babies in their arms.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some families died by walking into the rivers, tied together.<ref name=lakotta/> A local forester first shot three young children, then their mothers, then his wife and then himself, surviving as a blind man.<ref name=zimmer3/> In another recorded case, a daughter cut the wrists of her parents.<ref name=zimmer3/>\n\nNot every suicide case was completed.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some mothers who had drowned their children were unable to drown themselves thereafter.<ref name=zimmer3/> In other cases, doses of poison proved to be lethal for children, but not for their mothers.<ref name=zimmer3/> There were also cases where children survived attempted drownings.<ref name=zimmer3/> Some members who survived a first attempt at suicide killed themselves by others methods. A mother and her repeatedly raped daughter, for instance, died by hanging themselves in an attic, after repeatedly failing to drown themselves in the Peene river.<ref name=zimmer3/> Another mother who had poisoned and buried three of her four children before, tried to hang herself on an oak three times, only to be prevented to do so each time by Soviet soldiers.<ref name=lakotta/> There are further records of Soviet soldiers preventing suicides by retrieving people from the river and nursing cut wrists.<ref name=lakotta/> In another case, a grandfather forcibly took away a razor blade from a mother who was about to kill her children and herself after being raped by Soviet soldiers and hearing of the death of her husband.<ref name=lakotta/> After Soviet soldiers had raped a girl to death and shot her father, an aunt cut her daughter's and son's wrists as well as her own. The other women of the family committed suicide, only one aunt was able to save the grandmother.<ref name=lakotta/> One family survived, because the 15-year-old son persuaded his mother, who had become a rape victim, to abort her induced drowning, when she was already being dragged by the Tollense river.<ref name=lakotta/>\n\nDemmin's current chronicler, then 14 years old, recalls:<blockquote>My mother was also raped. And then, together with us and with neighbors, she hurried towards the Tollense river, resolutely prepared to jump into it. [...] My siblings [...] realized only much later that I had held her back, that I had pulled her out of what may be called a state of trance, to prevent her from jumping into the water. There were people. There was screaming. The people were prepared to die. Children were told: 'Do you want to live on? The town is burning. These and those are dead already. No, we do not want to live any more.' And so, people went mostly into the rivers. [...] That made even the Russians feel creepy. There are examples where Russians, too, tried to pull people out or hinder them. But these hundreds of people, they were unable to withhold. And the population here was extremely panicked.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1}} Quote: \"[...] auch meine Mutter fiel der Vergewaltigung anheim. Und dann rannte sie mit uns und mit Nachbarn in Richtung Tollense und hatte den absoluten Vorsatz hineinzuspringen. [...] Meine Geschwister [...] die haben das auch erst viel sp\u00e4ter mitbekommen, dass ich meine Mutter zur\u00fcckgehalten habe, sie aus diesem - ja man k\u00f6nnte es Trance-Zustand nennen - gerissen habe, um sie daran zu hindern, nicht ins Wasser zu springen. Da waren Menschen. Es gab Schreie. Die Menschen waren bereit zu sterben. Kindern wurde gesagt: 'Wollt ihr noch leben? Die Stadt brennt. Die und die sind auch schon tot. Nein, wir wollen nicht mehr leben.' Und so sind die Menschen zumeist in die Fl\u00fcsse gegangen. [...] Das wurde auch den Russen unheimlich. Es gibt Beispiele, wo auch die Russen versucht haben, Menschen rauszuholen oder sie daran zu hindern. Aber die Hunderte von Menschen haben sie nicht hindern k\u00f6nnen. Und die Bev\u00f6lkerung hier war in einer riesigen Panik.\"</ref></blockquote>\n\nGisela Zimmer writes that many of the dead were buried in mass graves<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=zimmer4>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1256.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=4}}</ref> on the Bartholom\u00e4i graveyard.<ref name=\"zimmer4\"/> Some were buried in orderly graves on the initiative of relatives.<ref name=zimmer4/> Others were not buried, as their bodies were not retrieved from the rivers.<ref name=zimmer4/> More than 900 bodies were buried in the mass graves.<ref name=lakotta/> 500 of them were recorded on sheets of a warehouse accountant's book converted into a death register.<ref name=vernier/> Weeks after the mass suicide, bodies still floated in the rivers.<ref name=lakotta/> Clothes and other belongings of the drowned formed a border along the rivers' banks,<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=vernier/> up to {{convert|2|m|ft}} wide.<ref name=vernier/>\n\n==Death toll==\n''[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]'' magazine (1995) quoted Norbert Buske as saying, \"We will have to assume more than 1,000 deaths.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.focus.de/politik/deutschland/die-letzten-kriegstage-tragoedie-an-der-peene_aid_151639.html|title=Trag\u00f6die an der Peene|last=Vernier|first=Robert|publisher=[[Focus (German magazine)|Focus]]|date=1995-05-08|accessdate=2010-08-20|language=German}} Citing Buske (1995): Das Kriegsende in Demmin. Quote: \"Wir werden von mehr als 1000 Toten auszugehen haben (lit.: we will have to assume a number of more than 1,000 dead).\"</ref> According to Goeschel (2009), with reference to Buske (1995), \"Some 700 to 1,000 people are said to have committed suicide directly after the arrival of the Red Army;\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Suicide in Nazi Germany|first=Christian|last=Goeschel|publisher=Oxford University Press US|year=2009|isbn=0-19-953256-7|pages=162, 205}}</ref> Grashoff (2006), using the same reference, stated that \"estimates of the number of suicides range from 700 to 1,200.\"<ref name=Grashoff184/> ''[[Der Spiegel]]'' (2005) put the death toll at \"more than 1,000.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German |quote=\u00dcber 1000 Menschen in dem vorpommerschen St\u00e4dtchen t\u00f6teten sich selbst samt ihren Familien (lit.: More than 1,000 people in that Western Pommeranian town killed themselves and their families).}}</ref> The [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] stated that \"nearly a thousand women and children committed suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1250.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=1| quote=Die Schreckensbilanz am Ende: fast tausend Frauen und Kinder begehen Selbstmord (lit.: The horrible outcome: almost a thousand women and children commit suicide).}}</ref> Bauer (2008) wrote that \"some thousand people committed suicide, mostly by drowning.\"<ref name=Bauer533/> According to psychologist Bscheid (2009) and jurist and sociologist Volkersen (2005), it was the largest recorded mass suicide in Germany.<ref name=Bscheid>{{Cite web|url=http://edoc.ub.uni-muenchen.de/9966/1/Bscheid_Andrea.pdf|title=Das N\u00fcrnberger B\u00fcndnis gegen Depression. Pr\u00e4/Post-Vergleich eines depressions- und suizidpr\u00e4ventiven Programms nach 2 Jahren Intervention|first=Andrea Karoline|last=Bscheid|publisher=University of Munich|year=2009|page=19|language=German |quote=Die bislang gr\u00f6\u00dfte bekannte Massenselbstt\u00f6tung in der deutschen Geschichte ereignete sich im Mai 1945 in Demmin. Ca. 900 Einwohner nahmen sich vor und nach dem Einmarsch der Roten Armee das Leben, indem sie sich selbst in der Peene ertr\u00e4nkten (lit.: The greatest mass suicide that is known in the history of Germany so far took place in May 1945 in Demmin. About 900 citizens took their lives before, and after the Soviet invasion [of the town] by drowning themselves in the Peene river).}}</ref><ref name=Volkersen>{{Cite book|title=50 einfache Dinge, die Sie \u00fcber Ihr Recht wissen sollten|first=Nils|last=Volkersen|publisher=Westend-Verlag|year=2005|isbn=3-938060-05-0|language=German|page=86}}</ref> Both mentioned 900 suicides.<ref name=Bscheid/><ref name=Volkersen/> [[University of Rostock|Rostock]] historian Fred Mrotzek estimated that the death toll was 1,200 to 2,500 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stern.de/politik/geschichte/hysterie-der-massenselbstmord-von-demmin-539858.html|last=B\u00fcssem|first=Axel|title= Der Massenselbstmord von Demmin|publisher=[[Deutsche Presseagentur|DPA]], [[Der Stern|Stern]]|date=2005-05-02|accessdate=2010-08-21|language=German}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mz-web.de/ntb/ContentServer?pagename=ntb/page&atype=ksArtikel&aid=1114363664655&openMenu=1012569559900&calledPageId=1012569559900&listid=994342720546|title=Der Massenselbstmord im mecklenburgischen Demmin|date=2005-04-27|publisher=Naumburger Tageblatt/Mitteldeutsche Zeitung|accessdate=2010-08-21|language=German}}</ref>\n\n==East German Taboo==\nUnder the [[Communism|Communist]] [[East Germany|East German]] government, the mass suicide became a taboo.<ref name=lakotta/> The site of the mass graves was deliberately not cared for, became overgrown, and was at times tilled with sugar beets.<ref name=lakotta/> The only visible hint of the mass grave was a solitary monument with the engraved date \"1945\",<ref name=lakotta/> soon also overgrown. In contrast, a {{convert|20|m|ft|adj=on}} obelisk was erected in Demmin's burned down center to commemorate Soviet soldiers who had died in the area.<ref name=lakotta/> The local museum listed \"2,300 deaths due to warfare and famine\" for the years of 1945 and 1946.<ref name=vernier/> As late as 1989, the chronicle of the district's [[Sozialistische Einheitspartei Deutschlands|Communist party]] blamed the destruction of the town on [[Werwolf]] and [[Hitler Youth]] activities.<ref name=vernier/> The atrocities were blamed on Germans disguised as Soviets by a document found in the local Soviet military administration in [[Neubrandenburg]].<ref name=lakotta/> As ''Der Spiegel'' puts it:<blockquote>Arbitrary executions, the rapes, the torching of towns \u2013 the atrocities of the Red Army were a taboo in the GDR, the mass suicides as well. Those who had witnessed it all or even survived a failed suicide \u2013 children, elderly, raped women \u2013 were ashamed and kept quiet. Somehow, life had to go on in the system of the liberators. Today, many do not want to remember, for too long they had struggled to find a balance between what they had suffered and what they had learned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/spiegelspecial/d-39863564.html|title=Tief vergraben, nicht dran r\u00fchren|last=Lakotta|first=Beate|publisher=[[Der Spiegel|SPON]]|date=2005-03-05|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German}} Quote: \"Willk\u00fcrliche Erschie\u00dfungen, die Vergewaltigungen, das Abfackeln der St\u00e4dte \u2013 die Gr\u00e4ueltaten der Roten Armee waren in der DDR tabu, ebenso die Massenselbstmorde. Diejenigen, die alles mitangesehen oder gar einen gescheiterten Suizidversuch hinter sich hatten \u2013 Kinder, Alte, vergewaltigte Frauen \u2013 sch\u00e4mten sich und hielten still. Irgendwie musste das Leben im System der Befreier ja weitergehen. Heute m\u00f6gen manche nichts mehr davon h\u00f6ren, lange genug haben sie um die Balance zwischen Erlittenem und Erlerntem gerungen.</ref></blockquote>\n\nOnly a few East German documents mentioned the events. The first post-war district official (''Landrat'') of Demmin, who was confirmed in this position by the [[Soviet Military Administration in Germany|Soviet authorities]] on 15 May 1945, briefly mentioned the events in an internal \"activity report\" of 21 November, speaking of more than 700 suicide victims.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bessel|first=Richard|title=Policing in East Germany in the wake of the Second World War|journal=Crime, histoire et soci\u00e9t\u00e9s|volume=7|issue=2|year=2003|pages=5\u201321: 6\u20137}} Referencing MLHA, Kreistag/Rat des Kreises Demmin, pp. 46ff, 62\u201364: [The Landrat des Kreises Demmin] to the Pr\u00e4sident des Landes Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, Abteilung Innere Verwaltung, [Demmin], 21. Nov 1945, T\u00e4tigkeitsbericht \u00fcber die Verwaltung des Kreises Demmin vom Mai bis November 1945. Quote: \"365 houses, roughly 70% of the town, lay in ruins, over 700 inhabitants had ended their lives by suicide.\"</ref> Dieter Kr\u00fcger, eyewitness of the events, son of a raped mother and survivor of a failed family suicide, started recording the mass suicide when working for the local museum in the 1980s, but his works were confiscated.<ref name=lakotta/> Historian [[Erla Vensky]] managed to \"smuggle\" a line about a \"panic, in the course of which 700 people committed suicide\" into the \"History of the local workers' movement\".<ref name=vernier/>\n\nAfter the [[Die Wende|collapse of the East German government]], some of the eyewitnesses, including Demmin's current chronicler, \"broke the silence\" and made their account of the mass suicide public.<ref name=zimmer5>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ndr.de/land_leute/norddeutsche_geschichte/erinnerungen/vor_der_teilung/ndr1258.html|first=Gisela|last=Zimmer|title=Kriegsende in Demmin|publisher=[[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]]|accessdate=2010-08-16|language=German|page=5}}</ref> A new memorial was dedicated at the site of the mass graves.<ref name=zimmer5/> A dedicated issue of a journal published by the state of [[Mecklenburg-Vorpommern]] was released in 1995.<ref name=Buske/> Since then, accounts of the event have been published by German media. In 2008, the mass suicide was a theme of a novel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mare.de/index.php?article_id=457&setCookie=1|title=Canitz' Verlangen (review)|publisher=mare online|accessdate=2010-09-04}}</ref>\n\n==Similar mass suicides==\nMass suicides occurred all along the late-war Soviet-German front line.<ref name=lakotta/><ref name=Bauer533/> Examples include:\n* [[Neubrandenburg]]: more than 600 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Burg Stargard]]: 120 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Neustrelitz]]: 681 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Penzlin]]: 230 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Tessin, Germany|Tessin]]: 107 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Vietzen]] and [[Rechlin]]: mass suicide by drowning in Lake [[M\u00fcritz]]<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Teterow]], [[G\u00fcstrow]], [[Rostock]], [[Bad Doberan]]: hundreds of suicides each<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Malchin]] more than 500 suicides, buried in a mass grave<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Sch\u00f6nlanke]] (now Trzcianka): about 500 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Stolp]] (now S\u0142upsk): about 1000 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Lauenburg in Pommern|Lauenburg]] (now L\u0119bork): about 600 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Zielona G\u00f3ra|Gr\u00fcnberg]] (now Zielona G\u00f3ra): about 500 suicides<ref name=lakotta/>\n* [[Berlin]]: more than 4,000 suicides in April and May, including mass suicides<ref name=lakotta/><ref>{{cite journal| title=Sieg oder Untergang |trans-title=Victory or Doom |language=German |first=Heike |last=Talkenberger |journal=[[Damals]] |volume=47 |issue=4 |year=2015}} Book review for {{cite book |title=Kind, versprich mir, dass du dich erschie\u00dft |trans-title=Child, promise me to shoot yourself |language=German |first=Florian |last=Huber |publisher=Berlin Verlag |year=2015 |isbn=978-3-82701-247-0}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n;Subject literature\n*{{Cite book|title=Das Kriegsende in Demmin 1945. Berichte, Erinnerungen, Dokumente [The End of the War in Demmin in 1945. Accounts, Memories, Documents]|first=Norbert|last=Buske|location=Schwerin|publisher=Helms|year=1995|series=Landeskundliche Hefte|isbn=3-931185-04-4|language=German}}\n*{{cite book|last=Huber|first=Florian|translator-first=Imogen|translator-last=Taylor|title=Promise Me You'll Shoot Yourself|year=2019|publisher=Allen lane|location=London|isbn=978-0-241-39924-8}} (Originally published in {{lang-de|Kind, Versprich Mir Dass Du Dich Erschie\u03b2t}})\n*{{Cite book|title=\u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0445 \u0438 \u0431\u043e\u044f\u0445 [In Campaigns And Battles]|first=Pavel Ivanovich|last=Batov |authorlink=Pavel Batov|location=Moscow|publisher=Golos|year=2000|isbn=5-7117-0212-2|language=Russian}}\n\n;Fiction\n*{{Cite book|title=Canitz' Verlangen|first=Zora|last=del Buono|year=2008|isbn=978-3-86648-091-9|language=German}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.demminarchiv.de/Seiten/schutt_asche.html Collection of photographs showing Demmin in 1945, after the fire (demminarchiv.de)]\n*[http://www.demmin-web.de/j1/index.php?option=com_joomgallery&func=viewcategory&catid=19&Itemid=2 Collection of photographs showing Demmin in 1945, after the fire (demmin-web.de)]\n\n{{Mass suicide}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mass Suicide in Demmin}}\n[[Category:Mass suicides]]\n[[Category:History of Pomerania]]\n[[Category:1945 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Soviet World War II crimes]]\n[[Category:May 1945 events]]\n", "name_user": "PrairieCat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSuicides:Spelling/grammar/punctuation/typographical correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_suicide_in_Demmin"}
{"title_page": "Kerry Godliman", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|BLP=yes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Kerry Godliman\n| image       = Kerry Godliman 2011.jpg\n| caption     = Kerry Godliman in 2011\n| birth_name  = Kerry Anna Godliman\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1973|11|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Perivale]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| nationality = British\n| occupation = Actor, comedian\n| years_active = 1998\u2013present\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.kerrygodliman.com/}}\n}}\n'''Kerry Anna Godliman''' (born 17 November 1973 in [[Perivale]], [[London]]) is an [[English people|English]] comedian and actor. She played Hannah in ''[[Derek (TV series)|Derek]]''{{Hair space}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Kerry Godliman interview for Derek |url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/kerry-godliman-interview-for-derek |publisher=channel4.com |accessdate=29 March 2013 |author=Channel 4}}</ref>, Nicky Rawlings in ''[[Bad Move]]'' and Lisa in ''[[After Life (TV series)|After Life]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGodliman was born in [[Perivale]], London<ref name=\"taskmaster\">{{cite episode|title=Series 7, Episode 3|network=[[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]]|airdate=19 September 2019|series=[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]}}</ref>, and trained at [[Rose Bruford College]], south London.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chortle.co.uk/comics/k/187/kerry_godliman |title=Kerry Godliman, comedian : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide |first= |last= |work=chortle.co.uk |year=2015 |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nGodliman has appeared in ''[[Law of the Playground]]'', ''[[Spoons (TV series)|Spoons]]'', ''[[Extras (TV series)|Extras]]'', ''[[Life's Too Short (TV series)|Life's Too Short]]'', ''[[Rush Hour (UK TV series)|Rush Hour]]'', ''[[Michael McIntyre's Comedy Roadshow]]'', ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]]'', and ''[[Home Time]]''. She appeared in the final episode of the first series of ''[[Frankie (TV series)|Frankie]]'' as a seriously ill hardworking patient.\n\nGodliman plays Hannah in [[Ricky Gervais]]' Channel 4 sitcom ''[[Derek (TV series)|Derek]]''. She played the mother in ''[[Our Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9949408/Our-Girl-BBC-One-review.html |title=Our Girl, BBC One, review - Telegraph |first=Sarah |last=Crompton |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> She appeared in the [[Sky 1]] sitcom ''[[Carters Get Rich]]'' as Liz Carter, the mother of Harry, who invents an app and becomes a [[millionaire]]. She guest-starred in an episode of ''Damned'', with [[Jo Brand]] and [[Alan Davies]].\n\nSince 2017, Kerry has portrayed the role of Nicky in the ITV sitcom ''Bad Move'', and in 2018 she played Peggy Aytean in the [[Channel 4]] computer game series ''Rob Beckett's Playing for Time''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rob Beckett's Playing for Time |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8216630/ |website=IMDB |publisher=IMDB |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Kerry won the seventh series of [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]]'s comedy-gameshow ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]'', beating [[James Acaster]], [[Jessica Knappett]], [[Phil Wang]], and [[Rhod Gilbert]]. Recently, Godliman starred as Lisa in the [[Netflix]] black comedy series, ''[[After Life (TV series)|After Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/after-life-cast-ricky-gervais-netflix-new-series/|title=After Life cast: who stars with Ricky Gervais in new Netflix series \u2013 and where else you\u2019ve seen them|last=Sanusi|first=Victoria|work=iNews|date=8 March 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Kerry guest starred in the eighth episode of the eighth series of ''[[Call the Midwife]]''.\n\nShe portrays Carol on [[USA Network]]'s ''[[Treadstone]]''.\n\n==Radio==\nGodliman has appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''At the Fringe''. From the end of April 2013, she also had her own four-part series on Radio 4, ''Kerry's List''. In August 2014, she made her debut appearance on the long-running BBC Radio 4 quiz, ''[[Just a Minute]]''. In 2017 Godliman starred (alongside [[Stephanie Cole]]) in an episode of ''[[John Finnemore (writer)|John Finnemore]]'s Double Acts'' on [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] and (with [[Marcus Brigstocke]]) in ''The Wilsons Save the World''.\n\nShe also starred as a guest on the [[satirical]] radio show ''[[The Now Show]]'' to reflect on International Women's Day on 10 March 2017 and took part in episodes 3 and 4 of ''I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue'', series 70, that were recorded in Woking. She has appeared on [[The News Quiz]].\n\n==Voice acting==\nGodliman has done voice acting for the BBC Bitesize GCSE section. She has also narrated the [[Blighty (TV channel)|Blighty]] series ''Save Our Boozer''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy==\nKerry has performed as a stand-up comedian throughout her career, including several appearances on ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'', and she tours extensively in this capacity.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kerrygodliman.com Kerry Godliman] Personal website\n*{{IMDb name|id=0996942|name=Kerry Godliman}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Godliman, Kerry}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English women comedians]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:People from Perivale]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Rose Bruford College]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|BLP=yes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Kerry Godliman\n| image       = Kerry Godliman 2011.jpg\n| caption     = Kerry Godliman in 2011\n| birth_name  = Kerry Anna Godliman\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1973|11|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Perivale]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| nationality = British\n| occupation = Actor, comedian\n| years_active = 1998\u2013present\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.kerrygodliman.com/}}\n}}\n'''Kerry Anna Godliman''' (born 17 November 1973 in [[Perivale]], [[London]]) is an [[English people|English]] comedian and actor. She played Hannah in ''[[Derek (TV series)|Derek]]''{{Hair space}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Kerry Godliman interview for Derek |url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/kerry-godliman-interview-for-derek |publisher=channel4.com |accessdate=29 March 2013 |author=Channel 4}}</ref>, Nicky Rawlings in ''[[Bad Move]]'' and Lisa in ''[[After Life (TV series)|After Life]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nGodliman was born in [[Perivale]], London<ref name=\"taskmaster\">{{cite episode|title=Series 7, Episode 3|network=[[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]]|airdate=19 September 2019|series=[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]}}</ref>, and trained at [[Rose Bruford College]], south London.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chortle.co.uk/comics/k/187/kerry_godliman |title=Kerry Godliman, comedian : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide |first= |last= |work=chortle.co.uk |year=2015 |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nGodliman has appeared in ''[[Law of the Playground]]'', ''[[Spoons (TV series)|Spoons]]'', ''[[Extras (TV series)|Extras]]'', ''[[Life's Too Short (TV series)|Life's Too Short]]'', ''[[Rush Hour (UK TV series)|Rush Hour]]'', ''[[Michael McIntyre's Comedy Roadshow]]'', ''[[Miranda (TV series)|Miranda]]'', and ''[[Home Time]]''. She appeared in the final episode of the first series of ''[[Frankie (TV series)|Frankie]]'' as a seriously ill hardworking patient.\n\nGodliman plays Hannah in [[Ricky Gervais]]' Channel 4 sitcom ''[[Derek (TV series)|Derek]]''. She played the mother in ''[[Our Girl]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/9949408/Our-Girl-BBC-One-review.html |title=Our Girl, BBC One, review - Telegraph |first=Sarah |last=Crompton |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group|TMG]] |location=[[London, UK|London]] |issn=0307-1235 |oclc=49632006 |accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> She appeared in the [[Sky 1]] sitcom ''[[Carters Get Rich]]'' as Liz Carter, the mother of Harry, who invents an app and becomes a [[millionaire]]. She guest-starred in an episode of ''Damned'', with [[Jo Brand]] and [[Alan Davies]].\n\nSince 2017, Kerry has portrayed the role of Nicky in the ITV sitcom ''Bad Move'', and in 2018 she played Peggy Aytean in the [[Channel 4]] computer game series ''Rob Beckett's Playing for Time''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rob Beckett's Playing for Time |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt8216630/ |website=IMDB |publisher=IMDB |accessdate=8 July 2018}}</ref> In 2018, Kerry won the seventh series of [[Dave (TV channel)|Dave]]'s comedy-gameshow ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]'', beating [[James Acaster]], [[Jessica Knappett]], [[Phil Wang]], and [[Rhod Gilbert]]. Recently, Godliman starred as Lisa in the [[Netflix]] black comedy series, ''[[After Life (TV series)|After Life]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/television/after-life-cast-ricky-gervais-netflix-new-series/|title=After Life cast: who stars with Ricky Gervais in new Netflix series \u2013 and where else you\u2019ve seen them|last=Sanusi|first=Victoria|work=iNews|date=8 March 2019|accessdate=8 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Kerry guest starred in the eighth episode of the eighth series of ''[[Call the Midwife]]''.\n\nShe portrays Carol on [[USA Network]]'s [[Treadstone]].\n\n==Radio==\nGodliman has appeared on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''At the Fringe''. From the end of April 2013, she also had her own four-part series on Radio 4, ''Kerry's List''. In August 2014, she made her debut appearance on the long-running BBC Radio 4 quiz, ''[[Just a Minute]]''. In 2017 Godliman starred (alongside [[Stephanie Cole]]) in an episode of ''[[John Finnemore (writer)|John Finnemore]]'s Double Acts'' on [[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]] and (with [[Marcus Brigstocke]]) in ''The Wilsons Save the World''.\n\nShe also starred as a guest on the [[satirical]] radio show ''[[The Now Show]]'' to reflect on International Women's Day on 10 March 2017 and took part in episodes 3 and 4 of ''I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue'', series 70, that were recorded in Woking. She has appeared on [[The News Quiz]].\n\n==Voice acting==\nGodliman has done voice acting for the BBC Bitesize GCSE section. She has also narrated the [[Blighty (TV channel)|Blighty]] series ''Save Our Boozer''.\n\n==Stand-up comedy==\nKerry has performed as a stand-up comedian throughout her career, including several appearances on ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'', and she tours extensively in this capacity.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kerrygodliman.com Kerry Godliman] Personal website\n*{{IMDb name|id=0996942|name=Kerry Godliman}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Godliman, Kerry}}\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English stand-up comedians]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English women comedians]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from London]]\n[[Category:People from Perivale]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Rose Bruford College]]\n", "name_user": "Roisterer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision:italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerry_Godliman"}
{"title_page": "Doesn't Really Matter", "text_new": "{{short description|2000 single by Janet Jackson}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Doesn't Really Matter\n| cover      = Janet Jackson - Doesn't Really Matter.png\n| alt        = Jackson is seen hugging Eddie Murphy's character, Sherman Klump, while surrounded by the Klump family. The text above reads JANET JACKSON \u2013 DOESN'T REALLY MATTER\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Janet Jackson]]\n| album      = [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack]] ''and'' [[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2000|5|21|mf=y}}\n| format     = \n*[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch single]]\n*[[CD single]]\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = Flyte Tyme, [[Edina, Minnesota]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n*[[Pop music|Pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n*[[Dance music|dance]]\n<!--Do not add unsourced genres-->\n| length     = 4:18\n| label      = \n*[[Def Jam Recordings|Def Jam]]\n*[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n| writer     = \n*Janet Jackson\n*James Harris III\n*Terry Lewis\n| producer   = \n*[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n*Janet Jackson\n| prev_title = [[Girlfriend/Boyfriend]]\n| prev_year  = 1999\n| next_title = [[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n}}\n\n\"'''Doesn't Really Matter'''\" is a song recorded by American singer [[Janet Jackson]] for the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|soundtrack]] to the 2000 film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'',<ref name=\"KlumpsMTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1428172/20000523/dmx.jhtml|title=LL, Sisqo, Jay-Z, Foxy, DMX, More For \"Klumps\"|website=[[MTV News]]|date=May 23, 2000|access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref> and on her seventh album ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]'' as a slightly modified version. It was released as a [[Single (music)|single]] on May 21, 2000, after an unfinished version leaked to radio. \"Doesn't Really Matter\" is a [[Pop music|pop]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[Dance music|dance]] song that speaks about loving a person for who they are and disregarding their physical appearance. The track is based on an incomplete poem Jackson had written, which was later applied to her character in the film. The song was a contrast from the dark tone of her previous album ''[[The Velvet Rope]]'', returning to a brighter and more contemporary sound.\n\nThe song generally received positive reception, becoming Jackson's ninth number-one single in the United States after peaking on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] for three weeks. It was Jackson's twenty-first single to be certified, placing her as the second female artist with the most certified singles. The single reached number five in the United Kingdom, and peaked within the top-ten in Italy and Denmark, eventually attaining a silver certification in the United Kingdom.\n\nThe [[music video]], directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], resembles an [[abstract art|abstract]], futuristic environment based on Japanese culture. In addition to scenes from the film, it also features futuristic technology, morphing clothes, and a dance sequence on a levitating platform. It had a reported cost of over $2.5 million, causing it to become one of the [[List of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos]] of all time. [[Jenna Dewan]] made one of her earliest appearances in the video, performing as a dancer. She was later personally offered by Jackson to appear in the music video for \"[[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\", and perform as a dancer on the [[All for You Tour]].\n\n==Background and development==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" was written and produced by [[Janet Jackson]], [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]] as the theme for the [[Universal Pictures]] film ''[[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps]]'', starring Jackson and actor [[Eddie Murphy]].<ref name=\"LinerNotes\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=Doesn't Really Matter|others=[[Janet Jackson]]|year=2000|type=booklet|publisher=[[Def Jam Records]]|id=314 562 846-2|location=New York City}}</ref> She portrays Professor Denise Gaines in the film, the love interest of [[The Nutty Professor (character)|Sherman Klump]], who is one of many characters portrayed by Murphy.<ref name=\"KlumpsMTV\"/> When asked to contribute a single for the [[Nutty Professor II: The Klumps (soundtrack)|movie's soundtrack]], Jackson stated that she would consider if she found an appropriate song.<ref name=\"Bronson\">{{cite book|last=Bronson|first=Fred|year=2003|title=Billboard's Hottest Hot 100 Hits|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard Books]]|edition=3|page=902|isbn=0823077381}}</ref> The single would allow Jackson to continue releasing music, while simultaneously devoting time to her film career.<ref>{{cite book|date=July 21\u201323, 2000|title=Action Jackson|work=[[USA Weekend]]|page=6}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|date=November 2000|title=Janet at the Crossroads|work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]|page=181}}</ref> To help inspire Jackson, director [[Peter Segal]] brought a rough cut of the film to Flyte Tyme Studios where the singer was recording her seventh album, ''[[All for You (Janet Jackson album)|All for You]]''. She decided to write an uptempo love song rather than a [[Sentimental ballad|ballad]], inspired by Segal finding her love for Murphy's unattractive character in the film convincing.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/>\n\n{{listen|pos=right|filename=Janet - Doesn't Really Matter.ogg|title=\"Doesn't Really Matter\"|description=The lyrics were initially written by Jackson as a poem, before being implemented into the song. Both choruses written by Jackson and Jam are used as the final two choruses.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/>|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nThe lyrics of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" were based on a poem Jackson found which she previously wrote and disposed of.<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2015/jun/03/janet-jackson-10-of-the-best|title=Janet Jackson: 10 of the best|last=Cragg|first=Michael|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=June 3, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> The poem's lyrics were kept intact, although its structure was altered. Jackson wrote further lyrics for the song during the same night Jam came up with the melody alongside drum programmer Alex Richburg.<ref name=\"Bronson\"/> After an early version of the song was created, Jackson requested Jam and Richburg to add more instrumentation, however Jam decided to record from [[Broadcasting#Recorded and live forms|live to tape]] after Richburg left the studio.<ref name=\"Keyboard\">{{cite magazine|last=Rule|first=Greg|date=November 2000|title=Jimmy Jam: Inside Flyte Tyme studios|magazine=[[Keyboard (magazine)|Keyboard]]|volume=26|issue=11|pages=32-40|issn=07300158}}</ref> Initially conceived as a \"slow melody\", Jam chose to increase its [[tempo]].<ref name=\"Bronson\" />\n\nTwo different choruses were written by Jam and Jackson; Jam wrote \"Nutty, nutty, nutty, my love for you\" while Jackson wrote \"Doesn't really matter\". They decided to use Jackson's chorus, and include Jam's chorus towards the end of the track. Jackson presented three songs to Segal on May 12, 2000, three days prior to his set deadline for the soundtrack. He chose \"Doesn't Really Matter\", believing it was a better fit and a \"summertime record\". A slightly modified version was included on ''All for You'', featuring an alternate introduction and elements from the song's [[Rockwilder]] remix.<ref name=\"Bronson\" />\n\n==Composition==\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" is a [[Pop music|pop]],<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/><ref name=\"MTV\"/> [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]],<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"Farber\">{{cite newspaper|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=18 July 2000|title='Nutty Professor' Music Mixed Bag; Freddie King|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]]|page=43}}</ref> and [[Dance music|dance]] song.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/><ref name=\"BillboardTop100\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/list/9339652/best-songs-of-2000-top-100|title=The 100 Greatest Songs of 2000: Staff Picks|last=Daniel|first=Danica|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=March 23, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Although making using of [[Funk music|funk]] production, common in R&B music at the time of its 2000 release, the track was viewed as an R&B-pop take on [[lounge music]].<ref name=\"Farber\"/> Its upbeat pop sound is akin to Jackson's 1995 single \"[[Runaway (Janet Jackson song)|Runaway]]\", a stark contrast to the sparse R&B of her previous album, ''[[The Velvet Rope]]''.<ref name=\"ChuckBillboard\">{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA31|title=Reviews and Previews|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Taylor|first=Chuck|authorlink=Chuck Taylor (music journalist)|date=July 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Music critic Jim Farber compared the retro-style melody in \"Doesn't Really Matter\" to compositions by [[Burt Bacharach]].<ref name=\"Farber\"/><ref name=\"EWFlashback\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20267962,00.html|title=Now That's What I Call Music! 5|last=Farber|first=Jim|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 17, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The production makes use of sparse, programmed percussion,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Trammell|first=Matthew|date=20 November 2017|title=Current State|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|volume=93|issue=37|page=20|issn=0028792X}}</ref> filled with Latin flourishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/janet-jackson-all-for-you/94|title=Janet Jackson: All for You \u2013 Music Review|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|date=June 13, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of the track was played live to tape, even though it sounded [[Music sequencer|sequenced]]. Jam recalled that only a small portion was sequenced, which was used to double the [[melody]].<ref name=\"Keyboard\"/> The song utilizes both a syncopated drum loop and a [[bassline]], which passes the [[circle of fifths]] to reach the [[Circle of fifths#Modulation and chord progression|V chord]]. The bassline allows space for the [[snare drum]] to be heard on the second and fourth beats, as well as accentuating the snare before the fourth beat is played.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Flavor of the month: Janet's 'Doesn't Really Matter'|magazine=[[Bass Player (magazine)|Bass Player]]|date=November 2000|volume=11|issue=11|page=94|issn=1050785X}}</ref>\n\nThe song begins with a 20-second mid-tempo introduction performed by Jackson in [[breathy voice]],<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> and then shifts to a [[Half-time (music)|half-time]] verse with a [[Stutter edit|stutter-beat]].<ref>{{cite magazine|title=All for You Review|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Sinclair|first=Tom|date=May 4, 2001}}</ref> Jackson performs a [[falsetto]] [[Trill (music)|trill]] on the lyrics \"My love / For you / Is unconditional too\".<ref name=\"EWFlashback\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1226514,00.html|title=Chart Flashback|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Pastorek|first=Whitney|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The chorus has nearly twice the speed of the stop-start verses. A more fluid breakdown features halfway, offsetting the pace and high-energy dynamic of the chorus.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> According to Jackson, the lyrics for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" are about Gaines' love for Klump and refers to \"how it doesn't matter what is on the exterior, but the interior\".<ref name=\"Making\"/> Similarly, they were interpreted by [[Chuck Taylor (music journalist)|Chuck Taylor]] of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as how \"love makes the most difference in life\".<ref name=\"ChuckBillboard\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\nIn his review of the single for [[AllMusic]], [[Promis (musician)|Jose F. Promis]] called it \"impossibly catchy\",<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/doesnt-really-matter-us-cd5-cassette-mw0000101400|title=Doesn't Really Matter [US CD5/Cassette]|work=[[AllMusic]]|last=Promis|first=Jose F.|authorlink=Promis (musician)|date=August 8, 2000|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> while [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] commended the song for maintaining Jackson and her producers' reputations as the \"leading lights of [[Urban contemporary|contemporary urban]] [[Soul music|soul]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/all-for-you-mw0000017729|title=All for You \u2013 Janet Jackson|work=[[AllMusic]]|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|date=April 24, 2001|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[Chuck Eddy]] of ''[[The Village Voice]]'' regarded it as Jackson's best single since 1990's \"[[Black Cat (song)|Black Cat]]\", stating that \"the melody's subliminal Asianness makes the nothingness of her piddly voice pretty\u2014fragile like [[rice paper]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2001/03/13/backstabs-in-the-material-world/|title=Backstabs in the Material World|website=[[The Village Voice]]|last=Eddy|first=Chuck|date=March 13, 2001|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref> Matt Diehl of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' found the track \"effervescent\", and cited it and [[R. Kelly]]'s \"Just a Touch\" as the only two consequential R&B songs on the soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64793,00.html|title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps Soundtrack Review|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Diehl|first=Matt|date=July 10, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Writing for the ''[[New York Daily News]]'', Jim Farber viewed the track as innovative, noting that it \"dodges current clich\u00e9s\" and has \"the yearning freshness of a summer breeze\". According to him, \"The baby's-breath tune and lightly skittish beat provide the perfect accompaniment for Jackson's coo of a voice.\"<ref name=\"Farber\"/> Melissa Marschheuser of the ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]'' wrote that the song has \"a beat you just can't help but hum along to\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2000-08-04/entertainment/0008030478_1_nutty-professor-ii-buddy-love-klump|title=The Nutty Professor II: The Klumps|website=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Marschheuser|first=Melissa|date=August 4, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> while [[CNN]] described it as a \"pleasing single\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0007/23/wbt.00.html|title=CNN Transcript \u2013 WorldBeat: Summer Music Festival Adds Flavor to Diverse Soundscape of Quebec; Ekova Gets Inspiration From All Corners of World \u2013 July 23, 2000|website=[[CNN]]|date=July 23, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Rob Kenner of ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' described it as a \"bright, shiny sound\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fyYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA114|title=Sonic Boom|website=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|last=Kenner|first=Rob|volume=9|number=7|page=114|date=April 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Sean Piccoli of the ''[[Sun-Sentinel]]'' called it a great song with \"a less suffocating shade of pop\" than other tracks on ''All for You''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-05-01/lifestyle/0104300241_1_janet-jackson-album-jackson-family-song|title=Janet Jackson Says Goodbye With A Bite|work=[[Sun-Sentinel]]|last=Piccoli|first=Sean|date=May 1, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In a mixed review of the song, Chuck Taylor described the track as \"frothy\" and \"singsongy\", as well as a \"leftover\" from Jackson's previous singles. However, he commended the track for being \"innocent fun\", stating that it would be able to attract listeners on the [[Mainstream Top 40|mainstream]] and the [[Rhythmic (chart)|rhythmic]] radio stations.<ref name=\"ChuckBillboard\"/>\n\nBill Lamb of [[Dotdash|Liveaboutdotcom]] ranked \"Doesn't Really Matter\" as the ninth best song of the year, describing it as a confident \"midtempo classic\".<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/top100lists/tp/top100songs2000.09.htm|title=Top 100 Best Pop Songs of 2000|website=[[Dotdash|Liveaboutdotcom]]|last=Lamb|first=Bill|year=2009|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Lamb also ranked the song among the top hundred best songs of the decade, indicating that it is \"one of the best examples of how Janet Jackson can make a hit single sound completely effortless\".<ref name=\"Decade\">{{cite web|url=http://top40.about.com/od/top10lists/tp/top1002000s.01.htm|title=100 Best Pop Songs of the 2000s|website=[[Dotdash|Liveaboutdotcom]]|last=Lamb|first=Bill|year=2009|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In a twentieth anniversary list of \"The 100 Greatest Songs of 2000\", ''Billboard'' staff placed the song at number seventy-three, with Danica Daniel acknowledging that it was lovely hearing Jackson \"sing about inner beauty\".<ref name=\"BillboardTop100\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nAn [[Audio mastering|unmastered]] version of \"Doesn't Really Matter\" [[Internet leak|leaked]] ahead of its release date and received airplay from several radio stations who made their own edit from the leak, which pleased producer Jimmy Jam.<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/971570/jimmy-jam-prepping-klumps-soundtrack.jhtml|title=Producer Jimmy Jam Readying 'Klumps' Soundtrack, Janet Jackson Album|work=[[MTV News]]|date=June 3, 2000|access-date=February 2, 2001}}</ref> The song became Jackson's ninth number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on August 26, 2000, selling 96,000 units in its first week.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Pietroluongo|first=Silvio|date=August 26, 2000|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA106&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=101|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> It stayed on top for three consecutive weeks and was replaced by [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s \"[[Music (Madonna song)|Music]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.celebrity9.com/janet-jackson/biography.html |title=Biography of Janet Jackson |work=Celebrity9 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> It made Jackson the first artist to achieve a number one single in the 1980s, 1990s, and 2000s on the Hot 100,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6677541/rewinding-the-charts-15-years-ago-janet-jackson-scored-a-hot-100|title=Rewinding the Charts: 15 Years Ago, Janet Jackson Scored a Hot 100 First|last=Anderson|first=Trevor|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=August 26, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> and became Jackson's nineteenth single to receive a gold certification, and twenty-first single to be certified, ranking her as the second most successful female artist with the most certified singles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|title=RIAA \u2013 Recording Industry Association of America|website=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=February 7, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221215851/https://www.riaa.com/newsitem.php?id=8FE9018F-4FD8-8A99-C464-ED5774E23BF3|archive-date=February 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song was released in the United Kingdom on 7 August 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/janet-jackson-66-1396324|title=Jackson Case Thrown Out|author=NME|website=[[NME]]|date=July 25, 2000|access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> where it attained a silver certification on 20 October.<ref name=\"UKCert\"/> It also received a [[Broadcast Music, Inc.|BMI]] Pop Award for Most Played Song and [[Japan Gold Disc Award]] for Top Selling Song of the Year by a foreign artist.<ref name=\"RIAJ\"/> The song peaked at number one on [[Top 40 Tracks]] and the [[Rhythmic Top 40]], three on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]], number nine on [[Hot Dance Singles Sales]], and number two in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/janet-jackson-mn0000208774|title=Janet Jackson \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography \u2013 AllMusic|website=[[AllMusic]]|author=Huey, Steve|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"can\"/> \"Doesn't Really Matter\" achieved success internationally, reaching number five in the United Kingdom, number two on the [[UK R&B Chart]], the top ten in Italy and Denmark. It peaked within the top fifteen of Norway, Sweden, Belgium, and the Netherlands, and among the top twenty in Switzerland.\n\nUpon its release, it became the most added song on pop, rhythmic, and urban formats, also added to [[Hot Adult Contemporary]].<ref name=\"RandR\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2000/RR-2000-06-23.pdf|title=Janet And Friends|magazine=[[Radio & Records]]|number=1356|page=1|date=June 23, 2000}}</ref> The song was the first number one hit by a female artist on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 since [[Aaliyah]]'s \"[[Try Again (Aaliyah song)|Try Again]]\" several months earlier, breaking the longest streak of male acts at the chart's summit since eight years prior.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZhAEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA106 |title=Oh Dear, What Can The 'Matter' Be? |work=Los Angeles Times |author=Bronson, Fred |date=August 26, 2000 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, ''Billboard'' ranked it the sixty-first most successful song by a female artist in the chart's history.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bronson |first=Fred |year=2007 |title=Billboard's Hottest Hot 100 Hits | work=Billboard Books}}</ref> The song's success allowed the film's soundtrack to open at number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] on the week of July 29, 2000, only behind [[Eminem]]'s ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP]]'', [[Britney Spears]]' ''[[Oops!... I Did It Again (album)|Oops!...I Did It Again]]'', and [[Nelly]]'s ''[[Country Grammar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2000-07-29|title=Billboard 200 \u2013 Week of July 29, 2000|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> The album was later certified platinum on August 24, 2000, with over one million copies sold in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=nutty+professor+2&col=title&ord=asc#search_section|website=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]|title=Gold & Platinum \u2013 RIAA|access-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n===Background===\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=328\n|image1=Akihabara Night.jpg\n|image2=Sony, aibo (cane robot), anni 2000 (ist. biorobotica polo sant'anna valdera).jpg\n|footer=The music video for \"Doesn't Really Matter\" is inspired by several elements from [[Japan]], such as the video's futuristic setting, and the [[AIBO]] that is seen near Jackson.\n}}\n\"Doesn't Really Matter\" was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]], and takes place in a futuristic city resembling [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> The video was filmed during a turbulent period, in which Jackson was experiencing a divorce from unannounced husband [[Rene Elizondo, Jr.]], leading to intense media scrutiny and fluctuations in weight.<ref name=\"Making\"/> It shows Jackson in an [[abstract art|abstract]] [[anime]]-based environment, featuring an [[AIBO]], which was the very first consumer Artificial Intelligence robot and was created for the companionship of adults and elderly people. Morphing clothes, levitating platforms, and a futuristic [[Acura]] vehicle, the [[Acura CL]]-X Concept Prototype, are just a few of the other things featured in this video.<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/> The music video was filmed in [[Los Angeles]] on June 4\u20135, and premiered on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Making the Video]]'' on June 28, 2000.<ref name=\"Making\">{{cite episode|title=Janet Jackson: Doesn't Really Matter|series=[[Making the Video]]|network=[[MTV]]|date=June 28, 2000|season=3|number=2|language=en}}</ref> The video cost over $2.5 million, ranking it among the [[list of most expensive music videos|most expensive music videos]] of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/most-expensive-music-videos/|title=The 5 Artists With the Most Expensive Music Videos of All Time|last=Bather|first=Luke|website=[[Highsnobiety]]|date=June 2, 2015|access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKahn described the video's premise as \"epic minimalism\" in an attempt to differentiate from the large sets of other music videos. He wanted to create the video by using minimal sets, which would look larger in appearance.<ref name=\"Making\" /> Jackson was willing to collaborate with Kahn, stating that she enjoyed taking risks.<ref name=\"Making\" /> The outfits worn in the video was based on [[Japanese street fashion|fashion from Tokyo]].<ref name=\"Making\" /> One of the dancers in the video, [[Jenna Dewan]], got the role at the age of 19 as the only spot the choreographers were looking for.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8456679/jenna-dewan-janet-jackson-dancer-interview|title=Jenna Dewan on the Life-Changing Impact of Working With Janet Jackson: 'Once a Janet Dancer, Always a Janet Dancer'|last=Milzoff|first=Rebecca|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=May 18, 2018|access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref> All the dancers performed choreography on a moving platform as they were harnessed on bungee cords.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> Jackson stated that it \"tilts, slants, you can slide off or fall\".<ref name=\"Making\" /> The original scene was designed on a set, but was taken apart and replaced with a [[green screen]].<ref name=\"Making\"/>\n\n{{multiple image|align=right\n|total_width=328\n|image1=Joseph kahn 01.jpg\n|image2=Jenna Dewan 2012.jpg\n|footer=Kahn studied Jackson's videos before becoming a director, while Dewan credited her appearance on the music video for being able to work with other artists.\n}}\n\nIn a 2014 interview with Video Static, Kahn praised his time working with Janet Jackson, acknowledging her work ethic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videostatic.com/interviews/2014/01/07/videostatic-interview-joseph-kahn |title=Talking Videos, Britney and more with Director Joseph Kahn |work=Video Static |date=July 1, 2014 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In an interview with ''Peel'' in 2000, he explained his experience in shooting the video with Jackson:<ref name=\"Kahn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.njs4ever.net/kahn3.html|title=An Interview With Joseph Kahn \u2013 Page Three|work=Peel|date=July 2000|access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref><blockquote>I was star struck on Janet for sure, because that was the first time that I really dealt with someone that was in my youth. I studied Janet Jackson videos growing up. So to finally see myself face to face with her and working with her and her calling me on a first name basis and calling my home and tracking me down on my cell phone[...] like her leaving messages, it was the weirdest thing[...] And Janet, she really is elegant, she's like royalty. Even though she's talking to you and trying to be normal, she's not \u2013 she's Janet Jackson \u2013 and you can never get that out of your head. You realize that she's a real person and she's got just the same emotions as everyone else, but you can never get around the fact that she's special.</blockquote>\n\nThe music video was one of the first appearances by Dewan, who stated \"I was fortunate enough to work with Janet who treats her dancers amazing,\" describing it as her most memorable video shoot.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/timberlakes-ex-blood-37259.aspx|title=Timberlake's Ex Is Out for Blood|work=[[TV Guide]]|last=Webb|first=Matt|date=February 17, 2006|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> After the shoot wrapped, Dewan was personally offered the role as one of Jackson's tour dancers in the All for You Tour by Jackson herself, dancing for her for two straight years.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/> She credited working with Jackson in the video, as well as \"[[All for You (Janet Jackson song)|All for You]]\" and the All for You Tour, for allowing her to later work with other major artists.<ref name=\"JennaDewan\"/>\n\n===Reception===\nThe video's premise, portraying Jackson as she \"romps around with some girlfriends in a futuristic setting\" and \"getting freaky in Tokyo\", was praised for its variation from standard \"lip-synch/film snippet formula\" used among pop videos at the time. It was also \"happily free\" of scenes from its accompanying film, saying the clip \"stands on its own\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdmg.com/klumpsuncensored.shtml |title=Nutty Professor II: The Klumps \u2013 Uncensored Director's Cut (2000) |work=DVD Movie Guide |author=Jacobson, Colin|year=2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[DVD Talk]] likened the video's setting to [[science fiction film]] ''[[The Fifth Element]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/1275/nutty-professor-2-the-klumps/|title=Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps : DVD Talk Review of the DVD Video |work=[[DVD Talk]]|last=Beierle|first=Aaron|date=November 11, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> The video's popularity saw the AIBO ERS-210 robotic dog generate increased market demand and commercial success, after the \"bionic beast got to snuggle up to Janet Jackson\" in the clip.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2001/01/03/business/let-aibo-tell-you-about-brand-image/ |title=Let Aibo tell you about brand image \u2013 The Japan Times |work=Japan Times |author=Gilhooly, Rob|year=2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Sun Sentinel]]'' included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" among several videos which set fashion trends and increased the popularity of \"must-have colors\" in clothing among youth. The vibrant \"red and orange\" outfits worn by Jackson, including \"sugary pinks and orange tees\", items from the ''Self Esteem'' line, and \"designer duds right off the runway,\" were described to heighten demand for similar \"bright colorful clothes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2000-08-08/lifestyle/0008070457_1_colors-young-women-video|title=What Are The Coolest Kids Wearing This Fall? Fiery Reds And Blazing Oranges Because They Are . . .|work=[[The Sun Sentinel]]|last=Hagwood|first=Rod Stafford|date=August 8, 2000|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Matthew Trammell of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' noted that the music video's influence of consumer technology consequentially led to the popularity of [[Siri]] and [[Amazon Alexa|Alexa]] in pop culture.<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/11/20/janet-jacksons-doesnt-really-matter-music-video-saw-the-future?verso=true|title=Janet Jackson's \"Doesn't Really Matter\" Music Video Saw The Future|last=Trammell|first=Matthew|website=[[The New Yorker]]|date=November 10, 2017|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> He also stated that the 2020 re-production of the AIBO model in Japan meant that the world is \"closer to the bulbous, pastel metropolis conjured by Janet Jackson in one of the most forward-leaning music videos of its time\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/>\n\n==Live performances==\nJackson performed \"Doesn't Really Matter\" on ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' on August 4, 2000,<ref>{{cite episode|series=[[Top of the Pops]]|network=[[BBC One]]|series-number=37|number=32|date=August 4, 2000|language=en}}</ref> and the [[2000 MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Awards]] on September 7, 2000.<ref name=\"VMAs\"/> Jackson opened the show in a black leather outfit in an aerial set among multiple backing dancers. Her long hair was obscuring her face for much of the performance.<ref name=\"VMAs\">{{cite web|last=Basham|first=David|url=http://www.sonicnet.com:80/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|title=VMA Report #2: Janet Jackson Kicks Off Night's Performances|publisher=Sonicnet|accessdate=December 27, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20001209075800/http://www.sonicnet.com/artists/ai_singlestory.jhtml?id=1123893&ai_id=1090|archivedate=December 9, 2000|url-status=live}}</ref> ''The Orlando Sentinel'' stated Jackson made \"a rare TV performance\" featuring a \"three-tiered set and ten backing dancers\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Style Beats Substance Among Artists At Video Music Awards|work=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|last=Abott|first=Jim|date=September 8, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001 and 2002, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was included on the [[All for You Tour]] as the encore.<ref name=\"RollingStone\"/> For the performance, she wore demure white tee and jeans. ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' considered the rendition \"jubilant and \"spirited\", while MTV News called it \"a fully [[Motion picture rating system|PG]] Janet\".<ref name=\"RollingStone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/ms-janet-jackson-gets-nasty-20010710|title=Ms. Janet Jackson Gets Nasty|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=July 10, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.mtv.com/news/article.rbml?id=1445013 |title=MTV Mobile News: Janet Jackson Live: Tears, Bondage And Tupac|work=[[MTV News]]|last=Greenblatt|first=Leah|date=July 9, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221203150/http://m.mtv.com/news/article.rbml?id=1445013|archivedate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> A writer for ''New York Daily News'' said Jackson performed a \"stripped-down \"Doesn't Really Matter\" with no choreography or dance troupe to hide behind.\" The tour's performance was also praised for allowing Jackson to appear \"looser\", which effectively \"cut the self-consciousness and relaxed into more natural moves\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2001-10-26/entertainment/0110240916_1_jackson-s-new-music-janet-jackson-tours/2 |title=Just Call Her The Diva Next Door \u2013 Page 2 \u2013 Sun Sentinel |work=Sun Sentinel |date=October 26, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/janet-find-article-1.932368#ixzz2tCK2UlPc|title=Janet's All For You, If You Can Find Her|work=[[New York Daily News]]|last=Farber|first=Jim|date=August 21, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Jam! Canoe]]'' considered the tour's performance \"upbeat and warm\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/J/Jackson_Janet/ConcertReviews/2004/09/25/pf-643658.html |title=CANOE -- JAM! - Air Canada Centre, Toronto \u2013 August 2, 2001 |author=Stevenson, Jane |work=Canoe Jam! |date=August 3, 2001 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nFor her first concert tour in six years, \"Doesn't Really Matter\" was included on the 2008 [[Rock Witchu Tour]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/janet-jackson-opens-rock-witchu-tour-with-three-decades-of-hits-video-duets-and-pyro-20080911 |title=Janet Jackson Opens Rock Witchu Tour With Three Decades of Hits |date=September 11, 2008 |accessdate=September 9, 2014|last=Sheppard|first=Denise |work=Rolling Stone}}</ref> During the [[Number Ones, Up Close and Personal]] world tour, she wore black jeans and a tank top to perform the song. ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the performance saying \"it's the closest she gets to representing life as lived rather than as performed\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/21/arts/music/janet-jacksons-number-ones-at-radio-city-review.html?_r=1& |title=Janet Jackson's 'Number Ones' at Radio City \u2013 Review \u2013 NYTimes.com |work=New York Times |author=Ratliff, Ben |date=March 20, 2011 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Jackson dedicated the song to the audience while performing in [[Santa Barbara, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepowerplayermag.com/Archive/PPMApril11/Thepowerplayermag/Events.html |title=Events|work=PowerPlayerLifestyle|date=April 8, 2011|access-date=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807062326/http://www.thepowerplayermag.com/Archive/PPMApril11/Thepowerplayermag/Events.html |archivedate=August 7, 2011}}</ref> The song's music video was played on screens preceding the opening number for selected dates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ocregister.com/soundcheck/ocregister-481692-http-soundcheck.html |title=Janet Jackson in top form heading into L.A. gigs|work=Orange County Register |date=April 11, 2011 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Jackson included the song on her second leg of the 2018 [[State of the World Tour]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|title=Janet Jackson turns Syracuse into dance party with a message (review, photos)|url=https://www.syracuse.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2018/07/janet_jackson_syracuse_concert_review.html|date=August 10, 2018|publisher=Scene|access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> as well as on her 2019 Las Vegas residency, [[Janet Jackson: Metamorphosis]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Mitchell|first=Gail|title=Janet Jackson Draws Queen Latifah, Eve & More to ''Metamorphosis'' Residency Opening in Las Vegas |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8512088/janet-jackson-metamorphosis-las-vegas-residency-opening-review|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|date=May 20, 2019|access-date=January 22, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Covers and usage in popular culture==\nJapanese singer [[Hitomi Shimatani]] covered the song under the title \"Papillon\", which sold over 200,000 copies, and made her become one of the top artists on the [[Avex Trax]] label.<ref name=\"Avex\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpopasia.com/celebrity/hitomishimatani/ |title=Hitomi Shimatani's bio \u2013 singer \u2013 jpop |work=JPopAsia|year=2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Shimatani was presented the idea to cover the song due to its success, saying \"the song had a big impact\" and was \"played repeatedly.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jame-world.com/us/articles-3517-an-interview-with-shimatani-hitomi.html |title=An interview with Shimatani Hitomi \u2013 JaMe U.S.A. |work=JaME World |date=December 12, 2007 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> [[N\u00e9stor Torres]] recorded a jazz version of the song for his seventh album ''This Side of Paradise''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.courant.com/2002-08-26/news/0208260048_1_nestor-torres-latin-grammy-band |title=A Romantic, Energetic Evening From Nestor Torres |work=The Courant |date=August 26, 2002 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Glenn Gamboa of ''[[Newsweek]]'' considered [[Rihanna]]'s \"[[Watch n' Learn]]\", from her sixth studio album ''[[Talk that Talk]]'', an \"answer to Janet Jackson's \"Doesn't Really Matter\" due to its similar production and \"playful\" nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/music/rihanna-s-talk-is-another-winner-1.3332047|title=Rihanna's 'Talk' is another winner|website=[[Newsweek]]|last=Gamoba|first=Glenn|date=November 18, 2011|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> Geoff Mayfield of ''Billboard'' likened [[Destiny's Child]] to being influenced by Jackson's strategy of releasing a soundtrack single shortly before an album campaign with \"Doesn't Really Matter\" for \"[[Independent Women]]\", stating that the group \"began planting the seeds for the upcoming release\" in a similar vein.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FikEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA146|title=Between the Bullets|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Mayfield|first=Geoff|date=August 12, 2001|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe song was used in the international arcade releases of the ''[[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNova]]'' series and ''[[Dance Dance Revolution X]]''.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNova]]|developer=[[Konami]]|publisher=[[Konami]]|date=2006|platform=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]}}</ref> In 2012, [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] political strategist [[Richard Socarides]] selected \"Doesn't Really Matter\" for a live playlist on CNN.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://startingpoint.blogs.cnn.com/2012/08/01/starting-point-playlist-for-wednesday-august-1-2012/ |title=Starting Point playlist for Wednesday, August 1, 2012 \u2013 Starting Point |work=Starting Point |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=August 1, 2012 |accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref> In September 2013, [[record producer]] and [[radio personality]] [[Mister Cee]] included \"Doesn't Really Matter\" blended with [[Maino]]'s \"[[Hi Hater]]\" during a live set upon his return to famed [[New York City|New York]] radio station [[WQHT|Hot 97]] following several solicitation allegations, saying \"Just listen to the words.\" The inclusion of Jackson's song was considered to subliminally reveal his bisexuality, called the set's \"most triumphant moment\", and a response to critics in opposition of his sexual orientation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/09/mister-cee-hot-97-resign-first-mix/ |title=Embattled DJ Mister Cee Returns to Hot 97 With Hour-Long 'Can I Live' Subtweet \u2013 Spin \u2013 Newswire |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |date=September 12, 2013 |access-date=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n'''Australian CD single {{small|(562915-2)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=162597 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter Australia 5\" CD SINGLE (162597)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><br>\n'''Japanese CD single {{small|(UICD-5001)}}'''<ref>[http://eil.com/shop/moreinfo.asp?catalogid=162609 Janet Jackson Doesn't Really Matter Japan 5\" CD SINGLE (162609)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><br>\n'''Taiwanese CD single {{small